animal.description:
**SPECIAL NEEDS - EXTREMELY SHY **

Male Border Collie Mix: 50 lbs

Born around May 2016 and arrived at TVR April 23, 2019

Kids: 16 and over Dogs:  Yes, REQUIRED   Cats: Unknown

Linus is a very special boy who will need a patient, quiet, and loving home to help him come out of his shell and gain confidence. In his first couple of years this bashful boy was not often exposed to every day life situations, if at all and perhaps he was even a stray at some point. 

Since arriving at TVR, he has become more confident and secure in his surroundings. He genuinely loves to play with the other dogs and feels much safer in their presence and with a pack. He is becoming more comfortable when interacting with people but it still takes a long time for him warm up to new people. In spite of his fears, he does know how to walk on leash and seems to be reasonably house-trained although accidents can occur during any new and/or stressful situation.

Linus belongs in a home with at least one other dog who is super friendly and confident to take the lead and show him the way. He will benefit from an outgoing counterpart that will help him find his courage. His human can help soothe Linus by brushing him (he loves it) and filling his dog bed with cozy blankets before tucking him into bed. 

We are not 100% sure what incident occurred to make the world an intimidating place for Linus, but we know in our hearts that with the right person by his side and the security of a home he will learn to feel safe and at ease. He will finally be able to take a breath and live a happy peaceful life which he deserves. 

Are you ready to give this sweet, gentle and shy boy the home he has been waiting so patiently for?

*HEARTWORM UPDATE: Linus has completed his heart worm treatment and is ready to go to his new home! It is very important for Linus to be kept on a monthly Heartworm preventative (such as Heartgard Plus) and not miss a dose. Linus will need to be taken to the adopters primary vet in 9 months (approximately June 10th, 2021) to be retested for Heartworm Disease.

Linus is available for adoption through Their Voice Rescue (www.theirvoicerescue.org). If you are interested in Linus, please contact them by email (adopt@theirvoicerescue.org) or by phone (540) 497-3562.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Cheerio and Im a 1 year old Pittie mix with a tall order. Im a very special boy looking for a very specific home. I know, I know that people arent lining up out the door to meet a Black furred Pittie, with a very crooked smile like myself but I promise Im a sweet, lovable guy with lots of potential in me. 

I really like other dogs and would really like to have another one in my forever home. I have some behavioral issues and separation anxiety. Because of my past, I have a hard time trusting new people right away. You see, when I was a pup, humans werent very nice to me. One even broke my jaw before they dumped me off at the vet to euthanize me. Thats where the nice people at ARAR stepped in and saved me and when I met my foster mom. My foster mom says Ive come such a long way from the broken puppy I once was but when I look in the mirror, I look just as handsome to me! I do have a crooked grin, because of the way my jaw healed but that just means i stand out from the rest of the dogs around, and yes, I did win best smile at puppy school. Because of my anxiety, I am on medication that I will need for the rest of my life. Along with visits to see my favorite doctor, the behaviorist, every 6 months, but its okay, i really like her, she gives me lots of treats and cookies and tells me what a good boy i am! I would require a dog savvy, and patient pet parent, who can financially afford to take me to these appointments. Someone who would like to learn and grow with me, after all who doesnt love growth on all levels?? My foster mom says that Meets and intros would be very slow because it takes a while for me to trust strangers. I cant live with kids or be around them-they scare me. Im also not a fan of big crowds. I guess you could say Im in introverted guy, so maybe an introverted person would be my perfect pair. I am crate and potty trained. I love my crate and use it for comfort and when left alone. I know just about every trick under the sun and love to learn new things! I am a higher energy, 65 lb boy that loves to play with squeaky toys and balls. I love to go swimming and am very good at it. Im a good walker for the most part. After a fun day with adventures and play time there is nothing I love more than snuggling up with my bonded people and relaxing, And I make the most perfect little spoon. 

Ive been waiting for my perfect person to come along and rescue me for quite some time now. Lots of foster friends have come and gone, while I patiently wait for my turn. Think we could be MFEO? (Made for each other ) then contact the rescue today!

animal.description:
Hope came from a hoarding situation when over 80 animals were surrendered to a shelter. The surrender of so many put all occupants of that shelter in jeopardy and the staff worked feverishly to get rescue for all of the new intakes.

Although all dogs were so frightened after being torn from the only home they'ed know for much of their lives, not one dog showed any aggression......just fear.

Our Ms. Hope was one of the better, but will still require a special family who can help her get beyond the fear she now feels. Patience and love are the order. She is so sweet and so wanting to know the love of a human it will tear your heart out to see her be so scared that she tries to hide....and, yet when you have a break through and she trusts you, you will feel elated and wishing for more. She's been with a trainer for some decompression time while being in a home environment with him. She's in a TLC program with a great foster family now and is doing very well.  

Recently our trainer had her over for a few days boarding when her foster family went away and he said: "Placing Hope is like placing a special needs dog. She is special needs. And her behavior will need to be managed for an undetermined period of time. What we know, factually, is that she doesn't have an aggressive bone in her body. She eats well. She crates well. She is crate trained. She is fine with other dogs and cats. And she's been in two home environments. She progressed steadily here. And she progressed steadily with foster. So wherever she goes they need to understand she needs time. And they need handling instructions. But Hope is so low maintenance. She's like a cat really. Feed her, water her, take her to the bathroom... And she's fine. The relationship part with a new person and new environment will take time."

We will require that an adopter have another dog, as Hope is very dependent on her confidence from another canine.  We will also require that an adopter have a fenced in yard.  No apartment or condo living would work for her.  She is NOT a dog that will take rides and enjoy dog parks or hikes or trips...she will not want to leave her safe environment and an adopter has to be satisfied with the progress made on her own "turf".  

Hope is around 40lbs, she has been brought current on all vaccines, spayed, microchipped and made ready to begin her second chance at a life where she knows human love and caring.

You will simply be AMAZED when you follow her story on Facebook.  Updates, photos, videos and all posted to give you a full indication of what our Hope is all about.  She's a beautiful dog with incredible spirit....and is so very brave!

CHECK HER OUT ON FACEBOOK:
https://www.facebook.com/adoptmehope/

animal.special_needs_notes:
HOPE CAME FROM A HOARDING SITUATION where over 30 dogs were confiscated and taken to a kill shelter.  She will need a patient, loving home!

Long ago Hope stole our hearts and her story is told on her Facebook page at:
https://www.facebook.com/adoptmehope/?modal=admin_todo_tour

Take the time to follow that journey. Scroll down to the beginning.  There you will find the video of her when first taken to our trainer.   Hope was sent for their rehab/enrichment program.  Her total lack of socialization and her "over the top" fear in that initial video with our trainer will tear your heart apart!

Once Hope completed time with our trainer she went to a foster home.  This foster family had helped another dog that we rescued from the same hoarding surrender and was experienced in helping dogs like Hope progress.  

It has been a very slow process but we are SO VERY PROUD of Hope and are inspired by her.  I cannot even begin to imagine what it has taken for her to get as far as she has.  She is INCREDIBLY BRAVE but still has a long way to go.  ARE YOU THE PERSON WHO CAN HELP HER in continuing that journey to go beyond her fears?

Do you have any other dogs?  Hope is very dependent on having another dog to help her.  She is NOT going to be a dog that you will be taking for walks and rides....she has come a long long way but has lots further to go and we feel that her family MUST have a canine companion.  She is great with other dogs and with cats to!

If you have ever known a feral dog, the lack of socializing done with dogs that are in hoarding situations is the best way to describe where Hope has come from.

If you are not experienced in handling dogs who have come from this situation or are feral and if you do not have another dog to help give her direction and confidence, Hope is not the dog for you and your family.

She is special needs in the sense that she will needs lots of patience and direction and continued encouragement.  But, the rewards of every little bit of progress will melt your heart......and, her devotion will be never-ending!

animal.description:

She is 38 lbs and about 3 yrs old and looks like a pit hound mix.  She loves going for car rides and loves her foster mom.  A recent major storm that destroyed buildings has spooked her.  She is heartworm positive and started her heartworm treatment. Not only does she need a fabulous forever home, she needs a home to decompress while going through her treatment.  

Lily is up to date on her vaccinations and is spayed. I can't stress how much love pours from Her wonderful heart.  Her adoption fee is $175

animal.description:
Follow us on Facebook for updated photos and more information on our adoptable pets!
Hi, I'm Mario! I'm between 1 and 2 years old with a lot of puppy energy and a teenager attitude. My favorite pass time activities include squirrel watching, chasing squirrels, going on walks to hunt squirrels and dreaming about squirrels. I'm told I'm very smart and learn new things quickly. While I seem perfect on the outside I've got a few issues I've been working on and could use some continued help with. I'm kind of awkward and goofy at times, but aren't we all? I love kids, especially the ones who like to play with me! I like to make friends with most other dogs, but I'm still learning what the appropriate way to meet them is. Cats.. why don't they want to play with me? I love a good routine, so if you think you are up for it I think we could be best friends!

From the foster parents: 
Mario is a very sweet boy and smart too! He's a lab mix, but don't let the photos fool you; he is smaller than he looks weighing in around 45-50lbs. He's surprisingly very soft to pet and tends to shed a lot, but he doesn't mind being brushed. Mario was found wondering the streets in the city and taken in as a stray. When his previous owners never claimed him, Lucky Paws jumped in and rescued him. He's crate trained, potty trained and knows basic commands like sit, shake, down and a few others. 

Mario is a submissive dog with his humans and doesn't like getting yelled at when being naughty. He tends to act out when he doesn't get enough attention according to his standards, however he doesn't act out when you stick to a good routine. He likes to talk (bark) a lot more than some people enjoy; especially if there's a squirrel, dog or mail man around. He needs a home with a fenced in yard, because he will run off if not on a leash or in a fenced in area. He loves kids, but would do best in a home with older kids who will not let him run out the front door when you're not looking. He has some anxiety issues and is a bit high strung. We've been working on teaching him to trust and turn to his humans to tell him when things aren't dangerous. 

He gets along with most dogs, but not all. He does better meeting other dogs when he's not being restrained by a short leash. Smaller dogs seem to bother him less than the bigger ones. He likes cats and wants to play with them even though they want nothing to do with him. 

He's socially awkward at times and struggles with meeting and walking past other dogs. He really really dislikes older (senior) people. We have tried to figure this one out, but he is very nervous and uneasy around them. Mario is a fear reactive dog and tends to turn to "fight or flight" reactions. Some of his behaviors suggest that he was never properly taught how to socialize with other dogs and humans. We have worked very hard and have come a long way with teaching him to listen better, not to bark at other humans and dogs and to not pull while on the leash. His new family will need to continue training him with consistency. 

Mario is up-to-date on all vaccines and is microchipped. His adoption fee is $400 plus WI state tax!

Please go to www.luckypawsmidwest.org fill out and application and once approved we will set up a meet and greet!

animal.description:
DAMON
Damon is an adorable young pup with an estimated date of birth of July 15th, 2019. Damon is happy and healthy but nervous of new things. Brother to Jason, both from a remote northern community.
Damon is a timid pup and takes time to warm up to new situations & people, he is slowly learning that the world is not a scary place. He is good with dogs and cats although he does like to chase the cats. He is also house trained and crate trained. We would prefer Damon to go to a home with another female dog or no dog at all.
From his foster:
"He knows sit, down, touch, leave it and come. He’s good with our cat and listens to corrections from him. He is a giant puppy and likes to play rough and gets a little mouthy when he’s really excited. He is house trained and kennel trained but is good at night sleeping without his kennel. He doesn’t really like car rides and will drool everywhere! Damon loves to chase birds. He loves spending time outside and playing fetch, he is getting used to all the noises and isn’t as scared of anything new anymore, he even goes up to the fence when there’s people walking by or the neighbours are outside!"

Damon is now available for adoption. Please email our adoptions coordinator - adoptmasr@gmail.com

animal.description:
With her unique markings and happy attitude, Arielle turns heads wherever she goes! This gorgeous girl has won over volunteers with her sweet demeanor and readiness for whatever activities the day brings. She has a nice flexible energy, which often expresses itself as a burst of happy excitement and then settles into a nice, calm rhythm. Whether it’s a day spent playing in the yard or snuggling up on the dog bed, Arielle is ready—just make sure there’s time somewhere for a peanut butter kong! She'll be happy to busy herself with her bone or toys while you get some things done.


Arielle recently completed six weeks of training at the Lancaster State Prison with our friends at Paws For Life. There, she worked on her leash skills and polished her manners. Her trainers said she put a smile on their faces when they needed it most, and that she's a loving and affectionate dog. She's ready to take her new skills and bring them to your home!

Check out more from Arielle on her Instagram at @arielletheacpittie (https://www.instagram.com/arielletheacpittie/)

About 4 years old and 70 pounds, Arielle is crate-trained, house-trained, micro-chipped, up to date on routine vaccinations and working on her basic commands.

animal.description:
THIS IS A COURTESY POSTING BY THE FOSTER MOM:

Daisy is one of the smartest dogs I have ever met.  She learns quickly and at times seems to out think the people she is with.  She chases balls, does a few tricks, but really shines at figuring out puzzles and tasks on her own.  She can leap really high, and every year is fascinated by the barn swallows that nest in the eves around the house.  She doesn’t want to hurt them, but she does like to watch.

She is very food motivated and will try to steal other dogs’ meals if you don’t watch her.  She also requires a sturdy fenced-in yard to keep her safe since she is part hound and could wander if left loose.  Daisy will also climb a chain link fence, so she needs a secure fence, such as a privacy fence or another type which is climb-proof.

Daisy is about 6 years of age, spayed, fully vaccinated, and heart worm negative.  She weighs about 60 lbs and gets along well with other dogs.  She is cat aggressive, so her forever home must be without cats.  She is also likely to chase dogs smaller than herself.  She loves people and kids and will play all day if you let her.

A home visit is a must.

Please contact Sue Sweeney at 770.583.3297 or at fairviewfarm@earthlink.net if you are interested in meeting Daisy.

animal.description: Chiquitin! His name means tiny tot in Spanish. We're guessing he was the cutest little puppy ever but he is definitely more of a Big Tot these days! When Chiquitin arrived at the shelter, he was pretty shut down. This is normal, and heartbreaking, for many owner-surrendered pups. They have no idea what they did wrong, why they are in this loud place, where their family is, and are they ever coming back for them. This is where the power of AAC's shy dog volunteers come in! They worked with Chiquitin daily, and little by little, he started to come out of his big fluffy shell. Now Chiquitin does the cutest dance when he sees his friends! He is the master of zoomies, and he loves to play with other pups. His roommates keep getting adopted and we're hoping that Chiquitin's turn is next! Large black dogs are the most overlooked dog in the shelter system. We think it's crazy, too! You can follow Chiquitin on instagram: its_chiquitin To contact his foster, email kristin.skilling@gmail.com

animal.description:
*Do not message PetFinder.  Contact the rescue directly by email at furgetmenotrescue@gmail.com    PetFinder messages can not be answered.

*Meetings are scheduled after a no obligation adoption application is completed online at furgetmenotrescue.org   To learn more about our adoption process please visit http://www.furgetmenotrescue.org/commonly-asked-questions.html

Meet Dozer!  Dozer is a 3 year old male Olde English Bulldog.  The Olde English bulldog has a sweet, gentle disposition. Dependable and predictable, the bulldog is a wonderful family pet and loving to most children. People-oriented as a breed, they actively solicit human attention. We would love to find a family experienced with the English Bulldog breed for Dozer.  

Dozer is a lovable goofy boy.  We are requesting children older than 10 in the family due to his "bull dozing" capability.  He's just unaware of his size and could possibly knock small children down.  Dozer would love a fenced in yard of his own.  Dozer is very energetic but when exercised properly, enjoys lounging on the couch watching a good movie and snuggling.  He loves to be with his people and would benefit from being the only pet in the home so he can soak up all the attention himself.  Dozer is a happy go lucky kinda guy.  Everyone falls in love with him when they meet him. 

Dozer's adoption fee is $300.00 which includes his neuter, current on all vaccines including Rabies, de-wormed, tested heart worm Negative and current on heart worm prevention and current on flea/tick prevention.    


If you meet the requirements-physically fenced yard, home owner, no young children, English/Olde English Bulldog experience and/or not a first time dog owner, and are able to deal with vetting and possible health issues and separation anxiety, then please submit an application at: http://www.furgetmenotrescue.org/adoption-application.html If you do not meet the requirements necessary to fulfill Dozer's needs and safety for all, do not inquire, as no exceptions will be made and you will not be answered. We are serious about what we do and advocate for responsible adoptions, proper research and preparedness, and a safe environment for all involved. We are making positive futures for our rescues and their adoptive families and will not put them in a situation in which they will not thrive. 

If you're interested in adoption, but Dozer may not be a fit for your home, things happen quickly and change all the time in the rescue world. We can keep your application on file. We also network with several rescues and maybe we can work together to help you find the right fit for your home.


You can email his foster mom with questions at twelve.paws3@gmail.com

animal.description:
Jonas has only one wish this holiday season - he is hoping for a furever home where he can be a good companion to the right person who is a patient and experienced owner. Jonas has a long, soft, fluffy coat and is a smart boy who knows his basic cues, though he would love it if his furever family would dedicate time to add more skills into his toolbox so he can show off how exceptional he can be. Just like many of our pyr rescues, Jonas can be a tad wary when encountering strangers, but if you are patient and give him the time and space he needs, he will warm up to you in no time. Once he determines that you are trustworthy, he transforms into a loving companion where he may claim your lap as his own :) Jonas will thrive in a less active home without children and in a relatively quiet neighborhood, where his people have the time and patience to continue his training. This big boy has all the 'pawtential' to become your most loyal companion, will you open your heart to him?

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/rescue-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can call 877-739-3582 or email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description: Say hello to Stumpy! This good girl was rescued and is ready for a forever home! Stumpy is one of the sweetest dogs that you will ever meet. Stumpy is nine years old and has lots more love to give. She is both house and potty trained, but hasn't gotten used to her crate yet. Stumpy is a very loving dog, but she gets scared when she is around men. Stumpy loves barbeques and will smile when she is content. She doesn't like being alone and prefers to hangout inside the house. Stumpy needs loving, but is very happy to give it back. She has an amazing personality that will make a great addition to your family. Stumpy is ready to be a part of your forever home. This pet is available for pre-adoption and may not be officially ready for adoption, as it is still undergoing medical treatment. Depending on the medical status, a Meet and Greet may be put on hold until they can safely participate in a meeting with potential adopters. In some cases, this pet may be able to move to its forever home while it is still under the medical care of Dallas Pets Alive. If you are interested in learning more, apply now and one of our Adoption Counselors will discuss the options available so you can bring home your new furry family member! Applications are processed in the order in which they are received; please be aware that this pet may have interested applicants ahead of you. All Dallas Pets Alive adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon adoption. The standard minimum donation for dogs over six months to seven years is $200, puppies under six months is $250, dogs eight years and over are $100 unless specified otherwise. You can view all adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallaspetsalive.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/ . For more information, you can email adopt@dallaspetsalive.org.

animal.description:
MEET CHESHIRE!! **Please Note: This is a courtesy post for another rescue; different adoption fees/policy apply.

Cheshire is a 6 year old mix, who once comfortable, is the most loving, sweet, goofy, fun dog. He had no issues as a puppy, but when he was about 2 years old he decided that he wasn't a fan of other dogs and became a little fearful of people he didn't know. That's okay though because this boy has so much love to give that you'll want to give all your love to him and him alone!

Cheshire was diagnosed with hypothyroidism when he was 4, and it was explained that his changes in behavior likely resulted from this. The medication he needs is pretty inexpensive and an easy condition to treat.

He loves to hike, but is not a fan of the car. He loves to fetch, but it can be shortlived as he gets a little distracted. Haha He is a huge cuddlebug, and always wants to be as close to you as possible (he doesn't understand personal space). Cheshire is completely house-trained, and knows commands like sit, down, stay, wait, and come, although his recall could use some work because he gets distracted. He's crate-trained, although sometimes he does struggle with separation anxiety when he is not with his favorite person.

Meeting new people is scary, and generally takes more than one visit before he's comfortable enough to let people love him as much as he really wants to love them, but given some time he does come around. Because he is scared of new people, he can come across unfriendly and will take another meeting to get used to you. But once he trusts you, however, he will trust you forever. He has never bitten anyone or anything like that-- he is just scared and needs a patient hand to guide him and make him feel safe. He's definitely a lover when you offer him patience and allow him to move at his own pace.

Cheshire is a handsome and sweet boy who just needs someone dedicated to making him feel secure. An experienced owner who knows how to lead would be a great fit and he would look up to you and bond nicely before long. Cheshire has a great heart and would be such an amazing companion with the right person. If that's you, please inquire because this one is a hidden gem!

For more information or to meet this pet, please complete an application or send email to info@underdogaz.com

If you're reading this via a pet-search site, please view this pet's page

at www.UnderdogAZ.com/animals

for more photos and details.

Puppet is a medium energy dog who likes to play and has bursts of energy, but he's also comfortable just chilling with you. Puppet has lived with a young child before. Puppet needs to be the only animal in the house, and would prefer living in a neighborhood on the quieter side. Some awesome things about Puppet: - He's fully potty trained and is working on being crate trained. - A big cuddle bug (he's just a really fun dog to cuddle. He particularly likes napping with his people and butt scratches). - Knows several commands and is VERY food motivated during training. - Super comfortable being handled (having his feet/legs touched, getting bathed, etc.) He let his fosters give eye drops and clean his eyes following a surgery with no issues whatsoever, even on the first day he met them. - Likes napping with you and being close to you, but also will go off on his own for parts of the day. - Loves car rides and is generally pretty well behaved in the car. - Hasn't reacted to the door bell or the vacuum in his foster home. - Very nice and well-behaved with veterinary staff. - Polite at human meal times (doesn't beg excessively even though he really loves food). Puppet is just an all-around nice boy. He has a really fun and happy personality, is energetic, and has a lot of love to give to his future forever home.

animal.description:
Please note, RAGOM's adoption territory includes Minnesota, Iowa, North and South Dakota, and western Wisconsin within 75 miles of the MN border.   At this time, we do not adopt out of our territory.  

Did you go, "Gasp, that face is sooo cuuute!" when you saw Korey's photos? Yes, he really is as adorable as pictured!

What the photos don't show is the tough time he's had in his young life. Korey was found in the streets of China, beaten and left to perish. A local rescue nursed him back to relative health and contacted RAGOM. With the collaborative efforts of a village of volunteers, donors, and medical personnel, Korey arrived in Minnesota in January of 2020.

His abusive past notwithstanding, Korey is the most astonishingly bright-hearted pup ever! He's so happy, exuberant, and oh-so loving that everyone who meets him marvels at his resilience and can't help but shower him with affection.

The only remnant of the trauma he's suffered is his paralysis, which has barely slowed him down. He moves around the house easily by using his front legs and has a wheelchair for outdoor adventures. 

Sweet Korey is looking for a very special family who can manage his incontinence. Prior experience isn't required - we'll teach you. Fortunately, he is obedient so diaper-changing and cleaning will be easy once you learn the techniques.

If you have what it takes to provide for Korey's needs, he'll reward you with his perennial cuteness and undying devotion, and you get the bragging rights of being the forever family of an amazing survivor!  We ask that you read through Korey's page carefully and evaluate whether your home environment and lifestyle match his requirements before submitting an Inquiry for Application form on our website.

To learn more about Korey, see his bio at: https://ragom.org/dogs/korey-19-257c

(3/8) Return after 2 months - aggression to people.Dog Meets:Big Ben and Peanut: https://youtu.be/ka9LRcHy7F0Big Ben and Lexx: https://youtu.be/UwbyYI0Cx2sVideos:Big Ben is a gentle boy: https://youtu.be/FcWPITn7pEUBig Ben taking treats so gently: https://youtu.be/CHbPXh5y8IYBig Ben getting some R&R: https://youtu.be/hmJngaWGqvABig Ben meeting a new friend: https://youtu.be/PHSTzg7fPC8Day Trip Photos: https://photos.app.goo.gl/RYrY43eukdezXtrp7Photos: https://flic.kr/s/aHsmMpmsatWeight: 70.40 lbsMedical Observation: Neutered and Microchipped.(4/7) Vet Check -- Dog was in a fight two days ago. Sustained puncture wound above left eye that was crusted over with mild discharge when removed scab, no other puncture wounds found but did have some dried blood crusted to fur around eye. Both eyes have scleral hemorrhage but left more than right and left eye also had some mucoid yellow-green ocular discharge and mild conjunctivitis. Not blepharospastic, no overt swelling.(3/24) Vet Check -- Ambulatory x4, but grade 1/4 lemaness left forelimb. No pain or discomfort elicited with orthopedic exam, good ROM all joints. Walks with left elbow slightly abducted from body. Still active, walking and trotting, pulling at leash. Would benefit from full orthopedic work-up and may need chronic NSAID therapy which is beyond shelter's capacity for treatment.(3/19) Vet Check - Senior dog with possible arthritis(3/16) PE: Slightly Cloudy Slightly Dirty Ears Tartar on Teeth Pressure on Legs(3/15) NRO(12/8) Vet Check - Patient had to be muzzled by kennel attendant and low growling throughout time on exam room when started assessment even if not performing anything hands on. Scrotum is very mildly enlarged but soft, incision site healing well with no active discharge. Mild scrotal hematoma that already appears to be resolving on own. Digit 2 left front foot filed down and quick opened up while walking and actively bleeding(12/6) Dog presented in kennel with diarrhea. Tx: drontal and a monitor sheet(12/1) Initial Exam- dirty coat, long nails, dirty ears waxy earsBehavior Observation: (4/15) Easily leashed, walks with mild pulling, in the yard he sniffed the perimeter with a loose body. He approached the handler and solicits interaction with a soft body and open mouth. He is not interested in toys. Takes treats with a soft mouth, knows sit and stay.(3/8) Per adoptive owner - protective, quiet, fights with other dogs, walks well on leash, aggressive - bites, snaps at animals, no interactions with young kids, used to be fine around the 16-year-old kid who worked with the owner. Then the other day he bit the kid on the arm. Only shown aggression to people one time. However he does not like it if people lean over top of him - he feels threatened. He is mostly dog aggressive but bit with no warning recently. Very smart dog, trains easily.(12/8) Vet Staff - Patient had to be muzzled by kennel attendant and low growling throughout time on exam room when started assessment even if not performing anything hands on.(11/30) Per finder- "so so", calm as far as finder could tell, barked at other dogs while on a walk, pulled when walking but gets tired* * * * *Bite Details* * * * *Have you noticed any unusual behavior prior to bite: no, dog was playing with the victimWhat were the events leading up to this bite incident: 16 year old was playing with the dog at the owner's shop. They were done playing, and 16 year old walked away. Big Ben came up to him as he wanted to keep playing. He leaned over top of Big Ben, and the dog suddenly bit onto his left arm, clamped down and did not let go. Did you think the animal might bite before the incident happened: no, he's never bit someone before and was really good with him before, so they didn't think he would biteDescribe another time this animal bitten or scratched: he previously bit another dog, as he is very dog aggressive, but he has never bitten a person other than this recent incident. Two past times, he reacted aggressively when people leaned over the dog's head - he seems very threatened by this. Neither of those incidents resulted in an actual bite.

Silly Tori! Tori's favorite things to do are snuggling with her people and being outside just watching everything. She may not make a great Livestock Guardian Dog but she definitely has the tendencies. Tori enjoys watching over her home and property.

She has come a long way since she was found dumped on a country road, skinny and neglected. She's a little timid, but she has been coming out of her shell in her foster home and she loves her people. She's been showing us how funny and affectionate she can be.

Tori has a malformation in one of her front legs; we've had it checked by several vets and so far, they have recommended against amputation. Tori gets around great--she loves to chase squirrels and do zoomies! This sweet girl will make a wonderful, loyal, loving pet.

animal.description:
Brennan is about 55lbs Australian Kelpie mix and around 2-3 years old.
If you LOVE cattle dogs and their energy, Brennan is the one for you! He's medium sized and full of energy, very food motivated, loves to play fetch, chew on his bones and RUN! We stress the play and run because he’s a little busy boy, great companion on leash, loves to explore. If you’re looking for an adventurous and active dog, this is your man! 
Good with other dogs, but extremely playful so he would do best in a home with another active or very tolerant pup.  
Brennan also does know how to relax though. He’s a great cuddle buddy and makes the funniest little groans when he's being loved on.
He's neutered, house trained, and up to date on all of his vaccines and prevention. He is heartworm positive, but has received treatment.

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our dogs are healthy, spayed/neutered, vaccinated and on heartworm preventative. They live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. Many have basic obedience skills and all have been temperament tested. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, please visit our website to complete an application: http://www.takepawsrescue.org/adoption-form
(please note: app cannot be done on a mobile device)

If you have any questions, please email us at adopt@takepawsrescue.org

I may be a middle aged girl but I've got the energy of a pup to go along with my wisdom. I love the outdoors and belly rubs and love having human friends around to hang out with.I pull at my harness when we walk but it's only because I love being out in this beautiful world of ours! A little tug on the leash will remind me to slow down and walk with you.I looove to run! I'm very fast but I know you're slower than me so I'll run at whatever pace you choose. I even run in my sleep. Did I mention I hold the record for fastest mile ever? ...at ACCT Philly that is.I get very excited when I see other dogs. Pets and reassurance that we're safe keep me calm until the other dog passes.I love humans of all shapes and sizes. Big or small we get along great. I always want to be in the room with you, unless maybe there's something exciting outside the window.I like to cuddle and I love a good belly rub. Don't worry, I make it easy for you to reach and am happy to lean into you to make you feel loved too. I also use pillows like humans do so you're going to have to share.I'm very patient and very gentle. I'll wear silly things for photos, I take treats nicely, if my nails are too long I'll let you cut them, and I'll even let you pick me up and carry me around if that's really what you want to do.I'm not at all food aggressive. I once found a tasty chicken bone on the Philly streets but my foster dad caught me in the act. He told me no so I let him open my mouth to take it out. I think I earned an extra treat later for being so nice about it. I think he wanted it for himself.I'm learning lots of new tricks at my foster home. I'm a pro at sit, come, and paw. I know wait for walks when we need to stop at a corner and look to get my attention. I know what stay means but it's just so hard to stay when there are treats to be had! I'm working on it. Can't give it all up at once.Intake Type: 3/4 - Return adoption; 1/17- Return adoption after 3 weeks - Aggression to animals; 12/17- Return adoption after 3 days - Aggression to animals; Owner Surrender 11/20 - HomelessnessWeight: 65.20 lbs++Bite Details++ The adopter and Diamond were on a run. Diamond saw another dog and the adopter held Diamond between her legs. She states she's taken Diamond out on runs before, and Diamond hasn't reacted like this. When the other dog owner was trying to pass Diamond disregarded the fact that adopter was trying to hold her back and dragged adopter which lead to her scraping her back. Diamond jumped on the other dog and an officer ran up on the scene and maced Diamond in the face to get the dogs off of each other. While the dogs were tangled together and both owners were trying to separate the dogs, the other owner got bit by his own dog and Diamond's adopter got bit on the right thumb by Diamond. Diamond did not continue the attack on the adopter; it was a quick redirection bite.This animal is currently available through ACCT Philly's Adoptions Programs. animal.description:
Please click "MORE ABOUT US" at the right and read about our adoption process before contacting B.O.N.E.S.



4 year old male
**Needs a Physically Fenced Yard**
Good with dogs
Unsure about cats
Good with kids of all ages

Hi, I'm Chief, do you want to play? I like to have fun, and you know I'm happy because my tail never stops wagging!

I have lots of toys to play with. My foster mom picks up all the toys and puts them in a bucket. Now it's time to take all the toys from the bucket and spread them all around! Yay, this is such a blast! My brother (Jimmy) and I like to do this together. It's awesome to have my brother with me... we really enjoy each other's company. As a matter of fact, we not only play together, but also sleep together and get belly rubs together. It's double the fun!

I bet you didn't know that I'm already both house trained and crate trained. I also know the commands "sit," down," and "come." My humans are very pleased with my knowledge. They also enjoy the fact that I walk very nicely on my leash. However, I prefer to walk around in the yard instead of on the street. I get really scared when cars go by. If I see one of those frightening cars, I just roll over and refuse to get up. I get pretty jumpy when the wind blows things around, too. I'm learning to accept the windy weather and overcome any fear pretty quickly. However, I will need a lot more support to get over my fear of cars.

Speaking of cars, I am not a huge fan of riding in them either. I just get so anxious. Oh, no. Now I am so embarrassed... I left a little piddle behind. So sorry... I just got nervous.

When nighttime comes, Jimmy and I snuggle in bed with our foster family. It's so nice to cuddle and feel safe. Do a pair of lovable beagles sound like the perfect addition to your family? Please consider adopting me along with Jimmy and we promise you will never have a shortage of beagle love.



------

B.O.N.E.S. is a foster-home-based rescue organization serving dogs and potential adopters in the New England states. We do not have a shelter. Please visit our home page at www.bonesbeagles.org for information about our adoption process.

animal.description:
Please click "MORE ABOUT US" at the right and read about our adoption process before contacting B.O.N.E.S.



4 year old male
**Needs a Physically Fenced Yard**
Good with dogs
Unsure about cats
Good with kids of all ages

Hello, I'm Jimmy, who are you? Do you like to play with toys? I have lots of toys to play with. My foster mom picks up all the toys and puts them in a bucket. Now it's time to take all the toys from the bucket and spread them all around! Yay, this is such a blast!

My brother (Chief) and I like to do this together. It's awesome to have my brother with me...we really enjoy each other's company. As a matter of fact, we not only play together, but also sleep together and get belly rubs together. It's double the fun!

I overheard my foster mom say that I am very puppy-like. Okay, so maybe I am not a little pup anymore, but I am certainly very young at heart. I am making very good progress on my house training, and I am already crate trained. Sometimes I do things that my foster mom doesn't want me to do, so she tells me "no." Hmmm, not sure what that means. Oh, well.

I do have a tendency to be a little nosy. If my foster siblings are playing, I will go over to see what they are up to. Even things that scare me at first eventually pique my curiosity. I jump when I hear a loud noise, but shortly thereafter I'm investigating the sound. I am a beagle who needs to know things.

I like to go for walks, and I walk very nicely on my leash. Of course, running around with Chief is also great fun!

When nighttime comes, Chief and I snuggle in bed with our foster family. It is so nice to cuddle and feel safe. Do a pair of lovable beagles sound like the perfect addition to your family? Please consider adopting me along with Chief, and we promise you will never have a shortage of beagle love.



------

B.O.N.E.S. is a foster-home-based rescue organization serving dogs and potential adopters in the New England states. We do not have a shelter. Please visit our home page at www.bonesbeagles.org for information about our adoption process.

Geppetto is crate trained and would need to be crated when no one is home. His curiosity when left alone sometimes gets the best of him.

Geppetto is located in Arizona and is adoptable in Arizona only.

animal.description:
Lucky here! I was hit by a car and left for dead on the side of the road. A nice lady found and took me to the closest vet where they contemplated euthanasia. You see, my spine was fractured leaving me paralyzed from the waist down. 

Thankfully, this rescue gave me a second chance. I am happy to be alive and am perfectly capable of living a good quality life. I just need to find a family who is perfectly cable of caring for my special needs :)

I am guessed to be a 5-year-old Treeing Walker Coonhound. I love the company of other dogs and walking in my cart! I also enjoy getting pet by everyone I meet. If you don’t come to me, I’m rolling my way to you. 

My bladder needs expressed every 6 hours, and I cannot control my bowels. If you cannot deal with diapers, pee, and poopy messes, I will not be a good fit for you.

I had bilateral leg amputation surgery to remove my back legs since they were dead weight. More recent pics are me without legs :)

animal.description:
This super sweet 6 year old girl is hoping that you'll look past her many scars, her worn teeth, and her saggy boobies, and see her for who she really is- a loving, affectionate, friendly dog that is so deserving of a good life. We'll never know what happened to Ellie in the past, but it couldn't have been a happy life that she lived. That's all behind her now and Ellie doesn't hold anything against anyone. Ellie needs a pet-free home, but she sure loves people. She is an absolute angel. A strong and active angel, yes, but so well-behaved and sweet. Ellie sits and lays down when she's asked and she's very gentle with taking treats and toys. Ellie would just love a home where she can plop on the couch with you at night and lay her head in your lap, and be loved by a good family forever. File#29441 1/17/20 Call 609-693-1900 or email: office@ahsppz.org for an appointment to meet Ellie.

If interested please visit our Forked River Shelter. We are open Mon. - Fri. from 12:00 P. M. - 6:00 P. M.; and Sat. & Sun. 12:00 P. M. - 5:00 P. M. for directions call 609-693-1900. There is an adoption donation required. The society cannot accept personal checks but we do accept Visa, MC, AE, Discover and cash. As part of our adoption process, we must have proof of residency. Homeowners must show proof of ownership; landlord approval is required for renters before an adoption can be approved.And as always we thank you for your kindness in opening your heart & home to a Society orphan.

animal.description:
Click my picture for more info. on me!
Bailee is a super cute ball of fun! Bailee is a compact little pitbull mix who is about one and a half years old. She is full grown at about 35 pounds. She loves to snuggle and play.

Bailee loves to play with other dogs and really needs a home with another young dog who can play with her all day! She really benefits from structure and she needs to taught that by another dog in the home too. Currently she shares a foster home with three other dogs and she would love a forever home like that too. However, she can be a bit of a bully to older dogs who don't stand up to her. She's young and sometimes doesn't realize that she is not in charge.

She also is in a foster home with cats and loves to play with the household kitten. The older cats are not as thrilled about her energy level though, so we think that a family with dog savvy cats would be best. We also think that she would do well with older kids. She is a little too rambunctious for toddlers. Bailee is about 95% housebroken- sometimes she gets excited and slips up. She has amazing recall and learns new things quickly! We do not think that she needs a fenced in yard, but she does need a hone who will keep her active. She competed in a lure coursing event and won her class- she is a fast little girl and loves to run and play fast!

Estimated DOB: 12/16/2018

Adoption fee: $250

animal.description:
Angus is about 2 yrs old and came to us earlier this year from the Laredo shelter. This sweet boy was just returned after only a few days and is heartbroken to be back in a shelter environment. Angus suffers with some separation anxiety, but is improving greatly with his meds and our fabulous trainer which will continue to support his new foster or adopter! Angus would do best as the only pet in the home, he just adores his people so much he prefers not to share. This handsome boy has waited long enough to find his special someone! He has so much love to give and deserves to be doted on, snuggled and played with. 


To apply to foster or adopt this medium sized boy, visit CaneRossoRescue.org. Any donations towards his medical care are also truly appreciated.

Thanks for considering a Cane Rosso Rescue dog! 
We place dogs mostly in Texas but have adopted out a few out-of-state as well.
 
If you are interested in one of our dogs, please first complete our adoption application.
You can find it at http://www.canerossorescue.com/application/ . His adoption fee is $300. Our dogs are spayed or neutered,
microchipped, vaccinated and heartworm tested and treated (if tested positive) before 
going to a new home. For more information, visit our website www.canerossorescue.com
or email us at rescue@canerosso.com.

animal.description: Princess is an interesting looking four to six year-old shepherd mix. She has quite an underbite which gives her a very unique smile. She was transferred to us from another shelter where she was scheduled to be euthanized for space. She is currently heartworm positive. She might be an older gal, but she definitely feels large and in charge. She likes to be the boss in canine relationships. She has been kenneled successfully with other dogs, but it has to be the right fit; she's not a fan of anyone who likes to talk back to her or tell her what to do. She was easy to handle during physical exam although when she first arrived she was a bit on the nervous side. She has settled in nicely. She walks pretty well on a leash and is attentive. She was well mannered during physical exam. We think that with her age and slight behavioral quirks, she would probably do best in a home with children 10 years of age and older and with an owner who is willing to help her adjust to her new life. We think a quiet home would suit her best. She is able to climb fences, so her new family would need to be prepared to handle that situation. Dogs are generally tested with dogs of their own size; and dog meets with the resident dogs are always encouraged. Our cat test should be used as a general purpose screening only to rule out overt aggression; we always recommend caution when introducing dogs to cats in the home. Recommendation on suitability of placement with children by their ages is based on behavioral observations including energy level and response to body handling. We never recommend leaving young children unsupervised with dogs, and we cannot guarantee the behavior of dogs with children, other pets or cats. Behavior evaluations should be considered as a snapshot of the behavior of the dog at this point in time; SCPR believes all dog families need to be prepared to invest time and energy into training as well as provide common sense management of their new dog. We always encourage family to do some research on the breeds or mixes of breeds prior to adoption as many can have some unique characteristics that may or may not fit into their families. For more information about this dog or any others at our Shelter, please visit www.doitforthedogs.com. We are the Second Chance Pet Rescue in Grove, OK. 918-786-7630. You can email us at doitorthepets@gmail.com

animal.description:
Crystal Symphony is a beautiful female estimated between 2 and 3 years of age. She was found as a stray and has an unknown background. Her conformation and personality speak to a possible English Shepherd pedigree but that is a question we will never really know the answer to.

Crystal is a lovely girl who enjoys herding people and dogs in the yard, romping in the house, and getting attention when it pleases her. She can be reserved with new people and seems to be more weary in new situations. She may take a few minutes - plus a walk with treats - to warm up but once she does she is a very affectionate and sweet girl. Crystal is best described as 'gamey' which is to say she sees nearly everything as a fun game and is always looking for something to get into. Given socialization and confidence she would make an amazing advanced obedience or dog sport prospect. Crystal can easily jump a 4 ft fence and happily does so to switch play groups at her foster home. She is an athletic and energetic girl who will need either leash walked or a solid fence to ensure her safety. Crystal has not been around children at this time.

Crystal is around other dogs in her foster home and does very well. She has a bossy personality and likes to try to round up the other dogs but they tolerate her well. She has a few that she enjoys roughhousing with and overall seems to have a good understanding of dog social manners. Crystal is well mannered and quiet when meeting new dogs while out on walks. Crystal has met some GSD puppies around 10 lbs and thought they were strange little playmates but ultimately did great with them. She has had one cat brief interaction with a cat that went well but would need further cat testing before going into a new home with cats.

Crystal is an active and adventurous young Shepherd who is looking for a family that will help her learn to trust the world and show her all the fun sides of life. If you're the home for Crystal Symphony please email Tierhavenrescue@gmail.com for an adoption application or visit our website, Tierhaven.rescuegroups.org to view our adoption process and fee.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Lilly is quite the special lady at Safe Haven - starting with her arrival in November as she flew in from a pound in Indiana on the volunteer 'Pilots-n-Paws' flight program! She won over the hearts of all that cared for her in Indiana, as well as all of us at Safe Haven! Because Lilly had a serious infection in her uterus (Pyometra) and the malnourished state she was in - her condition was critical! We were happy we had room and wonderful volunteers devoted to take Lilly in and slowly turn this sweet pup's life around! Lilly doesn't seem to appreciate any of the dogs in the shelter, and we feel she may likely do best in a home with no other pets. She is a 100% lover and cuddlebug - never met a couch she didn't like to cuddle on! :) She also does a fantastic job at keeping her kennel clean, so she appears to be housebroken. We also have decided Lilly must have a little 'Hound' mix in her because she loves to howl in her kennel, and sniffing around on her walk is also a favorite past time. It has been fun watching her blossom into the great dog she is, and guess what type of mix she is! When Lilly first arrived she had multiple health concerns, including being severely underweight. She hardly had any hair on her body, and her skin was very red and inflammed in several areas. We are happy to report that she has steadily gained weight (almost 20 pounds) and is looking much better. Lilly's bloodwork also revealed that she has a thyroid condition (hypothyroidism) which was definitely contributing to her poor overall health and lack of hair. After starting multiple medications (for thyroid, fungal infection, medicated shampoo, and possible skin allergies) she definitely looks so much better, and she will likely need to continue on at least the thyroid medication for her entire life. Lilly does not do well with cats at all, and is very selective about her dog friends - so she will be happiest as an only pet, and with a family that understands she would not do well at dog parks, trails, or other places where other dogs may be visiting too. After a couple months of steady improvements when Lilly first arrived to Safe Haven, she still seemed to have a few lingering issues with her coat and skin. At times the skin on her feet, belly and face turn red, and she has even broke out in hives a few times - so on 3/11/2020 Lilly went to an appointment with a specialty vet (Dermatologist) at Eastern Iowa Vet Specialty Center in Cedar Rapids. The vet is making some adjustments with Lilly's medication to try and help determine if she may have any environmental or food allergies. Depending on Lilly's response, we may need to do actual allergy testing. We hope to have some answers in a month. We are determined to help Lilly feel and look even better. We feel Lilly is stable enough for us to start looking for Lilly's FOREVER HOME and hope that her family will love her as deeply as we do!*Update June 2020 - Lilly is doing great on her current medication. She does have one prescription medication for her thyroid condition which requires her to take daily thyroid medication. This condition is likely to be a lifelong condition for Lilly, so her forever family will need to be willing to monitor this condition and ensure she has her thyroid levels tested annually and receives her medication. If needed, Safe Haven may be able to financially help with these expenses - as our goal is to help Lilly find a family to love her uncoditionally! She does still have occasional and temporary flare ups of red skin on her feet and sometimes belly and face - but that has gotten much better over the past couple months. Lilly receives regularly scheduled medicated baths that seems to help, and she also eats a sensitive skin food. *Update 11/1/20 - Lilly just never seemed to completely overcome her flare-ups of red, itchy skin - so the Dermatologist Vet started an allergy food trial this summer to see if this would improve her skin/coat condition - but after a couple months with no improvements, Lilly did have environmental allergy testing done in October which revealed she does have many different allergies to the world around her......including to different grasses, wildflowers, dust and dust mites, spiders, and corn - just to name a few. While these results with so many allergies were disappointing, they did not really come as any suprise and at least we now know exactly what is causing Lilly the most issues. She is now taking daily immunotherapy medication, which is a serum made up of small doses of the things she is allergic to, so that should help her build up a tolerance to these allergies over time. This immunotherapy process does take up to 12 months to really see it helping Lilly - but we are committed to seeing her through this process, and Safe Haven will continue to pay for this treatment over the next 12 to 18 months, because if the right family comes along we certainly don't want this treatment to deter her adoption! :) Interested in adopting this pet? Please click the adoption info link for more information. And then click on the 'Online Application' link at the bottom of that page.

Adoption Info

animal.description:
Maddie is a beautiful three-year-old, 52 lb. pitbull /terrier mix ready to finally find her happily furever after home ! Help her put a smile back on her face...she has a gentle soul and sadly had a difficult start to her life as she was used as a backyard breeding dog. She arrived to the shelter in pretty rough shape. Her eyes tell a story of neglect and she desperately wants to find love and a safe place to call home. Her ears are chewed up and we believe it's from the male dogs trying to dominate her. 

Maddie is a timid and shy pup but will warm up for attention and love, never having had that before. She loves to cuddle on the couch with you and watches tv too. She is afraid of every noise and sound  outside and will take extra time to decompress. As you pet her, her tail slowly begins to wag and she begins to trust you. She is the sweetest girl and wants to know you won't abandon her after spending five months in the shelter.

Maddie is very affectionate and has beautiful eyes. She just needs someone who will take it slow and help her feel safe. She will make a wonderful addition to a quiet and relaxed adult-only home. She is dog friendly and has made friends with a little shepherd pup. She needs another dog in the home to help build her confidence. Maddie loves to roam the yard and lay in the sun. She does fine on a a leash and likes her walks. A fenced yard is a must. Adopters that are NOT gone long hours are highly preferred.

Maddie  is currently being fostered in North Carolina as she finishes her heartworm treatment. Maddie will arrive up to date on vaccines, microchipped, and spayed. If you are interested in adopting this sweet and sensitive girl, please email   Laura@RoadHomeRescue.com

**No apartments or college students. We also do a trial foster-to-adopt period as we want everyone to be happy.

PLEASE call the shelter directly during business hours for more information (see number below) and confirm that this animal is still available and healthy enough to be seen..  DO NOT USE the e-mail attached to this account.

PUDDIN is an adult male American Bulldog mix.  He is black with white markings.   His weight is not noted, but he is clearly a mid to large size dog. Staff really likes him! His pictures make him look serious and severe. He is anything but that once he is allowed out of his kennel. Unfortunately, that has not been able to happen very often during the time that he has been at the shelter. He acts like a child in a candy store and he wants to run and play and he has the biggest smile on his face that you could ever imagine.  When staff takes him out of his kennel and puts him on a leash, he is pretty much adorable! He has not yet been neutered by whoever previously owned him.  So, that still needs to be done.  Please read the important information below for more details.  He is doing really well with the staff, but does need a firm responsible adult who actually knows how to manage this dog. Staff can fill you in on the details concerning what they are looking for in a potential adopter. 

Adoption fees are $80 for dogs.  Cat adoption fees are $50. Cash or check only. Please be sure to take the exact amount with you.

The shelter routinely vaccinates all healthy appearing animals upon their arrival at the shelter and deworms them.  Any animals not already spayed/neutered must have the procedure done through the veterinary clinic that contracts with the county before that animal can be released from the clinic to the new family. By state law, animals old enough to be given a rabies vaccine, must have that vaccine done, as well.  The vaccine is given by the veterinary clinic staff at a separate cost to the adoptive family. 

Hold periods for every incoming animal vary for several reasons including, but not limited to, whether the animal came in from the Cumberland County area, or from the City of Crossville, which contracts with the county for its animal shelter services.  Check with the staff to verify the availability date of every animal for which you have an interest.

For more information on this pet, call the shelter at (931)484-8525. The shelter is open Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Friday, and Saturday from 10am to 2pm. Closed Wednesday and Sunday and county observed holidays.

Dogs his size and people are high on his favorites list! He loves walks and does great on a leash. He really enjoyed having his foster mom home all the time. Bernie was rescued by an amazing foster after she found herself as a stray at the local shelter. She has completed heartworm treatment and treatment for her skin infection; Bernie has never let this little bump in the road stop her from enjoying her newfound freedom. 

Bernie is an active girl who loves to go on walks and play with any toy in sight! When it is time to relax for the day, you can find Bernie cuddled up next to her humans begging for belly rubs, or chewing on a bone. She will thank you with a big smile and unwavering loyalty!

She takes weekly outings in public, rides great in a car, and is doing great socializing and working on a leash.

While she is highly allergic to cats and cannot be in a home with them, she loves kids and humans! She does not currently play with other dogs in a group or pack setting. She would need to be temperament tested with any other animals because she is a typical bulky breed and enjoys playing gregariously.

DO NOT SEND INFORMATION REQUESTS THROUGH PETFINDER, WE DO NOT HAVE ANY ADDITIONAL INFORMATION ON COURTESY LISTING DOGS. CONTACT INFORMATION FOR THE CURRENT OWNERS IS INCLUDED IN THE BIO BELOW.

ARCBCR courtesy lists dogs for individual owners, other rescues, and shelters wishing to place their Border Collies or Border Collie-mixes themselves.
 
These dogs are not in the ARCBCR program.

ARCBCR does not warranty any of the information provided about the following dogs. Should any issues arise, ARCBCR will not be held responsible. Fees requested and policies may differ from ARCBCR.

Guppy is a super sweet, kind, and loving little girl. Gets along with everyone, loves to play and chew on treat-stuffed toys. She’s learning to bring back her toy for fetch, too. She is crate trained and house-trained, walks great on a leash (with some minor pulling only when excited), and is doing well with basic commands.

She loves to play with toys in the house, wrestle with her buddies, tug-of-war, or cuddle on the couch. Her favorite things include: chasing or being chased, anything edible, sitting on various furniture, and posing like a seal for attention.

Guppy is a silly goofball but is independent and adventurous. She’s a good guard dog and will bark at intruders, but absolutely loves most people and all dogs. She's still somewhat puppy-like but has some good manners and some training now. She has become friends with our kittens, but only under supervision. She gets excited when they are rambunctious so we cannot say she’s 100% “safe” around cats quite yet.

Her strong hound nature makes her fairly serious about 'hunting' bugs, birds, squirrels and small animals outside. She also will eat things she finds like bugs, plants, etc., so she requires supervision outside and a securely fenced yard. Invisible or electric fences would not be appropriate for her level of drive.

She has moderate energy, and could run/play for hours outside, or hang out inside when it's raining just as easily. She would be great with someone that likes to walk or hike and/or has some time to spend training or playing with her daily. She would probably be amazing at Scent-Work (nose work), or Barn Hunt competition.

Guppy loves kids, but tends to jump on them out of excitement, and may scratch or push little ones over. We don’t have a lot of small children around to habituate her to, so that’s where she is right now with kids.

She requires a person with at least a fair grasp of dog training who can be her consistent leader, otherwise she loses her manners. She would not be suitable as an off-leash dog (maybe only after extensive training), nor being left outside for long periods as she will try hard to get out and go 'hunting' on her own.

Guppy has a problematic habit of picking up and eating things that she can find - bugs, hairballs, leaves, toy stuffing, small cat toys, plastic pieces, etc., so she must be watched and/or strictly kept from random things getting into her mouth, or she could be in for serious health problems. She’s good with the “drop it” command, but the drive to eat anything she can find is strong and if you’re not paying attention, it’ll be gone in a flash.

For these reasons, we think an experienced dog owner would be required for this wonderful, silly little girl. Someone with experience with Border Collies and/or hounds is ideal, with a securely fenced yard, and at least a minimum interest in dog training.

She is up to date on her shots, is spayed, healthy with no known conditions, and is around 2 years old.

In order to become Guppy's new family, an adoption application, vet references, and a home visit will be a requirement, in addition to the adoption fee of $300 (which will be donated to one of the great rescue organizations we’re working with).

Guppy is in the Salisbury NC area. If she seems like the perfect edition to your family, please contact: Robin at conservebalance@gmail.com

animal.description:
Doll is 4 years old and 30-35 lbs. She has been here since she was a little puppy. She and her sister were found on a nearby hilltop, having likely never seen people before. They have never gotten over this early lack of socialization. However, Doll is not aggressive. And she loves other dogs. Her best pal is Julio.
She hides from people she doesn't know. But there is a volunteer who has spent time with her and given her treats, and Doll always does a happy dance when the volunteer comes. She even lets herself be petted a little. It's possible she would open up in a patient home where she would see her people more often and would get one on one attention. It would help if her future home had other dogs, because she seems to learn from their example.
*What people who adopt such unsocialized dogs need to consider is that the yard and house must be secure- it would be hard to get her back if she were to escape the yard or run out the front door. That is often the first instinct of very shy dogs in new homes. They need a little time to adjust to the new routine. They should improve once they see how their new home is much better than the shelter environment, and once they associate their new owners with the people who give them food and other good things.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

animal.description:
Max Lucas comes from San Diego - he was a stray and spent a few months in the Humane Society in Oceanside. While there he had the advantages of some special behavior modification therapy - which proved successful. He is 7 years old and 30 lbs. His eyes are hazel.
He is treat motivated - and this is a good way to distract or re-direct his attention. He likes to walk and will cooperate with you putting his loose lead on.
Go slow and don't surprise him - he does guard his food. So feed separately from other dog/s and watch picking food up or moving it while near him. Use a stick - distract him - toss a toy or treat in other direction.
He is well worth the investment to help him relax and trust people. Lovingly named after the two humane society volunteers who we worked with to get him.

animal.description:
Rock Star is a beagle mix, 3 and a half years old and about 40 lbs. He is two tone---brown/white-- and an active boy. Before he came to us, he had several homes that didn't work out. In one, he chased the cat. We can tell you how to introduce a cat and dog who are not famliar with one another.
In the other two, there were nipping issues (no skin breakage) when new owners tried to restrain him by the collar. It is entirely possibly he gave a warning that he did not want to be pulled by his collar and it was ignored. And with a new dog we always recommend leash work. We would not want to be pulled by a collar, or the collar of our shirt - and if that were done and we gave warnings that were ignored, we might then punch the 'puller' or do the same back.
You gotta listen and pay attention to your dog - educate yourself on dog signals, behavior+++ The better informed you are, better teacher and respectful, the better your dog will be. He will do well in a home like this; He is eager to learn. One of our dog walkers has worked with him, and he loves to go out on the leash.
NOW FOR THE GOOD NEWS: On his SAFER test assessment, he scored all 1's (A's) except a 2 on tag item (may be a little sensitive to high energy). He was described as jumpy social, active, sweet, bubbly. Enjoys going on walks. Needs manners training.
At this point he needs a patient, training savvy person or adult home. We'll keep you updated as anything changes. In the meanwhile, basically look at other dogs on our site if you are not up to meet his needs.

animal.description: Hi, my name is JINGLE and I would love to meet you. I am a Spayed Female Pit Bull Terrier and Chow Chow. The shelter staff think I am about 2 years and 9 months old. I have been at the shelter since Oct 28, 2020. ***********THIS DOG IS NOT AT THE SHELTER*************** Jingle spent the past month in a wonderful foster home where we learned so many things about her silly and funny personality! Jingle is a cuddly clown in the house. She loves to play with her toys, chew on her bones, and snuggle with her people. She enjoys some good zoomies in the yard but that`s pretty much enough for her to settle down in the couch with her peeps. Her foster mom reports that Jingle does fine sleeping in her crate but would MUCH rather spoon in bed with someone! This sweet girl came to the shelter as a stray, so her history before foster is unknown. Jingle enjoys going for walks and runs but she tends to be very excitable and vocal when seeing other animals. Her foster home was working on this behavior and she is slowly coming along but will need the help of a qualified trainer with her new family. But it is easy enough to find places where there are no other dogs for walks or she is pretty content to run and play in a fenced yard. Jingle would love a home with a big fenced yard where she can run and play as much as she wants. Jingle is looking for a home with Teens or Adults who would be comfortable interacting with a bouncy dog. At this point she does need to be the ONLY PET in the home. Due to Jingle needing her own space from other dogs, apartment living is not appropriate. This girl wants her own backyard to run and hangout with her family. Jingle is ready and willing to jump right into some private training with a qualified trainer who can help her work on her leash reactivity. If you think Jingle could be the ONE for you PLEASE EMAIL: DOGFOSTER@THEHUMANESOCIETY.ORG

animal.description: Handsome Tucker! Tucker is extremely smart and knows all his obedience commands. He loves to learn and be rewarded so continued training in a home can be made a fun and happy time. He's rides well in a car and is always excited when it's his turn for a car ride. Once the initial excitement of a walk is over, Tucker walks well on leash and enjoys a nice long walk. He is young boy with a lot of energy and would do best if he had a yard in which to run and play or some type of doggie sports such as agility or fly ball to keep him mentally and physically challenged. He enjoys the kiddie pools at the shelter and would likely enjoy swimming. He has a canine girlfriend at the shelter and would enjoy a canine sibling. Once play time is over, he's happy to snuggle with you. Tucker is estimated to be approximately 2 years old. For an appointment to meet him, please email adoptions@satchelslastresort.org or call 941-924-5070.

animal.description:
Update: Humphrey is a dog that requires patient, love and consistency.   Humphrey has been returned four times. He needs an experienced home with an experienced handler.  He can be quite affectionate and loves dogs his size.  He enjoys playing fletch.  

He can be nippy if he becomes frustrated so he needs an active and affectionate home.  He responds well to calm... he responds poorly to be yelled at or handled roughly.  

Humphrey is an energetic boy who we're guessing has some Lab, golden retriever and chow in him. He was left behind by his family in a dirty, abandoned house in Puerto Rico.  Thankfully some of our rescue partners in Puerto Rico stepped up and took him to safety.

He has all his basic obedience commands and gets along well with dogs his size, but will need a family that will continue to provide structure and loving attention as he can be a loyal and loving addition.   No small dogs.  Cats are ok!

Humphrey is neutered and up to date with vaccinations. He will need a few meet and greets. He is extremely loyal once he is bonded to his family.  He is also good with cats.  

His adoption fee is $350.00. To apply go to monkeyspack.com

We cannot adopt to MA residents :(
