animal.description:
If youre looking for an easygoing, sweet dog to dote on with a funny, winning personality, then look no further: youve hit paydirt with Benny! Benny is a 10 year old Bully mix who loves chin and ear scratches, belly rubs, tasty snacks, and soft pillowy beds. He currently lives with a foster family and their miniature zoo. Hes a gentle giant that gets along with everyone: his Bully mix foster brother and ODH alum Thomas, five (!) cats, and a 15lb Flemish Giant rabbit named Julius.

If he could talk, Benny would wholly identify himself as a cat-lover. He likes to think he is young and spry, and loves to bark at the cats and chase them, which involves some hops and a quick shuffle in their direction. He quickly tires out and lays down after this. The shy cats in the household dont particularly care for this approach and will run from him when he does this, but the dog-savvy cats dont care, and will often let him indulge in some sniffs and a few kisses. Benny is also gentle with Julius, the aforementioned Flemish Giant, however, Julius is not afraid to give anyone a piece of his mind, and has established that he rules the house (dont tell the cats!).

For everything that hes been through, Benny is a very warm, agreeable, and loving pup! Hes our $12,000 dog thats about the final cost of saving his life after he was viciously attacked by another dog prior to coming into our care. Youd never know it, though! He has had no long-term ill effects from the attack, and hes a happy go-lucky guy that loves everyone. Hes also HW negative and neutered.

Given his age and size, Benny does have some old man arthritis, but he doesnt let it hinder him! His foster family lives in a two-story home, and Benny climbs up the stairs with a slow-but-steady confidence. He does need assistance getting down the stairs, which is made easy with a specialized harness. Benny will need ongoing care for his arthritis, in order to manage any pain he feels and keep his joints functioning. Currently, he receives weekly cold laser therapy, a joint health supplement with his meals, and at-home Adequan injections. Dont despair about the injections! These are very easy to give and he is the absolute goodest boy for them. He stands still and waits patiently, though lets be honest, that patience is probably reserved for the treat he gets afterward. Bonus: he can catch treats that are tossed to him! Hes got great eyesight and great reflexes, and as long as the treat is tossed directly to him, he will catch it.

While his foster family would consider Benny to be housetrained, due to his arthritis, Benny sometimes has number 2 accidents indoors. These mostly occur when hes sleeping, though occasionally he will have a movement fall out while hes walking around. His foster family has given him the nickname Plopper because of this, and joke that its his middle name. Benjamin Plopper OldDogHome. Hes a good boy who tries his best to wait to go outside for number 2, and consistently does his number 1s outside, but he cant help it when he has a number 2 accident inside. He would love nothing more than to have a forever family that would chuckle about it, and then clean it up as if nothing happened. Bonus points if his forever family keeps his nickname!

Benny would love a forever family to call his own! Hes great with other dogs, cats, and gentle older children. He has lots of love to give, and would love to meet you!
animal.name: Benny

animal.description: Mia resides at her foster mom's home. Please e-mail info@sheltertohome.com for an application, more information or to set up an appointment to meet her. *Mia has Evan's Syndrome, which is an autoimmune disease requiring a monthly visit the vet as well as daily medication. Please understand that if you are interested in adopting Mia, you would have to make a commitment to keep up on vet visits and costs.* Mia came into our rescue after being found on the streets. It appeared as though she was attacked by another dog. She has healed from her cuts and an abscess on her front leg. When it came time for Mia to be spayed, we discovered that she was pregnant with five pups. Her puppies have all been adopted. We noticed Mia having low energy, and we discovered she has Evan's Syndrome, an autoimmune disease. She currently gets a monthly blood test and is on a daily medication to help with her blood levels. Mia is a calm dog that does best with women, or calm adult men. She tolerates children well, but does not like loud noises and fast movement. Sometimes she is wary of men, but she gets along with the two adult men in her foster home. Mia enjoys going for short walks around the block, and playing with her chew toys. She is very gentle and loving. She gets along with other dogs, but should probably not be in a home with cats. Mia's adoption fee is $200, which includes spay and up to date shots.**All Shelter to Home animals are fully vetted per their age. We believe in pediatric spay and neuter. All animals will be spayed or neutered, tested for FIV/FeLV or heartworm, given age-appropriate boosters and rabies, dewormed, flea treated, and anything extra that is needed to give this animal a wonderful forever life in a permanent home. Adoption fees are usually $50 for cats and between $150-$250 for dogs, unless the pet is sponsored or we are running a promotion. Please visit our website at sheltertohome.com for information on our adoption process.**
animal.name: Mia

animal.description:
Piper is a high energy, high anxiety husky that loves to be with her person. She is one that’s always glued to her foster mom's feet. If she goes outside, PIper has to go to, even if she’s only watching me from the porch; if not, she cries. Her weight fluctuates from time to time, so an adopter must also pay attention to those needs. Piper is great with kids (her foster mom has two, ages 4 and 5) and dogs her size. She cannot be around tiny dogs, cats, or small farm animals. Piper can not be crated for long periods of time other than nighttime (3-4hrs max during the day or she will be stressed).  

An ideal home for Piper would be someone who works from home, will give her the time and attention she needs and is experienced with the breed. 

If you wish to apply for PIper, please email bjames@westga.edu, and your inquiry will be forwarded to her foster mom.

animal.description:
This sweet girl was running the city with no place to call home. She had a liter of pups under a strangers house and after a few weeks they boarded up the hole to where she couldn't get back under. I got the call about her and rushed over. After some investigating I found out that someone had come and taken her babies but left her behind because she was so scared. That was in Jan. She is still scared but as you can see by the pictures she is learning to trust every day. She loves other dogs and ignores the cats. She loves to snuggle in bed but once I stand up she is fearful and wants to run. She will need a family that is very dog savvy and is ready for a project pup. It will take some time to earn her trust, but when. you do, you will have a loyal friend till the end. She weighs about 50-60 pounds and is maybe 2 years old. It's time for her to have a family of her own.
Please go to funnyfarmrescueranch.org if you are interested in adopting. There you will find the adoption application as well as information about our rescue and how the adoption process works.
Adoption fee (including transport): $550

animal.description:
Bella is a survivor, she was dumped by her people at Harbor Shelter in Sept/Oct 2019, she was obese, couldn't walk, and in a lot of pain.  Bella is only 5yrs old but her neglectful owners just made her suffer.  We changed that, she is a spry little lambchop who is getting physical therapy at Beach Animal Rehab and had surgeries to help her knees bilateral and remove some bladder stones.  Bella is doing the best she can and manages to get down a ramp to the backyard to use the potty. She is pee pad trained too.  Bella is very sweet and grateful to be rescued, we've invested quite a bit of funding to ensure you don't have to worry about anything but love and exercise when you adopt her.  She connects instantly to her people, she is good with dogs and cats, she is good with kids over 12.  Bella's favorite past time is cuddling with you on the couch and gazing into your eyes.  She is definitely a foodie.  

Bella may need a doggie wheelchair as she ages but will remain strong if you allow her to walk on her own as much as possible.  She is on one NSAID pain medication for her arthritis and that should continue throughout her life.  She is WORTH her weight in gold and will make an excellent pet for anyone who cares enough to adopt her.  

Submit your application here: www.gonetothedogsrescue.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Gucci is a fabulous dog who was rescued from a local shelter, where he'd run out of time. Gucci is great with other dogs and loves to romp with his foster brother Ricky (also available for adoption if you're looking for 2 dogs!) and sister Maisie. He likes to play fetch and will even return the ball. Gucci walks very politely on the leash, with or without a canine walking companion. This affectionate snuggle bug loves to crawl into his foster mom's lap for cuddles. Gucci is crate-trained, house-broken, uses a dog door, and rides nicely in the car. He's the total package!

7/07/20 update: Gucci has become shy/fearful with new people when they're in his personal space. Gucci is working with a dog trainer to develop confidence with new people. By his third training session (over a 2-month period), Gucci was best friends with his trainer. He needs slow introductions to new people and a few positive encounters to warm up to them. He will do best in a quiet, adults-only household with someone who has experience with dogs and is willing and able to continue working with Gucci to help him overcome his shyness. No children for Gucci.

Gucci is neutered, current on vaccinations, heartworm negative and micro-chipped. Gucci will make a terrific companion for a lucky person or family. If you'd like to meet him, please complete an adoption application at https://legacyhumanesociety.org/adoptfoster/adoption-application/, and someone will respond within 48 hours. Gucci's adoption fee is $275.

Age: Approximately 2 years

Weight - 50 lbs.

We do not have a facility to house the dogs in our program. They are all kept in foster homes until they are adopted. Therefore, if you are interested in adopting from LHS, please complete an online application at http://legacyhumanesociety.org/adoptfoster/adoption-application/ and we will contact you asap about the status of your application.

animal.description:
Knoxville, TN - Chop is looking for his forever home! We saved him from a high kill shelter the day he was to be euthanized. Chop had hind end weakness, incontinence and was dragging his back legs. We consulted two veterinarians that indicated this was an old injury.  This was far from the correct diagnosis. 
After many months of negative progression we began getting more opinions from specialty vets and it was determined after diagnostics with UTK that he had subarachnoid diverticulum between his T9 and T10 vertebrae. Essentially the lining of the spinal cord fills with cerebrospinal fluid and causes compression on the spine. This diagnosis absolutely fits his symptoms and explains so much we have questioned over the last year.

Chop had the necessary surgery to help with his diagnosis. There has been positive improvements and he is now ready for his forever home! What an amazing Christmas gift that would be, right? 

Chop needs to be an ONLY dog and we do not recommend a home with cats either. We understand this is hard to find, but as you can see, he is a sweet boy who loves life and loves humans. He also needs someone that can accommodate potty breaks frequently, such as every 4 hours to help with is continued healing. 

We are begging all of our followers to please share Chop. This boy escaped death just in time, went through a spinal surgery and now he needs a forever home to help him thrive! He has such a will to live and needs a family that will love him and help him??

Additional Adoption Info:
Please visit our website for a detailed outline of our process: 
https://www.battleforthebully.org/

The Adoption Application can be found here:
https://www.battleforthebully.org/adoption

animal.description:
Sadie was brought in from another rescuer who was unable to keep her due to her high prey drive for cats.  She was relinquished to a facility because she was in rough shape upon coming in for a dr visit.  One of the employees at her previous intake location fell in love with her and took her home.  Sadie killed two of the cats in living in the home.  For this reason, they were unable to keep her and started looking for other options to re-home her.  When we got Sadie, she tested positive for heartworms and tested positive for Ehrlichia.  She has been treated for both and is doing well.  She will need to be spayed before she leaves the facility, but she is ready to start accepting adoption applications.  Sadie is kennel trained and does well at keeping her kennel clean.  She does get along with other dogs here at the facility, but she will need to go to a home with no cats or other small animals.  She is very sweet, loves treats, and can be shy at first, but warms up rather quickly.  If you think you may make a great home for Sadie, stop in to visit with her and fill out an application.

All of our animals are cared for and examined by our veterinarian, spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, and dewormed. To inquire about any of our animals please e-mail us at rescuedheartanimalhospital@ymail.com or click on the link. Provide the name of the animal that you are interested in and your preferred contact information. We will then send you an adoption application and/or set up a time for you to stop in and meet Sadie to ensure that she's the right dog for you.

animal.description: Hi! I'm Sahara! I'm a fun-loving, high-spirited young girl who loves to play! I love to frolic in the baby pool, I love to play with all sorts of toys, I enjoy walks or runs, and I think fetch is great! I am a smart girl and can learn new things quickly- I know to sit and wait for my food and I am house trained. After a fun day, I love some good snuggles- I'm very affectionate. Although I can enjoy play time with other dogs, I need slow introductions to other dogs and may not pair well with some- I am not a good dog for a dog park. My perfect home would be one where I would be the only pet in the home OR where I get to live with a confident playful large male dog that I pair well with so we can play. Although I love walks and runs, I am reactive when I see other dogs on leash so I would also love to find a forever home with a fenced yard so I can also enjoy off leash play time without the stress of seeing other dogs on leash. Yes, I know I have some quirks but I promise that my big heart, playful antics, and goofiness are worth it- I have a LOT of love to give, pick me!

Code red was on them and no rescues were taken them . So what do you do ???

We did not wait and took them both under our wings .

Meet Athena. She is reported to be a Pit Bull Terrier Mix. She is 3 yrs old. She is energetic, playful, loving, and a great snuggle buddy. She knows basic commands. She is house broken and free to roam throughout her foster home. She is potty trained however being as she was used for breeding her bladder can be leaky at times especially if she is excited or has to wait too long to be let out to potty. She came into rescue from a bad situation in which her reality was being locked up in a kennel, breeding, and malnourishment. That being said she has done amazing in her foster home. Athena needs an experienced dog owner who will continue working on training. She is dog selective and can be reactive to strangers as well out of fear/nervousness. She will not be a dog you can take into populated situations and will never be able to go to the dog park for her safety and the safety of other dogs. She currently lives with another dog who is older/submissive and they get along just fine. She currently lives with cats however she does like to chase them so a home without cats would be ideal. She needs a fenced yard preferably privacy or a home without neighbors in close proximity. 


Athena is vaccinated for rabies, distemper, and bordatella. Athena is spayed and is microchipped. Athena's adoption fee is $350 plus WI state tax!

If you are interested in meeting Athena, please fill out an application at luckypawsmidwest.org. Once your application is approved, we can set up a time for you to meet Athena!

animal.description: Shine Shine Shine!!  This gal has the most soulful set of eyes!  She looks at you as if all the worlds problems are hers to solve.  They could also be just so very heavy as she has had a rough life.  Shine is approximately 4 years old.  She was brought to our attention from our friends at HARTT.    She showed up and started to sleep in the carport of a home that belonged to a caring couple in Ton0pah, AZ .  She stayed for weeks, accepting food and water but not allowing anyone to come close to her.  Initially she had open wounds, a heavy limp and it was obvious she has had multiple litters.   Volunteers from HARTT were able to humanely trap Shine and after some bouncing around, Shine is now in our care.  We have really enjoyed falling in love with this beautiful soul.  She is as grateful and sweet as can be.  She will thrive in a home that has no other animals and a family that will allow her to snuggle up with them and to watch a good movie or to share a pillow over night.   We have listed Shine as a special needs dog as she will need life- long management care for her elbow.  She has to have limited exercise (just walks) and it is important that she does not become over-weight.  X-rays show  an extreme  arthritic elbow that can cause her quite a bit of discomfort.  But Shine will live happily ever after in a home that lives a low key lifestyle and will spoil her.  She does just fine with her sore elbow. If you are interested in adopting Shine, please take a moment to fill out our application:  www.povertyspet.org/adoption.   There is a $200 donation and all adoptions are required to have an application to begin the process.  Once received, you will be contacted within 48 hours.  Thank you!

animal.description:
Cooli is a loving, smart 2-year-old, 55 pound Pit mix. She loves to go for walks and run around in the yard with a stick in her mouth waiting for someone to play fetch! She also loves her puzzle toys because she's a very smart girl! She takes her treats very gently too. Cooli's ideal family would need to be dedicated to exercising her regularly (walks, toy time, and yard time...hikes would be a bonus!). Due to her energy level, she will need a home with a fenced yard. Although Cooli loves people, she needs to be an only dog in the home so she doesn't have to share your attention. She has not experienced young children thus a home with no children or kids 12+ is needed. Cooli has wonderful house manners and is fully house trained. She is spayed, microchipped, up-to-date on vaccines and preventatives, and eager to find a family to love! If you are looking for an unconditionally loving, smart, energetic pup to bring into your family, Cooli is the girl for you!

The adoption fee for this dog is $350 which includes routine vetting and spay/neuter.

***Please note that our first step is submitting an application (it does not commit you in any way but allows us to discuss with you if you and the dog are a good fit). In addition, an important step in approving adoption applicants is to complete a vet check. Vetting of current and past pets is very important to us, thus we will be speaking with the vet(s) listed on your application to ensure that your current and previous pet(s) are kept up to date on vaccines (including rabies), spayed or neutered, maintained on appropriate monthly preventatives and examined annually by your vet.***

To complete an online application, please click here and email Crystal at cwoodlovepaws@gmail.com

animal.description: !!! AVAILABLE for Adoption from Foster Care !!! MACY - A#43781416Foster's email: beccanock@gmail.comPhotos: Macy in foster care - https://photos.app.goo.gl/hDNX3onwd7qSRKHc9Macy in foster care pt2! - https://photos.app.goo.gl/4Yaj1yHySuzcZnrm8Macy's Slumber Party - https://photos.app.goo.gl/jyuc8FgX8iPA2XT26Another Slumber Party - https://photos.app.goo.gl/yoxDGg8fSm8iZYy29Macy's beauty shots - https://flic.kr/s/aHsmLisZYnPersonality: - Macy is definitely a morning person! She is always very happy when she wakes up, wants to give extra snuggles, and is excited to go on a morning walk.- Macy loves sunshine. She enjoys laying in the sun or going on long walks on sunny days. She can get a little feisty on grey cloudy days.- Macy eats like a champ (so far she has loved all dry food and treats), and she is completely house trained (no accidents)!- She loves going out for walks. She preps by stretching, crawling on her elbows and knees, and howling (it's very cute).- Macy likes to spend as much time outdoors as possible, and we have found that she is pretty happy walking 4-5 miles per day.- We have been walking her 3 times a day - first thing in the morning, sometime in the afternoon (3-6pm), and then at 8:30pm.- She loves having her neck and chest scratched.- Macy loves all toys - we haven't found a dog toy she doesn't like. She especially likes rope/pull toys and balls.- Macy will not let you eat peanut butter unless you also give her some!- Macy likes to walk at a brisk pace and she will jog or run if you let her. She did a 9:45min mile and can definitely go faster!- Macy is an excellent city dog - she isn't scared of cars, bicycles, or other people. She wants to meet other dogs and play when we go out on walks, and she doesn't understand what a quarantine is.- Macy does not seem to like small dogs very much. She barks when she hears high pitched barking or when she sees a small dog barking on the street.- Macy loves toilet paper - you have to watch to make sure she doesn't unwind the whole roll or steal a roll to run around with.- Macy also loves drinking water, and she will stick her head in the shower while it is on just to see if she can catch a few drops. - She does like a lot of attention and will nudge you with her nose, lick your hands, or bark when she thinks you aren't giving her enough attention.- Macy loves to give kisses, especially face kisses.- Macy knows "sit", "down", and "come here", and she is currently working on "stay."- She is great during car rides.Intake Type: (2/7) Stray Weight: 47.00 poundsMedical Observation:(2/8) Senior dog with dental disease and fractured teeth, some cranial organomegally and low grade heart murmur, underweight body condition with muscle wasting r/o underlying medical/metabolic cause vs nutritional vs parasitic or other infectious. Single patch of hairloss on tail could be secondary to underlying endocrine disorder vs old trauma vs less likely FAD. Recommend promotion to rescue willing to perform senior bloodwork and dental +/- abdominal ultrasound pending bloodwork results and cardiac work-up. Behavior Observation: (3/12) Slumber Party Notes:Macy is a wonderful dog. She is so caring, sweet and very obedient. She was a wonderful snuggler and was just looking for attention and affection where ever she could have it. No accidents in the house. I know there was a question about being house trained, but she was great with us. She would howl a little bit to let us know she needed to go outside to pee. We walked her twice a day. Small quick walk in the AM and then a long one at night. She slept in a bed with us one evening but the second night chose to stay downstairs for the first half of the evening on the couch. She is a little bit of a snorer, but it was very cute. She was playful and energetic. She was not begging for food nor getting into anything she was not supposed to. We have an open garbage can in the kitchen and she paid it no mind. She walked wonderfully on the lease and was never timid, startled, or scared by anything on our walks. She was utterly unfazed and barely made a peep during her whole stay. She was never anxious in the car. She sat on the seat and just looked out the window. Granted we live in a quiet home, just my partner and I. There are no children nor pets but Macy was so peaceful that I can imagine her doing well in a lot of environments. Macy is an all-star and deserves the best!This animal is currently available from foster care through ACCT Philly's Adoptions Programs. If the foster has not listed a personal email, contact adopt@acctphilly.org to be put in touch with the foster.We encourage you to visit our shelter during our adoption hours to view our complete selection of available animals. In preparation for your visit, please make sure to visit http://www.acctphilly.org/adopt/ to review our adoption requirements, hours of operation, upcoming events, and more!Is this your missing pet? If you believe so, please make sure to follow the instructions listed at http://www.acctphilly.org/lostpet/ so that we can make sure that you are reunited as soon as possible!

She requires daily exercise every day. She has very loud bark, and likes to "talk" when she gets excited. When her foster family gets up in the morning and whenever they come home--she gets very excited and will leap with all four feet off the ground. This is just part of who she is. She could use some basic training. She has a very sweet spirit, and just craves attention. She is also very good with all other dogs, large and small. She loves her pack! Abby may be too hyper for small children, and not sure about cats. Abby’s adoption fee is $175 and includes age appropriate vaccines, spay and a microchip. animal.description:
Daisy is one of the smartest dogs I have ever met!! She learns quickly and at times seems to out think the people she is with.

She chases balls, does a few tricks, and really shines at figuring out puzzles and tasks on her own.

She is fascinated by the barn swallows that nest in the eaves around the house. She doesn't want to hurt them, just likes to watch!

Daisy can leap really high and requires a sturdy, safe fenced in yard. She is part hound!! She would wander off quickly without a good fence. 

Daisy is about 6 years of age, spayed, and fully vaccinated. She weighs about 60 pounds. Daisy gets along well with other dogs close to her size. She is likely to chase cats and small dogs.

She loves people and kids and will play all day if you let her!!

Please contact Sue Sweeney: fairviewfarm@earthlink.net for an application

animal.description:
Tyson came into the shelter as a euthanasia request. His owners decided he should be put to sleep because Tyson bit the child in home that tried to pick him up while he was eating. Some of the shelter employees fell for this misunderstood little man and asked us to help him. That we did.

While Tyson will absolutely let you know (by showing his teeth) when he doesn’t like something (usually while guarding his food), he is easily redirected. He doesn’t come gunning for you or looking to hurt anyone; his body language is pretty loud and clear. We have also found Tyson to be such a little lover. He likes to be picked up when he chooses to seek attention, almost cat like. He is house and crate trained as well as knows basic obedience.

Tyson is 6 years old and ready for another chance at life. This chihuahua needs a patient home that will take the time to get to know him and his quirks. We know there are those special humans out there who excel in handling fearful littles.

Tyson loves other dogs, but a little too much. He will usually chase them around and continuously hump them, often guarding them if you try to remove him. So while he’s friendly as all heck with dogs big and small, we think to set him up for success, Tyson should be the only dog in the home. This isn’t a definite  requirement but what we currently feel after initially observation.

So who is that special someone that can take the time to get to know our little dude? When not guarding anything, Tyson is easily handled, gives smooches, and loves to get all the pets. If you think you could be Tyson’s human, apply today! Go to www.pittiepleaserescue.org to apply.

animal.description:
Oh, Dillon.? We are forever thankful this handsome dude kept hanging on at the shelter. He waited at the south side intake shelter for months, after having been found as a stray with another dog. His buddy was rescued but Dillon sat waiting, said to possibly need to be an only dog from how much he declined.

Fast forward to PPR being able to break Dillon out. While he still has that pent up energy at times, he uses it only in positive ways since being in the comfort of a foster home! Dillon loves nothing more than to run around and play nonstop with #fkingRichard and has a number of girlfriends too! Dillon is currently working on his leash manners. We would love to see him find a family to call his own, humans that are active and excited to start some training classes together.

Dillon is such a pleaser. He just wants to make everyone happy while buzzing around as a social butterfly. He is thought to be about 2-3 years old and is a beast size, not too big. While his home is not limited to the following, this is what we envision being Dillon’s perfect setup: an active adult/couple with some experience and interest in training, with a yard and another playful female bully breed. Again, Dillon’s bestie is also a chihuahua, but a chi with a big dog personality. We just know he likes to play, play, play.

Dillon has been waiting so long for his own humans. We know he will make the right people so incredibly happy. He keeps us laughing and thankful to have supporters that help us fight for those long-term shelter dogs often left behind. Dillon deserves the best! Apply today www.pittiepleaserescue.org

I’m an extremely handsome, smart & loyal boy.  I love to give & receive affection and can go from silly & playful, to the hard working breed that I am, taking my work serious to please my human.  I will need a large fenced area, to satisfy my need to run, herd and protect, as well as a consistent trainer who will give me  lots of stimulation, exercise and positive correction to keep me focused and overcome my occasional stubbornness,  I really just don't realize my size or strength, so I would do best with adults or older children, slow introduction to other dogs, and experience with my Great Pyrenes breed would be a plus.  Do you have the love and patience I deserve, so I can give you all the love and loyalty I have?

You can complete an adoption application on our website at:  
     www.onceuponatailrescue.com
or
     Scroll down on this page & click "More About Us", & then click "Adoption            Application" underneath our bright Pink logo. 

If you want to meet a pup in person, Once Upon a Tail Rescue does adoption events at PetSmart in Covington, LA on most Saturdays with many of our adoptable dogs there. 

Don't forget to complete your application ahead of time, so you don't miss out on the pup you've connected with.  If pre-approved, you have first priority & can usually take home your new best friend the same day!  

*Please note that there is no obligation to adopt by completing an application.*

**All dogs are required to be fully vetted. Shots, rabies, spay/nueter and microchip.  This is all covered in Adoption fee. Some may still need vetting done due to age, size, breed and health. All vetting will be done by rescues vet clinic.

Additional info:

Tanner came to us from a hoarding situation and was the most fearful of all of his siblings. But in the months we have had him, he has come such a long way. He used to be so fearful of the leash that he would bite when it was placed on.  He does not get super excited when the leash comes out because he knows it means a walk. He still has some leash training to do and will run in different directions because he's so happy and he can be somewhat leash reactive. He loves to play with toys and play chase with other dogs and is now up for plenty of belly rubs. Tanner can still be a nervous with new people so his new person/people will need to have some patience in the beginning while he adjusts.  He will follow the lead of another dog so he does need another well adjusted and playful dog in the home that can help him learn the ins and outs of the household.

If you are not ready to adopt just yet and would like to help in other ways, please consider clicking on the green “Sponsor Me” button above to help this dog receive the best care we can give. We rely on the generosity of others to make rescuing dogs possible.

1.       Visit www.dogswithoutborders.org
2.      Then fill out an online ADOPTION APPLICATION -  http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-application/
3.       Please wait to hear from our representative in approximately 48 hours on weekdays.

animal.description:
Hello, I'm Amara.  I am a spunky girl born early November last year. I am still very much a puppy but I'm working hard on being a good girl. I am crate trained and house trained, I even bark at the door when I need to go out.  I am lean &  really fast! I love to chase balls, chew on stuffies and my bones. I like kids but since I have a lot of energy I would need to be watched around smaller ones.
I would love to meet you to see if I fit your family if you would like to meet me too please complete an adoption application. 

**Amara has a slight fear of strangers entering her home space. It is easily. manageable with slow introductions on leash.

animal.description: Boris is over this shelter business and ready to get the heck out of Dodge! He has understandably become more frustrated and anxious in the shelter, and he is a priority pup to get into a foster home. Based on some of his responses and behaviors, we think there is a strong possibility that Boris was exposed to harsh punitive training methods. And because of that, we make sure to keep our time with him super low-pressure and offer him lots of praise and encouragement! Boris can be a little tentative with new people, but just go slowly because he wants to be your friend. He wants to trust and to love. It is so easy to love Boris in return with his endearing demeanor. Boris has a short list of things that he really likes: squeaky toys, deli meat, and water fun! Put a kiddie pool in your backyard or patio, and Boris will happily lounge about for as long as you let him! Boris has his quirks and will need a low-traffic home without young children but respectful teenagers would be great! Boris has potential to live with other playful dogs but they would to be kept separated initially to allow him to decompress, and then slow and managed intros with which we can help! We know that a patient and compassionate person is exactly what Boris needs to increase his confidence, and we are excited for all the potential that he has! While whatever happened to him in his past makes us sad, we will do our best to make sure that his future is bright and happy. I weigh approximately 63 lbs. Click here to view all of Boris's behavior notes from staff and volunteers.

Merra is a 6 year old Boxer mix. She is up to date on shots, spayed, house trained and crate trained. Merra ended up in rescue due to no fault of her own. Her mom loved her very much and took excellent care of her but sadly couldn't keep Merra when she was being stationed overseas. 
Merra has been with JHS for several months now, and she continues to get overlooked. She has lots of energy and needs a home that loves adventures, like hiking and swimming. Merra is great off leash and know all her commands. Merra would do best with no other dogs in the home, but she gets along with cats and doesn’t mind other dogs out in public. 


The Junior Humane Society is a non-profit, all volunteer, animal rescue group. For over 30 years, we have helped animals in the Gulf Coast area. 
All animals waiting for adoption are placed in foster homes. Before placing the animal in a furever home, JHS provides all necessary vet care, including but not limited to: shots, spaying, and neutering. 
We hold adoptions event every Saturday at PetSmart in Pensacola, FL from 12-4

No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

animal.description:
Handsome Dipper is looking for a new friend and he wants to pick you! He is a very athletic dog, loves his long walks and playing fetch. You would think he is training for a marathon because he loves walking on a treadmill as well. He is a dog's dog when it comes to playing - he plays long and hard. Dipper is not a fan of cats nor small children, so keep that in mind. Dipper is very well mannered as he is potty and crate-trained and enjoys car rides. He also benefits from mental exercise, such as eating out of a slow feeder and Kongs filled with peanut butter.

Because of his athletic disposition, Dipper will need an active and confident handler who can set boundaries and funnel his energy into positive activities. Dipper is treat motivated so that will help with training and the bonding process. Dipper is asking for multiple meets with potential adopters to ensure his comfortability and to make sure this is a good fit for both Dipper and the potential adopter. But as we know, treats are his weakness! Once he settles in and establishes a routine, he will love you to pieces and you will have his absolute adoration. Are you that special friend Dipper has been looking for and needing? Come meet him today and see if you will be BFFs (Best Friends Forever).

Dipper is two years old and weighs 68 pounds.
 
Dipper's adoption fee is $200; he is microchipped, up to date on vaccines, and neutered. Some of our pets are in foster care and not located at the shelter. If you are interested in a specific pet, contact the shelter at (618) 939-7389 to arrange a meeting.

animal.description: Rocky that's Rocky James was  rescued from a  two lane freeway where  he diligently denied traffic looking for the truck that dumped him and drove off.  When we  came  upon him we knew  we  couldn't leave him.  Leaving him would have certainly meant a disastrous outcome. Teamwork, a tired dog and three hours later Rocky James was  safe.  No looking back for RJ.  We  are looking forward to finding Rocky J  his  own man cave  with a  whole new owner.  Rocky has  warmed  up quickly  to our kennel volunteers.  He  walks well on the leash and although  he  doesn't seem to know any formal commands  he  listens  well and  catches on quickly.  Rocky  is  cautious  and a bit scared  of loud  and sudden noises.  He  can be  a bit unsure in wide open situations that don't offer  security.  One-on-one  he is attentive and aims to please.  Rocky  will  benefit from  obedience training so he can respond accordingly in new  situations and have a clear definition of who  his leader is. Rocky is simply a big dog that fits the description of a loyal companion. He  is available for adoption.  He is neutered, up-to-date on shots and microchipped.  His adoption fee is $200  which allows us to rescue and save another dog in need.

animal.description:
Richard is  4.5 year old friendly little doxie.  He was diagnosed with IVDD when he went rear paralyzed in the fall.  His family chose to do the surgery to help him recover from the paralysis.  While he did resume his ability to wobbly walk he could use support  of water and physical therapy and our local neuro churopractor .  He remains incontinent and needs a family that can manage this lifelong. with no expectiations of improvement.  We have found a belly band helps and feeding him at regular intervals to time his potty needs

Richard loves everyone except for cats.  However because he is more fragile he should not be in a home with small children.  Richard is fully vetted, neutered and microchipped.  He has some initial separation  anxiety and would do good in a home with a homebody or at least some pets to help keep him company.

We would like to see him go to a home that has IVDD experience in the local Chicago metro area.  If you would like to know more about RIchard or request and adoption application please contact us at:  RescueTailsAnimalWelfare@gmail.com.  Please realize we are volunteers that work full time jobs.  We will try to get back to you within 48 hours.

If you’re looking for a handsome boy, you’ve found him! Terrell is short, stocky, & laid back. 

Background: Terrell was found as a local stray. He stayed at a vets office for a few months before coming to us. They got him fattened back up and even took care of his vetting. 

Age: The vet is thinking he’s around 7 years old. 

Size: Terrell is around 70-80 lbs but is short and thick. 

Coat: Terrell has short hair but does shed. He will need bathed every few weeks. 

Energy Level: Terrell is pretty laid back. Definitely enjoys his comfort and loves laying in bed. After he goes outside to do his business he’s ready for a nap. 

Medical Info: Terrell has been vaccinated, heartworm tested, neutered, & microchipped. He does not currently take any medications for any conditions, besides his monthly heartworm prevention. 

Terrell’s adoption donation is $175.

animal.description:
Cherry arrived on the 3rd of March after she was no longer able to stay with her owners. We believe she is a shar pei mix, about 2 years old, and 37 pounds. Cherry is a super sweet girl that has been in a foster home for most of her time with us. They have said that she is a sweet and affectionate girl. She loves to go on walks and even jogs but she is also chill in the house on her comfy bed. She is a quiet girl and doesn't bark much. They said she has adjusted well to their children but likely would be happiest with adults or teens that are a bit more mellow. She did well with potty training in their home and they started trying to work on basic commands as well. They said she hasn't been taught anything before but she is treat motivated and is seeming to pick up well. Cherry is a very sweet girl that will make a wonderful companion in a loving home.

HSMC Adoption applications must be done at www.hsmcohio.org  Please do NOT click on the "Adopt Me" button on this bio. It is only a pet inquiry. If you have additional questions about this dog, please call the shelter at 614-879-8368 or contact us through our website!

Our adoption fees vary, Shelter Dogs are $150, Prison Dogs are $200, Puppies are $250, and Popular Pure-Breeds are $400. The price includes: a Home Again Microchip, set of shots, de-worming, heartworm testing (if old enough), spay or neuter, and a 1 year rabies shot (if old enough). All dogs adopted must leave with a county license at an additional cost of $17, this fee is cash only. Adoption fees can be done using credit card or cash.  If you are interested in this dog, please call the shelter at 614-879-8368 or fill out an online application at www.hsmcohio.org

animal.description:
Rocky has made so much progress since being rescued in December. He was kept in a dark basement almost all of his life, where he had to ration his food and water, never went outside or received any affection. 

He may be 8 years old but he has so much energy! He loves to be outside and go for walks. Rocky has so much love to give and will make someone so happy one day!! He has the best smile and just hanging out with him will make your day. He is so grateful for his new life, he can sometimes be a little jumpy. Therefore we think he would do best in a home with only older children. 

Because of his past it takes him a little while to trust men. It is difficult for him to meet new people however once he gets to know you, he’ll shower you with kisses! Rocky does have a bite record, but has never turned on someone he knows.  

If you are interested in adopting, we recommend you visit him multiple times to see his true, amazing personality! It takes time to gain his trust but the loves he gives is well worth it! 

**We do not do out of state adoptions**

To do our part to contain the spread of COVID-19, The Animal Haven is only open by appointment for approved applicants until further notice. Check our Facebook page for more updates as the situation develops. Thank you for your understanding, and we hope you stay safe and well.

Applications are available on our website, theanimalhavenct.org. If interested, please send an application to Michelle@TheAnimalHavenCT.org or mail it to 89 Mill Road, North Haven CT 06473.


For additional information please check our Facebook page!

He was doing well working on potty training in his foster home, and will get there in no time with people who earn his trust. He enjoys laying in dog beds and walks well using a harness. Charlie would do best in a home with an outgoing dog that can teach him how to be a real dog (instead of a scaredy cat)!

animal.description:
Meet Bronx! This medium-sized guy is as smart as they get. He is between 1-2 years old. Bronx is very people social! We are happy about this because he had a rough start at life. He has been hand picked by a trainer & has been put through obedience training & is said to aim to please & is a quick study. He is a handsome guy & is ready to learn what a cozy house feels like. If you're looking for a loyal, respectable companion, here he is! We guess him to be a Staffordshire Terrier or mix. Bronx lived with children & is said to do well with them. We are only accepting applications for Bronx with the following:
*Must have a privacy fence 6' or taller on all sides
*No neighboring dogs
*No children in the home under the age of 12
Bronx is not ok with other pets but great with people! He has a strong prey drive. Bronx was recently adopted to a family with young children & he does great with kids, but a child walked Bronx out front since they had no fence & Bronx proceeded to get loose when he saw a small dog running at large. Bronx needs an adopter that will make sure something like this never happens again. Bronx is truly a remarkable dog & needs to be set up to succeed.

Interested? Please visit https://dogsbydebin.com/adoption-application/ to complete our quick online adoption application. His adoption fee is $175 & includes: Neuter, microchip, vaccines, heartworm test, deworming, & an offer of pet-healthcare insurance for 1-month.

Hi my name is Elwood and I’m still searching for my furever home. I thought I had found it but it didn’t work out. Apparently I can jump high and the fence there wasn’t sufficient to keep me safe. I will need love, patience and training to teach me not to scale the fence. I'm a smart boy so I know with your help,  I can learn.

I am a 1 1/2 to 2 year old, adorable tri-colored lab mix who loves adventure. I am in search of an active, adventurous family looking to make memories. I am an active boy who can keep up with your high energy level and together we can be our best selves. I am a very sweet, loving, and loyal companion. It may take me a little while to adjust and completely come out of my shell, but I’m sure we will be best friends! Sometimes I don’t realize how big I am, so I do best with children 13 and up.

Click on www.starsrescue.org to complete an application to be pre-approved to adopt this pup.  We will contact you regarding your application and date for meet and greet.

animal.description:
A young squishy faced boy was surrendered to CACC so sick with respiratory issues that blood and mucus were covering his face, and it was reported that he wasn’t eating. In addition to looking like a sick toddler who doesn’t know how to use a tissue, he was covered in urine and feces. None of this broke his spirit! He ate like a champ, responded well to antibiotics, and quickly became a cuddle favorite of volunteers. All the while we had been looking for a foster family, one who was truly dedicated and committed to training. Not just any training...one that is experienced with deaf dogs. Yep. You read that right. On top of all the hardships this young boy's body show he’s endured, he’s also deaf. Does that stop him? Nope. And it didn’t stop one of our foster families, they couldn’t have been more excited to step up for the undertaking
EDUCATION:
* Average energy
* Learning hand signals
* Sit
* Down
* Paw
* Working on other manners
ACTIVITIES THIS CUTIE ENJOYS:
* Playing with other dogs
* Cuddling
* Butt scratches
* Jumping into your lap
* Chewing on appropriate things
* Toys: Kong, Nylabones, ropes, chewies, the Kong Wobbler
* Treats: whipped cream, followed by peanut butter
* Food: did we mention whipped cream and peanut butter?
SKILLS:
* Dogs: friendly but overexcited
* Kids: loves them but needs time to warm up
* People: cautious and needs time to warm up
* Cats: unknown
CHALLENGES:
* Learning to love the crate
* He's deaf, needs consistent training
* Working on his confidence. The backyard is a little scary
* He nibbles on people to show his love
* Needs a long walk or run daily to keep his energy in check
* He's learning to be better on a leash. He gets excited to see other dogs and people
* Must have fenced yard

animal.description:
This pretty girl is IVY - she is only 20 months old and a cropped/docked female.

Loves to play and snuggle on the couch. Loves walks. Does good on a leash but does pull. Doesn't jump. Knows basic commands, doesn't minds baths. 

Currently she is fostered with small children (2 years old and 7 years old) but no other pets.  She tolerates the kids but has growled before at the toddler so proper pet boundaries should be in place to keep Ivy feeling safe.  She is a nervous girl, she does not like to be left alone or any distance away from her person.

At night she must sleep with people to relax; if not she paces and is destructive due to separation anxiety.  Due to this anxiety, she will not go into a crate and is not crate trained.  She does great on car rides and attends work with her foster mom.  Due to this, she is socialized to many different kinds of people and has shown some fear towards some adults.  She is protective and growls to show discomfort in her situation. 

Known history:   Prior owner said she was raised with a pit bull (female) and they played fine although ivy was very dominant over the female.

Woody came into our program from a hoarding situation. He is very sweet once you get to know him, but he is very shy at first. He runs and hides from any new person. Woody does well with other dogs. We have not tested him with cats and we do not recommend him for a home with children due to being fearful. 

All dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are up to date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered (age appropriate), and heartworm negative. All dogs are given monthly flea/tick preventative, monthly heartworm preventative, and are dewormed regularly. Dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are microchipped. Adoption fee is $50. Home visit and vet reference required. Applications can be put in online at http://www.troyanimalrescueproject.org/adopt.php or in person at our rescue center.

The address for our rescue center is 34 County Road 2266, Brundidge, AL 36010. We are one turn off Hwy 167. If you use Google maps, type in Troy Animal Rescue Project and it will take you right to us. Hours of operation are from 10-3 daily. We are open Saturdays and Sundays. No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Appointments can be made by calling 334-508-2367 or emailing troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

Joey would be a wonderful companion for a stay at home person or a senior person who just wants someone to love. You would need to be able to pick up 19 lbs in case Joey needed some help. A fenced in yard would also be good and give Joey the opportunity to roam around not on a leash. If you are interested in helping Joey please contact Vivienne at viviennejames@comcast.net or 615-943-7311. You won't be sorry. Joey is neutered, current on all his shots and microchipped. animal.description:
Hey y'all, I'm Otis! I'm about 2 years old and 75(ish) pounds of pure goofball and clumsiness!  I was chained up most of my life outside and I have some scars to prove it.  My foster family has kept me inside and shown me what a house full of love and family life can be.  I think I much prefer the inside.  Everything inside is new for me so you should expect that my head will be in every door and drawer you open.  

Toys fear me!  There is not a surviving plush toy in my foster parents house.  I will shred them and spread the stuffing around your living room like snow.  They keep buying them on sale though so I think they like the decorations I do for them.  If you give me a 99 cent squeaky ball, I will carry it for hours.  Squeaky balls are precious to me. 

I may be full of scars on the outside, but show me just a little love and I will be fiercely protective and loyal.  I am just now learning how to lay down and be calm next to my foster parents and they are working on showing me something called snuggles.  I watch my foster siblings snuggle and it looks amazing. 

I love walks!  I am good on a leash but sometimes I like to stop and ponder the world around me.  I am crate trained.  I am house trained and  will ring a bell and wait by the back door if you show me where it is.  

I think I would be best in a home with another good sized dog to play with.  I’m good with kids, but I have no idea how big I am and I don’t always know where my feet are.  Older kids might be better.  I’m not so sure about cats.  My current foster parents aren’t sure about cats either so I haven’t really met them much.  I am not food aggressive, but I prefer to eat in the solitude of my crate.  

Take me home!  Show me the love I need and we will be the best of friends.  I just need a little more time to come out of my shell.


Otis is neutered, microchipped, and vaccinated. He is crate trained and walks well on a leash, and is currently doing well with house training. If you think you could be Dasher's new family, please visit our website at www.maziesmission.org/adopt to fill out an application!

animal.description:
* Medical Special Needs *
Meet Crystal. What do you see when you look at Crystal? An overbred momma dog? A dog that had a horrible person chop off her ears? A dog that was left inside a crate at an abandoned property? You know what we see? Unconditional love, this girl wants affection and love so badly. She craves to be told she is a good girl, a warm leg to lean on. She is beautiful to us both inside and out. You will see that too when you come meet her and give her a chance. She enjoys a bath and belly rub, hugs and a romp in the yard but her favorite thing to do is hang out with people who love her. Sometimes it will take her a little while to warm up to new people, but the wait is so worth it. She is just a big love bug. She is not fond of other dogs. She can go for walks with them but not exist together in a house or come face to face. She is obsessed with cats so if you are interested in her, you can't have any of those either. She does have cancer (cutaneous hemangiosarcoma). It manifests itself with sores and blood blisters on her stomach and these will pop occasionally and bleed. Eventually the disease will go to her spleen. Her survival can be a few years with this type of cancer by the time it has spread to the spleen. Are you the person to love and provide care for Crystal for her remaining years? If so, please email adoptions@satchelslastresort.org or call 941-924-5070 for an appointment to meet her.

animal.description:
Wilder here! I’ve been told that I’m very cute and photogenic. You’re probably surprised to see me on a Malamute Rescue website since I’m a husky. Thank DOG for Moonsong for rescuing me; I was going to be euthanized because the shelter I was in didn’t have an adoption program.

I’m fun sized, weighing in around 50 lbs. Being smaller I can get intimidated by bigger dogs but with slow introductions, I do well with dogs over 20 lbs. I prefer ladies over men and walk well on leash unless I see a squirrel! No cats or farm animals for me because I want to chase them.

I don’t mind being brushed but baths are not my thing. My foster family is teaching me with positive reinforcement (treats and praise) to not greet people by jumping on them. It’s a bit embarrassing, but sometimes if I get overly excited, I pee. My tummy is sensitive, so I eat special kibble and like some dogs I can scale a 6’ fence easily so I need to be supervised in the yard. I am crate trained and sleep quietly in my crate all night. I’m good with children over 6 if they are respectful.

If you’re looking for a fun sized northern breed, then I’m your boy!     
 
See more images of Wilder on our web site here:
https://www.moonsongmals.org/adoption/Wilder_11_19/Wilder_11_19.html
 
STATUS/LOCATION: Available.  In foster care, Boise, ID. Please contact Gina - gina@moonsongmals.org -  for more information about Wilder.

animal.description:
IF THIS LISTING IS STILL UP, they are still available for adoption!    Inquiries asking about availability will not be answered. E-mails or contact forms that are submitted prior to completing an adoption application will not be answered.

***Please read this first, as it answers the majority of questions we receive***

Please do not contact us about specific dogs until you have completed our Adoption Application FIRST --- located at www.aussierescue.org

Once we receive your application, we will contact you. This chapter only receives applications from applicants living in Texas and Oklahoma. If you live outside of TX or OK, you will need to contact our organizations Management Team first: managementteam2@yahoo.com). Out-of-state adoptions are considered on a case-by-case basis.

Our organization requires prospective adopters to complete an approval process prior to meeting with dogs in our program. This includes:

*Completion of Adoption Application
*Veterinarian Check
*Reference Checks (non-relatives)
*Home Visit

Our ultimate goal is to screen and counsel potential homes to the best of our ability in an effort to find the most perfect match and fit for their lifestyle.

Please keep in mind that color and appearance of the available dog is last on our priority list, and will have no bearing on adoption placement decisions.

Please refrain from contacting members of our organization or asking about specific dogs/potential matches until after your screening process has been completed and approved. 

***Our organization requires a donation of $300 to adopt.***
--------------------------------------------------------

ABOUT BRIGHTON:
Rep: Laura Kempf - aussie330@aol.com

Brighton is located in North Richland Hills, TX and it is required that you travel there to meet her in person to adopt, no exceptions. We do need the entire party to be involved when meeting available dogs, including every family member and dog(s) that currently live in your home.

Brighton is a 4-year old, 35lb double merle female that is completely deaf.  While she has some vision impairments, she can still see plenty well enough to lead a very normal life!  She has been assessed by a Board Certified Ophthalmologist, and all of her records will be provided at the time of adoption.  Her future family will need to be prepared to have her eyes examined annually with a Veterinary Ophthalmologist.

Brighton is a DIVA!  She is silly, sweet, and adores people while also having quite a developed personality.  She loves to get the zoomies, snuggle, "talk to you" through play-growls, and be with you all the time.  She is housebroken & crate-trained, but could still use some work on a leash.  She does better after she has an established routine & route (for example, going on the same path each time.)  

Brighton tolerates other dogs, but she does not need them in her life to be happy, as she can be jealous when other dogs get attention.  She prefers to be the boss, and loves having a loyal subject that will dote upon her and let her wear the pants in the relationship.   Her ideal home would be as an only dog, or with a complacent, settled male dog that is indifferent about her diva lifestyle!  Brighton is fine with cats.

Brighton's favorite past times are napping on the couch, sunbathing, playing with her people, and being your best pal.

animal.description:
Cobalt is a happy, happy, sweet, adorable beagle mix. He weighs 24 lbs. Cobalt has the typical gorgeous beagle eyes and loving disposition. He gets along great with big and small dogs in his foster home, as well as the cats. He is still learning how to play with toys, but loves to hangout with his foster mom. He will follow his person all around the house and yard, just to stay close to you. He has a beautiful beagle baying alert when he catches the scent of a wayward squirrel in the backyard. Cobalt is potty trained.
 
Cobalt does have some special needs that will require a home where someone is available to provide care at ~3 hour intervals during the day. Cobalt came to ANLOL with a back injury and associated nerve damage. As a result, he has lost some of the use of his back legs. Crate rest and pain management have improved this and Cobalt gets around well, both walking and running (in a slightly wonky way). Cobalt also has paraphimosis from the nerve damage. He has undergone 2 surgeries for this, which improved it, but did not fully correct it. Thus he needs care every 2-3 hours to prevent further penile injury. Cobalt is a wonderful dog who truly deserves his new leash on life. 

Update: Cobalt has been diagnosed with pemphigus folliaceus, an autoimmune skin issue. He is responding well to treatment and appears to be headed into remission. It is a non-contagious condition which causes small lesions/hot spots on the skin. The original cause of his outbreak is unknown, and we do not know if it will flare up again after treatment is completed. 

Despite all of his health complications, Cobalt remains a sweet, loving beagle who loves attention, patrolling the yard for squirrels, and food. 

If you'd like more info on Cobalt and his special needs, please click "Adopt Me" to fill out an adoption survey. By filling out an adoption survey, we will be able to contact you to answer your questions about Cobalt and to help set up a meet and greet! (An adoption survey is not a commitment to adopt the pet you are interested in.)

animal.description:
IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THE FIRST STEP IS TO FILL OUT AN ADOPTION APPLICATION ON OUR WEBSITE AT:  
https://www.caninecastaways.org/adoption-application

NAME:  Princess
BREED:  Chihuahua
SEX:  female
COLOR:  tan
AGE:  7 yrs as of April 2020
WEIGHT:  6 lbs

PERSONALITY PROFILE
COULDN'T LIVE WITHOUT:  a snuggly blanket
PET PEEVES:  harness and leash, strangers visiting & small children
I NEED:   a fenced yard & a special diet
MY GOAL:  get all the treats
MY MOTTO:  Take a nap whenever you can!

NOTES FROM MY FOSTER FAMILY:
Princess is a very sweet girl but does need a special home that will be able to help her to feel safe and loved. She originally came to us from a bad situation a number of years ago. She was adopted out and returned to us recently. She will only be adopted out to a home with a securely fenced yard and with another small dog about her size that is outgoing and that will play with her.   She would not do well in a home with a larger dog.

When Princess returned to us, she desperately needed a dental and ended up losing all of her teeth.   At her age this is unusual but it has not bothered her at all.   Due to skin sensitivities, we did allergy testing on Princess and discovered that she is allergic to many things.   This testing recommended the protein in her diet be lamb or fish and definitely exclude rice, soybeans, corn, flax seed, barley, and liver.   We also learned that she has a major allergy to storage mites which are commonly found in dry dog food or treats; consequently, she must eat refrigerated, canned or frozen food.   

Princess is very apprehensive of strangers and and especially new situations.  Since she completely freaks out if you try to put a harness or leash on her, leash walks are not an option. This is not an isolated behavior and was one of the main reasons that she was returned to us.   A fenced yard is definitely a must.   Small children make her very nervous so she will need an adult ONLY home.   She also is much better with women so initially her primary caregiver should be female most likely to help her adjust quicker.  Like many dogs, Princess will need time to adjust to a new home and a person with the patience to make that happen.  When she moved to my house to foster it took her about 5 days to come out of her "safe place" in my spare bathroom but once she did she started making progress daily.  She loves food so that is always helpful since she started to be happy to see me around day 3 because I would give her treats and food.  She wants to love her person but just needs time to come around.  

As of this writing, she has been with me about 6 weeks.  She is doing great.  She lays up on the couch at night and she would be happy if I would pet her the entire time.  But once I stop, she lays down and dozes off.  She follows me around the house and sleeps next to my bed in a little dog bed with a fluffy blanket on it so she can snuggle under the covers if she wants.  She likes to play chase and would love a dog that will play with her that is about her size.  She seems to especially want to play with my Chihuahua more than my other dogs and I am assuming that is due to her being the same size.   She is honestly doing amazing.  I can pick her up with no issues now and she even snuggles in a bit.  She will take time but she is worth it.  She is a great girl that is going to make someone very happy as long as they give her the time she needs to feel safe and loved.  


MEDICAL NOTES: Princess had a small mass removed from her rear leg. Pathology revealed that it was a low grade mast cell tumor. She is doing well and her prognosis is good. Of course, there is always a possibility of recurrence with further treatment being needed but it is not expected.   Due to this unknown, if Princess is adopted and there is another tumor that pops up, Canine Castaways will treat the issue at our vet's office in Arcadia at our expense.
Princess also had been tested for allergies due to chronic skin issues. She is allergic to many things both environmental and food. As a result, she will need to remain on diet of lamb or fish as the main protein. The diet changes have made a big difference and she is not currently taking any medications.


If you are interested in adopting please complete our Adoption Application by copying and pasting the following link into your web browser: http://www.caninecastaways.org/adoption-application

For a full list of dogs we currently have for adoption use this link:  https://www.caninecastaways.org/adoptable-dogs


MEDICAL INFO:


The following has been or will be done for this dog...
- Basic Exam by Veterinarian
- Spayed or Neutered
- Heartworm Tested
- Placed on heartworm preventive
- Basic Bloodwork
- Urinalysis
- Microchipped
- Intestinal Parasite Exam and medication
- Vaccinations
- Placed on Flea preventive


ADOPTION DONATION: $250


This adoption donation helps to cover the vet expenses for this dog including heartworm preventive which is dispensed at the initial vet visit and then goes with the dog at adoption. All vet records will be provided to adopter. 

Visit us at www.caninecastaways.org

animal.description:
Hi Everyone!  I'm Milo and I thought I would take a moment and say "hi"!   As you can seen, I'm a handsome fellow and I'm a friendly boy too!  Unfortunately my first owners were not able to keep me, as they were moving and felt it was not the right situation for me, so that nice folks at NEBR came along to help me find a new forever home.
I'm about 1.5 years old, I love to play (with you or with another dog), and I'm smart too...I know lots of tricks - sit, down, high five, and I can learn lots more.  I'm a pretty athletic guy too, so if agility is your thing, I think I might be good at that too.  I walk well on a leash as long as I have my no pull harness on.  Of course, I'm crate trained and house trained, and I'm very loving (at least my foster mom says so).  I need a fenced in yard so that I can run and hopefully play with you. 
I have been neutered, am up to date with my vaccinations, am heartworm negative and on prevention and I'm microchipped too!
If you're looking for a sweet, loving and active boy, please take a moment and fill out an online application at www.nebrittanyresuce.org  Thank you and we look forward to hearing from you.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 5/23/2019
Reason for being in rescue: Owner release- Owner does not want.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Sasha came to us grossly underweight and with heartworms. Her foster mom has been working with her and her weight is back up to normal. Sasha is being treated with the soft kill method of heartworm treatment (monthly Heartguard only) and is now testing Heartworm negative.
Weight: est 45 lbs
Height: est 22 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $300

Fence needed? Yes without exception. 4' chain link is fine. She is not a climber although she likes to see if she can find the moles in the yard. A fenced in yard is not for you to leave your dog outside in it all day with no protection and with no human interaction. It is your dog's safe space for romping, playing and being the free spirited creature all dogs were meant to be - with you right there enjoying the time together with your canine best friend.

What kind of home would be best for me? Sasha has came a long way since coming to CPR and going to foster with our groomer, Amanda. She is a lot of dog, with a lot of energy, intelligence and curiosity. The husky breed is not for the faint of heart although with the right owner, she will thrive. She has with our groomer, a very experienced dog owner. Sasha needs a home with no children under the age of 15. She has a strong personality and a can be a bit of a challenge. Her previous owner did not give her the structure and discipline she needed so we're correcting all of that.

Sasha would do best in a home where there are no small dogs - it's not that she's mean or aggressive, but she is large and she likes her personal space. She co-exists now with several small dogs who are clingy/spoiled and don't know boundaries and she routinely corrects them and tells them to get out of her space. She simply does not want to share her home with little, irritating ankle biters. Large dogs are another subject all together. Her best friend is Dawson, an extra large shepherd mix who is also up for adoption. They would love to go together if you want two. They romp, play, run and wrestle and have a grand old time. With a dog her energy and size levels, she is an amazing companion dog.

What is my personality like? Intelligent - inquisitive - a little bit naughty and a little bit nice! Sasha loves people, and loves when anyone has food or treats! Trash can mining is a favorite past time. Sasha can not be left alone when her foster mom goes out. Unsupervised in the house, all that intelligence and inquisitive nature comes full force and she will get into something. You won't be happy with what she finds to get into.

If Sasha was a human, she may have ended up in military school to learn that it's okay to say Yes Sir and Yes Ma'am and that discipline and routine are good life arrangements that give you confidence. She also needs someone who is experienced in basic training and would love to be involved in a dog sport like nosework or weight pull. Sasha still has some quirks and needs to be consistently and gently reminded that she does not rule the house. Sasha is crate trained, walks well on a leash and has the most stunning blue eyes you've ever seen.

Sasha loves to be outside, so exercise is a must for her. She is pretty good about strangers also, she is just a very curious dog and wants to sniff and smell to see where you have been!

How do I act when I first meet new people? Friendly - she greets people nicely and politely. She's not a run up and jump on you kind of girl. She allows loving and petting but she does not need it unless she is trying to get you up so she can go out - she's definitely a morning girl and she's all over you. She is not a stuffed animal to be squeezed on. She has her own dance space and wants you to stay in your space and she will stay in hers. If you invade her space, she will tell you she doesn't like it by air snapping at you. She also can be food aggressive at times with other dogs. She has never been aggressive with humans but her foster mom also does not take food away once it's given. Remember, Sasha was grossly underweight when coming to CPR .At some time in her life, food was not guaranteed. She remembers. She takes treats with a lot of enthusiasm and you have to watch your hands! However, she eats a reasonable pace and does not bolt her food.

Other tips and tidbits: Est Birthdate 5/23/2017.

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

Yoshi is a young male Akita weighing approximately 80 lbs. He is very handsome and still growing. During the first few months of his life he only had limited exposure to the world outside of his previous home. Yoshi is highly intelligent and wants someone who will stimulate his mind and teach him new skills. It takes him a little bit of time to warm up to strangers and get used to them. Because of his cautious demeanor, he would do best in a calm and consistent environment with a good human leader to make him feel safe and help him develop into a more well rounded canine. He would do best with a breed experienced home that respects his space and positively encourages him as he learns what this world has to offer. He is confident and a happy easy keeper, that loves exploring. He would thrive with someone who believes in him as he learns what being a loved and accepted doggy is like. No children under 18 please, but he seems to be friendly with other social female dogs his own size!!Visit Akita Ranch 28930 Ellis Ave, Romoland, CA, Open 10-5 daily BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. animal.description:
My name is Karma. My original name here at shelter is Zita. I was here back in 2015 because I was dumped in the play yard here at the shelter with 3 of my puppies. we all got adopted out at that time. Now I am back and looking for a family who would take good care of me and give me the attention I need. I am very sweet when I am out of the kennel. I know I may not show it but I do deep down. animal.description:
Ranger is a highly intelligent 1 year old Red Heeler mix with an incredible knack for learning. He will flourish in an environment where he is given a lot of one-on-one time, consistent structure and continued training. His early life got off to a rough start, and as a result he sometimes experiences “stranger danger” with new people and is fearful of them. He is:

•	House trained
•	Leash trained
•	Crate trained
•	Basic obedience and recall trained
•	Good with medium to large female dogs and submissive males
•	Enjoys car rides
•	Not good with cats
•	Very high energy

He will do well with a knowledgeable alpha owner and is going to tightly bond with his human. He loves to play fetch, go for hikes and swim. Ranger is a high challenge rating companion but in the right hands will be an unwaveringly loyal and loving friend. He needs a special person who will be patient as he builds the confidence to interact with this great big world.

Ranger is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, and heartworm negative. 

For more information about Ranger or our shelter please call us at (830) 693-0569 or visit our website at highlandlakescaninerescue.org
