animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Name - Opal

Age - Young Adult

Weight - approx. 60lbs

Special Needs - Yes. Opal is deaf. She also has a "wonky" front right leg. This is a growth deformity. At this time, amputation is not recommended as it does not prohibit her from running or playing normally

Other dogs - Enjoys going on pack walks. Recommended as the only dog in the home. Supervised play dates OK

Cats - No cats - will chase

Kids - Loves children. However older children in the home is recommended due to her size and strength - her tail is like a whip and she's such a happy girl, the tail is almost always wagging. We do not want a young child being hurt accidentally

Background - abandoned on the side of the road. She was adopted briefly but it was not the right dynamic with the resident dog and so she was returned to ITP after about a month

Crate trained - She is great in her crate. Just make sure she has plenty of bones to chew and she will hardly make a peep. She will even put herself in the crate when she's ready to rest

Leash trained - Opal is trained on the slip leash, martingale collar and e-collar. We use the vibration setting ONLY for recall when in the backyard. She occasionally gets overly excited and will grab the leash while walking - her fosters are working on correcting this behavior

Housebroken - Yes. She has not had any accidents and will go to the door when needing to go out

Eating Habits - Not picky at all. Does use a slow feeder bowl to keep her from wolfing her food down. Must be given a metal bowl, as she will chew a plastic one. Very treat motivated

Commands known - Opal is trained with hand signals (sit, stay, come) and with the vibration collar for recall

Car rides - Rides pretty well in the car

Bath time - Opal loves water! She will try to bite the hose if possible. She enjoys being pampered

Affectionate - Very affectionate. She's affection motivated almost as much as being treat motivated. She just loves cuddling and snuggling up next to you

Activity level - Opal is on the higher energy level in the sense that she has bursts of energy. She'll play play play for 30 minutes or so then crash for a few hours. Then get up and run laps around the yard. A house with a yard is preferred

Play style - Opal will entertain herself with toys in the yard. She'll run laps and throw toys up in the air. She just loves tug and could do that for hours. She's incredibly strong though so we have developed a way to play with her appropriately with the help of a behavorist

Bad habits - Opal doesn't really have bad habits in the normal sense. But because of her disability, she can be a bit more challenging than a "normal" dog. She can be stubborn and is very strong so she'll need a strong handler, especially while out on walks. She is reactive to cars - we're not sure exactly why, maybe because she can't hear them and they "sneak up" on her. She will bark at them and in her over-excitement bite at the leash. We are working on desensitizing her and correcting this behavior

Redeeming qualities - Opal is just a happy-go-lucky dog for the most part. She's just genuinely so sweet and lovable

Best feature - Her pretty green eyes and her cute little pout

What Foster Mom/Dad wants you to know -
"Opal is a special dog. Not only because she is special needs but because she is just so loving. She just adores people and you can see her face light up when she looks at you. She still has puppy energy and will entertain you with her playful antics. Watching her do zoomies around the yard is hilarious. Just a warning - she does snore but it's so funny to walk in the room and the other dogs are barking or the kids are yelling and she's just curled up snoring away. She doesn't really have a care in the world - she's just happy and ready to play. She loves to snuggle and just loves when you love on her. She is very strong and we've had to adapt to how we handler her in light of her deafness. She is incredibly smart though and really is eager to please so she picks up on new training pretty quickly. I would love to see her be adopted into a home that could provide the ongoing structure and exercise she needs. And of course, a home to give her unconditional love because she really does deserve it

Please consider sponsoring Opal with either a one-time or monthly tax-deductible donation. Your donation will help It's The Pits with day-to-day care, including food, vaccinations, flea treatment, treats and toys. Click on the Sponsor This Pet link above to make your donation today. Thank you!Complete an Adoption Application!

animal.description:
***  Please read entire post ***

The first step is to complete an adoption application via our website, www.cofas.org (click on Adoption Information, Available Dogs, Dog Adoption Application). All of our adoptable animals are in foster homes. 

We do not arrange meet and greets until we have an approved application on hand.

Once we have reviewed your application we will get back to you as soon as possible. 
We have the right to decline an application if it is not a good fit for that particular animal. 
 
___

Not sure why we still have this beauty in our system?!  
Viola is just an adorable little shorty girl.  She came from a rural shelter where she was picked up as a stray and was in pretty bad shape. 

Beautiful Viola is looking for the perfect home.  
That perfect home has a fenced in yard for her to run and play in.  She would enjoy a family that is home a lot with a quieter household.  
She loves to snuggle with you on the couch.    But not saying she does not like to be outside or go for walks....she loves her family time.
Apartment life would probably not suit her.

It is apparent that little Viola had a rough life being used as a breeder and obviously kept locked up in a cage based on the soars that covered her body and the condition she was in when we got her.  She is happy and healthy now.  In spite her sad past she is extremely sweet and just loves people.   

We would really like for to be the only dog so she can get all the attention she deserves.  Previous adoption trials with current dogs did not go well....not her fault. 

She is great with people of all ages but we are recommending a home with  children 8 years and older.  She is good with cats that really like dogs.  Her current foster home has two 'dog proof' cats that just love her and she is very good with them.

Viola is estimated at about 5 years old and weighs about 50lbs.
Viola does have a functional heart murmur but has been checked out thoroughly by our vet and has no clinical signs of any issues related.

Her pictures do make her look a lot bigger than she is (she is very short and stout).  She is just adorable!

Viola is up to date on her heart worm, flea/tick preventatives, spayed, up to date on vaccinations, micro chipped and had a dental cleaning.
 

Any questions about Viola, please contact her foster Mom at kittypuppylv@aol.com



__________________________________________

Not yet ready to adopt? You can sponsor a pet now to help pay for medical expenses, special diets, toys and treats, emergency medical care, etc., to provide for him or her during foster care. Our adoption fee rarely covers our expenses, so any size donation is appreciated! Click the Sponsor Me! logo to make a donation. You can also donate by check or Paypal by visiting our website at www.cofas.org 


 All of our dogs are fostered in our homes so we know their temperaments. They are spayed or neutered, up to date on shots, de-wormed, heartworm tested (and treated if necessary), and on flea and heartworm prevention. Our adoption fee begins at $195.00 for all of our dogs and puppies. Our goal is to match our animals to the best home possible. Please email info@cofas.org for more information. You can also fill out an application at www.cofas.org

**COURTESY POST for Orphans of the Storm Animal Shelter**

Thea, short for Theadora, is a beautiful and intelligent 3 year old gal who is staying with us for training and socialization. Thea is a very playful young lady that loves running off leash and exploring the great outdoors with her fellow foster pups. Her favorite game to play is fetch and she does the cutest little hops when chasing after the tennis balls. She also enjoys going on nice, long walks but refers running in the yard much more. Thea is a rockstar at obedience and picks up on new tricks fast, especially when she is guaranteed some tasty treats as a reward! She is potty trained, walks well on leash, knows her training commands, does well with most dogs, and is just so much fun to be around.

Thea's ideal owner is someone who has breed/dog experience due to her nervousness around strangers. She needs a confident leader who will be her voice and say, "please do not pet," and will not force her to meet new people as she prefers to get affection and hang out with her family only. Thea also needs an owner who will be patient with her as it takes time for her to warm up, but once she does, she is your most loyal and trusting friend! Overall, Thea would do best with a family who is willing to continue her training and learn alongside her, and in an all-adult home with NO CATS and NO CHILDREN.

Contact (847) 338-3252 or email info@redemptionroadinc.org if you're interested in meeting the lovely Miss Thea! 1/27/21 10:12 PM

animal.description: Meet Tony! He arrived as a stray and was so afraid of all the new things at first. This gentle giant was lucky enough to land a fantastic foster home when the shelter closed in March. Tony's foster mom says that he is all love and no bark! He has the best smile and yes, cuddling is his specialty. Tony is low energy inside the home, but he loves to go on walks and explore! He enjoys sniffing everything... scent games are one of his favorite activities. Tony can have a bit of stranger danger when meeting new people. This means he needs slow, proper intros a few times before he feels safe with you. And that's okay! We don't know what Tony's life was like before we met him but he needs some time to be able to trust you. And once you are in with Tony, you are IN! Tony's ideal home would be low-traffic and adult only. He needs to be the only pet for now. Tony is house trained, quiet, and does well in apartment settings. He asked that we tell you that he loves to go on car rides, especially when one of the stops is for an ice-cream cone! Tony comes with the full support of the Orange Dot Crew (a volunteer advocacy group at Austin Animal Center) and will go home with a crate, all kinds of goodies and enrichment items, as well as a free training voucher. To contact my foster, email AACADOPTABLEDOGS@GMAIL.COM

animal.description: Hershey is a sweet boy who loves human attention. He is an active dog who would do best with an active owner to keep him busy with walks, hiking, etc. He will whine when he doesn't have enough to do (Mom! I'm boooored!!). He is fully potty trained and will go in the kennel when asked but has also been trustworthy when left out. He likes to play with other dogs his size with proper introductions. Hershey is not a fan of felines, so we would recommend a home without cats as he is too tempted to chase them. Hershey is likely a great candidate for some organized dog training classes to keep that active mind challenged. Classes are a great opportunity for a dog and owner to learn together and practice at home. Hershey needs a 6-ft fenced yard as he does enjoy the outdoors and having the opportunity to sniff and run freely around the yard (no apartment living for this boy). Hershey is a Chocolate Lab/mix, weighs 62 lbs and was born approximately 12-14-15. He is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, given flea/tick preventative, dewormed. Hershey had life-saving treatment for heartworm disease. He will need to remain on heartworm preventative for life, as is recommended for ALL dogs, and retested in 6 months to ensure he is heartworm free. Adoption fee is $250 to help offset the many expenses we have for vetting costs. We rely strictly on adoption fees and donations to continue to save the lives of orphaned & abandoned pets; 100% goes towards their care.

animal.description:
Meet Mina! Mina is a 6 year old blind pitty-type girl.

Mina came to us suffering from severe glaucoma. She has had necessary surgery to remove both eyes.

Despite this, Mina is an incredibly happy, spunky girl, and a staff favorite. She is currently residing in a foster home post-surgery. Potential adopters should have blind dog experience, or be willing to give her a proper adjustment period. She is still learning to master stairs and is apprehensive in new environments, but adjusts fairly quickly. She should go into a home with either no kids, or with kids old enough to know not to startle her. She is doing ok with other canines in foster but can get overstimulated if not monitored, so would be better with a laid-back male canine sibling, or as a spoiled only child. She was non-reactive when tested with cats. She does have some occasional anxiety when left alone, but crates very nicely when necessary.

animal.description: Mako is a 12 year old male mixed breed. He weighs 96 pounds. Mako is a resource guarder which means that he can be possessive of both treats and toys with humans. He gives plenty of appropriate warnings to let you know that he isn't fond of sharing. Mako was transferred from a county facility so we do not have information about his previous household. Mako can be friendly with other dogs although he is very fond of humping and needs a dog friend or friends that can give him appropriate corrections when they've had enough. Dogs that are not fond of being humped or that are prone to overcorrections may not make good dog friends for Mako. We always recommend a meet and greet with any resident dogs. If you are unsure about your pup's feelings on this type of play, our staff can help by supervising a meet and greet and explaining the behaviors they observe. We do not know if the resource guarding issue with treats and toys extends to his dog friends as we have not introduced toys during any dog interactions. Mako has been on a slumber party during which he was rude to the residents cats and chased them throughout the house. At this time we don't believe Mako would do well living with cats. We have no information on how Mako behaves around children. However, due to Mako's resource guarding we would recommend him only with older children that are able to read and respect his communication about sharing (or rather not sharing) his toys and treats. We always recommend a meet and greet with any children in the household or children that visit often, such as grandkids. Please call for more information or to make an appointment to meet Mako. (Updated 1/30/21).

My name is Blair, glad to see you visited my page.

When I was younger, someone dumped me on the side of the road.  A very nice older lady took me in and fostered me until the kind hearted Lucie's folks could fit me in.

Ready to go??  I am full energy and ready to run and play!!!  I just love kids because they tend run and play like me!  Oh yeah, I'm treat motivated :) :) :)

I love playing with toys but haven't quite mastered the whole retrieving thing  ;)

I would be an awesome family dog or one for an active adult who enjoys running or hiking.

At the moment, I am enjoying rough play with my kennelmates, so if you have another dog who enjoys that as well, that would be really swell.  I'm ok by myself too.

I am leash and crate trained.

Hope to see you soon!


*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description:
Intake date 5 November 2019 . 2 year old neutered male border collie (mix?). Meet Bart! ? Bart is a border collie (mix?) who came to us from a shelter partner where he had been picked up stray. ? Bart would love a fun job, and lots of games and play, as well as a fun pack mate or two. ? Bart is bright, eager, and willing. He can be silly and playful, enjoys playing with other dogs, and is a real pleasure to be around - and he is super handsome ? ? Bart will do best in an active home that understands that rules and parameters are part of the game. Bart would love to become someone's walking or hiking partner - he is very athletic and would enjoy becoming a training partner for games such as agility. ? Bart is crate trained, and is housebroken in his foster home. Bart enjoys training, and would enjoy a playful, confident dog partner, as well as a human partner ready to bend his brain. ? Bart's history with children and cats is unknown. He is located in Maryland. ? For information on adoption, please visit our website at mabcr.org. Please be sure to read our FAQs prior to application. #mabcr #rightdogrighthome #MABCRBart @ MABCR . Picked up stray, we pulled him when no one claimed him. Bart can be super bouncy and silly when excited -- he walks perfectly on leash until he is excited, then all bets are off! So far, Bart is great with other dogs (although he has a rougher play style than your typical border collie), and has been excellent with people. Bart will do best in a home that enjoyed training and exercise, and doing fun things with their dog. Bart is crate trained, appears to understand housebreaking, and will need work on leash walking. For information on adoption, our FAQ, and our application, please see our website at mabcr.org.
.
PLEASE READ our procedures for adoption prior to making inquiry regarding this dog. If you are looking for additional photos, video, or information on this dog, you will likely find that by searching our facebook page for their photo/description album.
.
Please see our main website at www.mabcr.org for more information regarding the adoption of this or any dog from our rescue. 
.
Please note that while this dog is currently available, any dog on our site may have an adoption pending and may not be available to you at this time. The same dog may later become available if the adoption falls through. 
.
Our website www.mabcr.org will give you details on our adoption procedures as well as an application for adoption. An application must be submitted prior to 'matching' an adopter with a dog as all dogs do not fit into all homes. We pride ourselves in our adoption process, we take the time to get to know our adopters so that we can place a dog with them that they can enjoy for years to come.
.
Please understand that we will not discuss dogs with individual adopters until after the application process is completed.
.
Our rescue does not have a public facility, therefore there are no visiting hours. Appointments to visit with the available dogs are made after the application process has been completed by our staff.  
.
To assist any dog within the MABCR organization, please consider making a donation to the general fund or to the medical fund. All dogs coming into our rescue are fully vetted (s/n and core vaccines) prior to adoption.
.
Rescuing animals is quite expensive. If you are unable to adopt, but would like to help this, or any other animal in our system, please consider a sponsorship donation. 
For information on our sponsorship program, please contact Sarah at SLR@mabcr.org. 
.
Thank you for your interest in Mid-Atlantic Border Collie Rescue.

animal.description:
In case you don't know what LOVE looks like...

Houston, TX area: Joey was rescued off the streets by a FPA volunteer. This poor boy was living out there for a very long time and was in horrific condition. Joey had been hit by a car (not sure how long ago) and his pelvis now twisted resulted in his back-left leg to dangle. He also had multiple skin and eye infections, he was also heartworm positive not neutered and was skin and bones.

Joey has come such a long way, he has been neutered, had entropion surgery and was on medication for ear and skin infections and has been through heartworm treatment. The vet looked at Joey's leg and pelvis and unfortunately there was so much arthritis that surgery would not help him. Joey is now taking Cosequin to help ease his discomfort. Joey is estimated to be 7 years old.

Joey is house and crate trained, he does well with other dogs and is a happy boy! Joey is a toy terminator as he loves to destuff toys! He also enjoys chewing on bones too! Joey loves to be outside in nice weather or run around the yard with a toy in his mouth. One of his favorite things to do is to get a belly rub! Joey also likes to snuggle on the couch, he loves to be loved on! Joey is looking for a family that will adore him like his foster Mom does and will love him through his senior years. Joey weighs 45 lbs.

Message or Email: forgottenpetadvocates@yahoo.com to meet this Gorgeous boy!

animal.description:
Tara is a beautiful sweet girl, 6 year old, 60 pound Labrador Mix. Tara has come from a timid girl to begging for belly pets and ear scratches. Having been kenneled when young, she is slow to warm up with new people, but is playful and loving with patience. Young children with sudden movement and loud sounds can still startle her, but once she is used to someone, she wants to please. Recommended to NOT have small animals or cats around her. She has been friends with a few dogs in her past, yet she is also territorial … so maybe a calm male dog for a companion (advance visit recommended).
 
She needs a yard for toy chasing and a 6 foot privacy fence required as she can jump something shorter. She appears to be housebroken, mostly from being let out in the yard and neighborhood walks 2-3 times per day, but she does not know how to ask to go out, so walks are a must. She is good on a leash as long as loud noises don’t scare her. 
 
She is very smart and naturally trainable when you show approval or disapproval, even without using treats. She has reached at least beginner level of: sit, lie down, hold (wait before going through the door of home and car), up (sofa or car), okay! (come through the door or out of the car), this way (when her nose wants to lead her astray on a walk), and “Tara, come” has her show up with her calm, slow walk.

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier
Gender: Male
Estimated Date of Birth: February 7, 2012
Size: 85 lbs
Location: Buford, GA

RESCUING LINKIN

Saldy, Linkin, formerly known as Shrek, had to be rescued from a rescue when a nonprofit rescue organization was raided in South Georgia. There were 70+ dogs on the property in horrific conditions. Shrek was living in a crate, had not been neutered, was a little thin, and infested with fleas. We had a foster step up and we were able to take him into our program on 2/6/2020. Linkin has no teeth and was treated for a double ear infection and skin infection from a severe flea dermatitis. It's hard to imagine what he has endured, but it's only uphill from here!

ABOUT LINKIN

Linkin is really enjoying that fostered life, outside the confinements of just a crate. Linkin is house trained and crate trained. He is good with other dogs and even his picky, canine foster-sister loves him! Due to his past neglect and lack of food, Linkin does not share food with other dogs and needs to be fed separately so he just eats his meals in his crate. He does well with kids, but is not suited for a home with cats. He is a low energy, lounge around, Netflix-and-Chill kinda guy. He always wants to be with his people and is a true velcro-dog as he will follow you from room to room. Next to his people, his favorite thing is food - any and all of the food! He already knows the commands sit, shake, and wait. Linkin is a sweet, affectionate boy who biggest joys are napping, car rides, snacks, and cuddling.

Linkin loves his people and is very loyal so he would really love someone who is home a lot. He sleeps most of the day, but follows his foster mom around the house, never letting her out of his sight. He can go on short walks, but doesn't enjoy being outside for long periods of time. He is looking for a forever family to lounge around with that will give him all the belly rubs and attention he lacked for so long. His past life has somehow left him with chronic Emphysema/COPD so his lungs have a lot of scar tissue from a previous unknown trauma. The cough he's had since we rescued him has gotten significantly better, but it's still lingering. Our vet seems to think Linkin may have some kind of immune deficiency due to his skin flare ups and chronic respiratory issues, but we are working on finding what works for him.

Photo Album of Linkin: https://www.facebook.com/pg/FriendsToTheForlornPitbullRescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=2984198311638315

Follow Linkin on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/whatapitty4them/

Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

Meet Cheyenne, a 7 year old black and white Pitbull with unusually striking markings. She is 48 lb and stands 18 inches. Cheyenne is very loving and sweet, but unfortunately hasn't had much training. She has been kept outside only and hasn't had house training. She is quite strong and active, so might do best in a home without very young children as she tends to jump. She has not shown aggression, but would do best in a home without cats or smaller dogs. She has done all right with dogs her size or larger.  She would do best with adopters who have experience with active dogs who need some attention and patient but firm training. She has a lot of love to give and would really treasure a new forever home, with active adopters who will give her some exercise and playtime. If you would cherish Cheyenne as your new canine companion and family member, please apply at yvpr.org/adoptions.


An application must be filled out and accepted before a meet can be set up. If accepted, you will hear from us within 72 hours. You will have the opportunity to ask questions before you meet the pet; an adoption may or may not happen at that time. We do adopt outside the Yakima area IF you are able to come to Yakima to pick up your adopted pet.  We do not have a kennel facility; all of our pets are in foster homes. Therefore, meets and adoptions take place at either our office or at a place chosen by the foster.   If a pet has 'pending' beside its name, an adoption is imminent. Please fill out an application anyway because adoptions don't always go through. Your application will be kept on file for 30 days in case you find another pet you'd like to apply for.  Thanks for thinking adoption and Good Luck!

animal.description:
Originally from Mississippi, it was evident by her reactions to people and situations, she had experienced trauma and lived a life of uncertainty. Her wait for the right forever home has been long, due to her very specific needs. 

Molly's needs are a lifelong commitment and will need constant management. She struggles with fear aggression towards new people. Her introductions are done at a very slow pace, with her comfort level as priority. She must meet any interested adopter several times before any interactions due to her fear. You will not see her true personality at first meet but she is worth every bit of extra time and patience. Once that breakthrough showing trust and confidence happens, you will see she is a wonderful, loyal dog who will accept you. 

Molly is a 5 year old hound mix, weighs 58 lbs., is spayed, current on vaccinations and completely housebroken. She enjoys walking, playing and quiet car rides. Molly gets along great with most dogs and would enjoy having a compatible dog sibling to help build her confidence. She is very intelligent, a champ at commands and very eager to please. Molly is very food motivated and is an expert at nose work, quickly searching out any hidden treats. She sits patiently in her "place" and awaits the "ok" command to find the goods! Without having to be prompted, she will sit, lie down or give her paw for rewards and positive words of praise. 

She requires a quiet, calm ADULT ONLY home (preferably with only one to two people). Molly is not suited for large gatherings of people. No children and no cats. 

A quiet home in a rural area is best. She is not suited for city/suburb living or for any apartment/condo complex living. 

We know her needs are very specific. She deserves to succeed in life and be a happy pup. We are committed to finding her the home and person she is meant to be with.

We kindly ask, IF YOU HAVE QUESTIONS regarding Molly, PLEASE EMAIL:

 adoption@popememorialcvhs.org

******************************************

AHow To Adopt a Pet

We are currently offering adoptions by appointment only, due to the Coronavirus. The Adoption Center remains closed to drop-in visitors.

The process to schedule an appointment begins with the submission of an application, which can be found on our website. Once the application is approved, we will reach out to you to schedule an appointment. Please bear with us, the new process has slowed our response time.

If you do not see an animal that would fit into your home, we highly recommend checking our website weekly as new animals may become available. We do not offer a waitlist for specific breeds, types, etc. 

As always, adoptions are first come, first serve, meaning the applicant who is approved first gets their choice of available appointment times and thus his/her choice of animals to meet and adopt. We are not able to extend holds on any animals at this time, so we ask interested adopters to make their adoption decision during their appointment and be prepared to take their new pet home with you.

The easiest way to communicate with us with any questions is via email to: 

adoption@popememorialcvhs.org


No phone calls please - Submit an application here ----> 

https://popememorialcvhs.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
4/22/2020 update - our adoption area is limited to UT, NV, ID, OR, WA and MT with a home visit.  If you are outside of this area please do a search for your local GSP/GWP/Pointer rescue group.

--------

I'm MAYLAN!  I'm a gorgeous GSP girl with lots of energy and a happy nature.  I love everyone and everything (except cats).  I'm very, very smart and acclimate quickly with the right people who know my breed.

My approx. DOB is 1/21/2016.  In at tall girl at 24" at my withers and weigh 45 lbs.  I'm lanky because of my activity level.  I'm loving my new life and ability to interact with lots of people and other dogs.

My foster mom just loves me.  I go hiking in the mountains with her and am great relaxing at home.  She thinks I'm the Best Dog Ever!

--------

GENERAL APPLICATION NOTES:

We strongly urge adopters to consider a male canine companion if they already have a female GSP/GWP. We get asked several times a year to take in one member of a 2-female GSP family because there are control issues between their girls that result in pretty ferocious fights. Interestingly that never happens among males. Go figure.

Dogs under 2 years of age need to go to a home with another well-socialized canine companion of a similar size (when grown) and within a few years of the pup’s age. This is how they maintain and continue their learning/socialization process. Socialization outside the home is important but doesn’t replace the in-home learning that is so important as the pup ages. https://www.facebook.com/ UtahsPerfectPointers/posts/ 1460968517254816

Most older dogs aren’t interested in having a puppy incessantly chewing on it and demanding attention. If you live outside of the Salt Lake area and are sure that your older dog just loves puppies, please arrange a visit at your home with a 2-4 month old pup for a couple of hours and make sure that your older dog feels the same way about this that you do. Please video the interactions and send it to us.

Just a word of caution........ most pointer types need jobs. Otherwise they're not good pets. They need to be able to utilize their brains and no amount of exercise without a "work" or "thinking" component is adequate. The job doesn't need to be hunting. But it does need to be something that satisfies their genetic predispositions - nose work, agility, tracking, dock diving, etc. The job cannot just be obedience. If they can't use their innate senses they're just never going to be the dog you want for the next 15 years.

A physical fence is required for most of our dogs.

As far as other breeds go, the pointers are generally good with most other breeds with the exception of the Arctic breeds and bulldogs. I'm not sure why, but if there's ever an altercation in daycare between a UPP dog and another dog, it's generally one of those two breeds. It may be the difference in energy levels. It may be some ancient behavior we know nothing about...... Not sure.

Utah's Perfect Pointers is a very small rescue group and doesn't have the resources to adopt to states except for the ones noted above. If you are interested in adopting a GSP please contact the closest groups below. Keep in mind that not all of their dogs may be listed on their sites.

animal.description:
Zirkel is a 1 year old female Bernese Mountain Dog rescued as a puppy from a puppy mill on 02/22/20 with what they thought was a heart murmur.

She is available for adoption but will need a home who accepts her medical condition and will follow up with her future medical care as instructed.

We had our veterinarian evaluate her and then she was referred to The Ohio State University Veterinary Medical Center

03/11/20 The Ohio State University Veterinary Medical Center Cardiology Department diagnosed our little girl with a Ventricular Septal Defect (VSD). While these can sometimes be repaired and some cause no serious problems, her problem is complicated by some other abnormalities (thanks to puppy mills and inbreeding). 
While we don’t have a long term prognosis, it is possible that she will live a somewhat normal and healthy life for the next 5-6 years, but she will need to have a follow-up echo done every 6 months to assess how she is growing. 

We decided to keep her on medical hold for 6 months until the next echocardiogram.

09/14/20 check up from The Ohio State University Veterinary Medical Center
Zirkel has a complex combination of congenital heart defects that makes assessment for long term prognosis difficult. Her long term prognosis is guarded overall. Luckily, she is not symptomatic for any of her cardiac disease at this time and appears to be on overall decent health. Zirkel had slight enlargement of two chambers of her heart (right atrium, left ventricle), but there is no reason to put Zirkel on any medications for her heart disease at this time. Zirkel will require life long monitoring of her heart with echocardiograms. Her next echocardiogram is due 03/14/2021

Despite her heart problems Zirkel is a fun loving girl! She is doing well in her foster home and gets along with the other dogs in the home.

If you think you would be interested, please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.luv4k9s.org. Select Available Dogs then scroll down to application, complete and submit. 

A physical secure fence attached to the residence is a requirement to adopt a dog from our rescue. Invisible fence doesn't meet this requirement. No exceptions.

Our adoption area is primarily OHIO. We will consider KENTUCKY, AND INDIANA AND CERTAIN AREAS OF MICHIGAN, WEST VIRGINIA, AND PENNSYLVANIA. 

WE DO NOT SHIP NOR ARRANGE TRANSPORTS.

THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. 

IT CAN TAKE AT LEAST 2 WEEKS TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION SOMETIMES LONGER DEPENDING ON VOLUNTEER AVAILABILITY AND NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS RECEIVED SO PLEASE BE PATIENT. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters must understand that each home is different, and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. 
Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for:
1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (ex. a 4 month old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break) 
2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old, to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise.
3.) Socialization: The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home.
4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded tenfold, for years to come.
Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy. Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time consuming and can be expensive. All Dogs Require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well-trained, well socialized dog is more than worth the effort put in to get them there. 

Our adoption fee includes spay/neuter, routine shots, rabies, worming, microchipped, heartworm testing and they are on monthly preventative. Visit our website www.luv4k9s.org for more information and to complete an application.

animal.description:
Charity found her way to Maricopa Animal Care and Control as a stray.

Charity is a 9 year old labrador retriever/ Pitbull Terrier mix weighing 55 pounds. She is a pretty darn near perfect dog! She has the sweetest personality and gives great hugs and kisses.

Charity is great with all adults and children, but because of her size, children over 5 years are best. She likes to be with you and is happy to keep you warm while cuddling on the couch watching TV. She sleeps quietly in her bed through the night.

For an older dog, Charity has lots of energy! She loves taking walks and does great on the leash. She also loves car rides to anywhere! She is a great companion to run errands or take on road trips. You will find her with her head daintily at the car window sniffing everything that passes by—always with a smile on her face. Charity is a happy dog with a tail that doesn’t stop wagging.

Charity also loves her time in the yard playing with her favorite blue shark toy or chasing the pole wand around until she is out of breath. Then she settles back inside on the couch for a nap.

Charity gets along with the cat in her foster home although she does get jealous when she doesn’t get all the attention! She is picky about her canine companions so she must be the only dog in the home.

Charity is housetrained and knows the commands of sit, shake and stay. She’s pretty great at catching treats too.

The ideal home for this pretty girl would be a family that is familiar with big dogs. Someone that has a yard to exercise and play. A family that is able to walk and/ or play with her several times a day. And most of all, someone that can look into those big, brown eyes and say, “ I’ll love you forever”…..and Charity will love you forever right back.

Do you have room in your heart and home for Charity?

animal.description:
Breed: Cattle Dog mix
Sex: Neutered Male
DOB: ~10/22/2017
Weight: 45 lbs
Energy Level: Medium
Personality Type: Wallflower, Extremely Smart, Food-Motivated, Introverted, Timid, Needs A Job
History: Transferred from another shelter
Ideal Home: Fenced in yard (privacy fence preferred), no kids, no other pets. Calm home without a lot of traffic or loud neighbors. No apartments.
Special Info: LOVES training, knows lots of commands! Loves puzzle feeder toys. Great walking/running partner! Housebroken! Please note, Beau's adopter will receive one FREE session with our trainer, included in his adoption fee.

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
**Please read entire bio before emailing or applying. Thank you!**
 
Bella is an 11-month-old, purebred, female, German Shepherd Dog who is available for adoption. She has come through a very long journey since she arrived in our care.
 
At 8 weeks old, Bella was hit by a car and surrendered to our rescue. What followed has been 10 months of hard work and dedication by her foster parents, caregivers and volunteers. Bella has had extensive medical and rehabilitation at Blue Pearl. She had an MRI and, most recently, full body X-rays to ensure nothing is hindering her from reaching her goal to be 100% mobile on her own.
 
Fortunately, Bella has never met a person she didn’t love. She is incredibly friendly and loving. Bella loves to greet visitors at her foster home and at the park or on walks. She also loves other dogs she meets, so a home with other male dogs or no other dogs would suit her well. Bella also loves car rides.
 
Bella is at the point where she can stand on all four legs and is upright on all four legs for walking for short periods (as seen in the videos). She will need a dedicated home to continue with her down this path. Bella will provide her new home with tons of love and kisses and devotion. It is the right time to find that perfect home for her.

If you would like to adopt Bella, please visit our website and apply today!

https://www.washingtongsd.org/adopt

Are you following us on Facebook?  Our most recent updates, rescue animals and volunteer opportunities are posted to our Facebook page:

https://www.facebook.com/WashingtonGermanShepherdRescue

Opt to Adopt! and give me a chance to love you! Copy/paste this link to your browser to fill out an adoption application for me at: www.ahimsarescuefoundation.  Please note that you cannot be considered to adopt a pet until the on line adoption application has been received.  
Thank you for your interest in adopting a pet from Ahimsa Rescue Foundation.  Our goal is to unite pets and people to form loving and lasting families. We take into consideration both the family’s lifestyle and the individual personalities of our animals.   To schedule an appointment, please complete our online adoption application at www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org 
There are many wonderful pets who find themselves homeless at no fault of their own.  Thank you for considering a rescued companion.  They make some of the best , truly devoted, forever faithful friends.
Medical Information:
When you "Opt to Adopt" your ADOPTION PACKAGE INCLUDES:
-Pet that has been temperament tested
-Neutered or Spayed
-Blood testing for heartworms, ehrlichiosis, lyme and  A Phagocytophilum disease  
-Veterinary General Wellness Exam 
-Vaccinations: Rabies, DaPPl+Lepto, Bordetella, 
-De-worming for hook, round, whip and tape worms
- ID Collar, slip leash and ID tags
-Microchip Placement and ID Tag
-Lifetime Registration of Microchip with Avid microchip company.

Ahimsa Rescue Foundation’s adoption donation varies between $150 and $250 for each pet. Ahimsa Rescue Foundation invests on average $200 per dog on medical, microchip and incidental care.
Special Requirements:

There is a knack to finding a good match for a pet and a family and we pride ourselves on taking time and care in doing that.

animal.description:
Good things can come out of something even as horrible as the coronavirus. Just ask any of our lucky shelter dogs who are being temporarily fostered in the homes of our huge-hearted volunteers. Miss Arabella, for one, is keeping busy and loving life. Here's what her foster mom has to say: 

"She is one smart cookie!!  Fully housebroken and so far not any signs of destructiveness.  When we walk, she is alert to everything that moves (lizards, squirrels) and likes to bird watch. Very strong on leash, but listens when told to go easy. She sits (with wiggles) while I harness her and can give paw if asked. Jumps in your lap and lavishes you with kisses.  Loves her Kong toy and a nylabone.  Also likes to pick up sticks in the yard and bite them into pieces.  She needs exercise as she is very high energy. Would do well with a large fenced yard to play in."

This sweet girl originally came to our shelter after being passed around from home to home. Arabella weighs around 50 pounds, with an estimated birthdate of Nov. 2017. She loves attention and is an indiscriminate kisser ... even the vet gets kisses!

Arabella can jump a 4-foot fence and will bolt through an open door in pursuit of a squirrel/chipmunk/anything that moves, so her home-to-be will need to be diligent. We are currently only accepting applicants with securely fenced yards (sorry, no invisible fences) for Miss Arabella. She will be her best and happiest self as an only-child with an experienced dog family. Please visit www.STAF.org for visiting hours, a downloadable application, and additional information.

•  All of our animals are spayed/neutered and current on shots.
•  We do not do same-day adoptions; we ask that you return for a follow-up visit before taking an animal home.
•  You must be 21 years or older to adopt from STAF.
•  We require a 4-foot-tall physical fence for homes with children under the age of 11. We also may require a physical fence for specific dogs on a case-by-case basis, depending on each dog’s behavior and exercise needs.
•  Due in part to increasing coyote activity/incidents in the area and the difficulty of predicting how a dog will respond to invisible fence training, we can not adopt to homes with invisible fences.
•  We do request vet and personal references.
•  We can facilitate adoptions within a 75-mile radius of our Cincinnati-based shelter.

animal.description:
**Due to the Covid 19 pandemic, our Adoption Team has decided to officially put all adoptions on pause. The health and safety of all involved is of utmost importance. Blind Dog Rescue Alliance prides ourselves in our very careful and thorough screening process of all applicants, and with all the current restrictions in our country, this is just not possible. We would not be able to conduct in-person home visits, a very important part of the process, nor would we be able to provide transport. As applications come in, they will be placed on hold until restrictions are lifted. Once restrictions have been lifted, we will reach out to the potential adopters to see if they are still interested before proceeding. If you have any questions please contact adoption@blinddogrescue.org. We appreciate your understanding during these difficult times.

Moose is being fostered in AL. BDRA will assist with transport within reasonable distance.

What we know about Moose:
*loves people
*housebroken
*playful

What Moose's foster mom has to say about Moose:
Moose is such a pleasant soul to be around! He has the innocence of an angel and the rowdiness of a bull in a china shop! He doesn't meet a stranger (human or animal) and he loves everyone he meets (human and animal!). Because of the damage to his left ear (he cannot hear out of his left ear) and left eye, he tends to list a little to his good (right) side and sometimes doesn't see objects in his left peripheral vision, but he has adjusted well and doesn't miss a beat. Moose can be hard to redirect when he gets excited because he truly can’t hear the commands or see some of the hand signals he may be given.
 He has had no accidents in months and goes outside to potty during the day and to enjoy the sun. He currently spends most of his days outside playing with several other dogs (Shih tzus, Lab mixes, Hounds, Terriers, Chihuahuas, Poodle, and another Pit bull). He sleep in the garage at night on his own bed and/or blanket. He loves life and is a friend to everyone he meets.
BDRA has voted against the use of electrical fencing effective immediately,

animal.description:
Maggie has been kept outside as the surrendering owner has too many dogs to keep indoors.  She's been safe, but her owner wants her to be able to return to being an indoor companion.

On her first night at her foster's, she slept in the bed with the foster's dog. The two dogs acted like they'd always been friends.  Maggie is very good with polite dogs.  She loves her foster family, but is suspicious of strangers.  She was in a foster home with a 6 year old, but their teenage daughter was her favorite.

With a guesstimated birthday in March 2019, Maggie weighs about 45 lb.  We've included a picture of her mom, Willow.  Maggie must have gotten her pretty color from her dad.

Maggie is comfy in a 42" crate so she can sprawl.  She's leash-savvy and enjoys sniff walks.  She's reliably house-trained when kept on a regular schedule.  She doesn't come when called, so care should be taken to keep her from slipping out of the house without her leash on.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience.

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

DUE TO TIME CONSTRAINTS, WE ARE UNABLE TO RESPOND TO EMAILS ASKING QUESTIONS ANSWERED IN THE BIO. ALL DOGS LISTED ARE AVAILABLE.

** Please read the bio in its entirety before emailing with questions or submitting an application**

As we are an all volunteer rescue with limited time to respond to emails, if you email us with questions that have already been answered in the bio, we won't be able to respond. We are being inundated with emails at the moment. Thank you for your understanding!

Bamm-Bamm here, and foster mom said I need to tell you all about me.

I'm 6 years old, have lots of energy and am the sweetest Chihuahua my foster mom has ever met! I love everyone I meet. I'm pretty tall, but only weigh about 6 lbs. Other dog friends would be great to have in my forever home, although not a requirement, as long as they're small like me. Big dogs scare me so I scream when they get too close, and then I frighten them with my screaming. Cats are fine though.

Leashes scare me and I may try to bite you if you attempt to put one on me, so a fenced in yard that's safe for a little guy like me is a must. I'm also finicky about being picked up so I'd prefer to be in a home where the people don't want to carry me. I'm crate trained and don't mind hanging out in there when no one is home. I love, love, love little stuffed animals that are just my size that I can carry around the house.

All of my vet care is done. I had a dental when I became a PawPrints dog, and they got me neutered, up to date on vaccines, and I'm heartworm negative.

If you have specific needs that aren't addressed in the bio (children in the home, small animals, apartment/condo living, etc) please email to ask if the dog is suitable for the environment before submitting an application. Once the application is submitted, please expect someone to email you with questions and/or provide more information about the dog is we are unsure that the dog may be a good fit.

Most importantly, please be honest! We have many people tell us what they think we want to read, not what's truthful. If there are discrepancies, your application will be denied. It's important for us to place dogs in a home that's suitable. You may be a stellar owner but possibly not a good fit for the dog you were first interested in adopting. We're not trying to offend anyone, we're trying to set everyone up for success. We're a best fit rescue and will verify your vet and personal references.

My adoption application can be found at www.pawprintsnky.com.

*6 years old

*Likes small dogs

* Good with cats

* Will not walk on a leash, so he must have a fenced in yard

*Loves everyone but needs a home with no young children, due to his size.

While viewing our available dogs, please understand that:

If you have a fence, it must be a physical fence
We do check persona and veterinary references. All current pets must be up to date on Rabies, spayed or neutered and on heartworm prevention (dogs).
Adopters MUST live within a 2 hour radius of Florence Ky. (sorry, no exceptions)
Please do not ask us to make an exception for you. We give great consideration to the needs of each dog and the basic requirements are based on what we believe to be best for the dog.
Meet and greets are arranged with an approved application which can be found online at pawprintsnky.com
When you send messages/emails through adoption sites, our website, etc they all go to the same inbox. Sending multiple emails/messages to us actually delays our response to you.

animal.description:
Kenzie Ann was a very sick pup when she came to WSRH. She had untreated diabetes which led to diabetic ketoacidosis and acute pancreatitis. Vets and volunteers have worked hard to stabilize her and set her back on path to a normal life. Kenzie will need to stay on a restricted diet and receive insulin injections twice every day. Her untreated diabetes also led to cataracts and so little Kenzie is blind. She still likes to chase squirrels, though, using her hearing and sense of smell to let her know where the little critters are.

Kenzie has been spayed, vaccinated, and microchipped. Her adoption donation is $350 which includes at least a month’s insulin and syringes, 6 months heartworm preventative meds, free microchip registration, and a safety harness.

If you are interested in adopting Kenzie Ann, please review the adoption process and fill out the application on our website: wsrh.com

All dogs are available until “Adoption Pending” is noted next to their names. WSRH DOES NOT HAVE A PUBLIC SHELTER. ALL OF OUR DOGS ARE FOSTERED IN PRIVATE HOMES. Approved adopters only will be invited to meet the dogs.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ FULLY: 
This sweet little lady is looking for a human to be her companion and "caretaker". 
This requires some specific things and an understanding that she cannot give what someone might expect to get from a dog. Her behaviors and interaction with her humans is less than a typical dog. 
Lily would prefer a quieter and less active household.  She does not see or hear well and is cautious when roaming around but does navigate her home well once she knows it. She requires daily eye drops for a condition called Keratitis/Pannus in both eyes. Lily is also on medication for seizures which she has acquired just recently. Her medication keeps it at bay but it does make her a little more sleepy than normal. She does like to go on short walks but is just as happy napping for as many hours as you'll let her. She is 10 to 12 years old and is a Lhasa Apso mix. She is about 15lbs. She is spayed and current on vaccines. She is very sweet and would love a home where she can live out her life as comfortable as possible and have a human that will provide her all the care that she needs.
Please fill out our application at www.clawsadopt.org to receive a call back. Her foster mom is able to describe in detail all that Lily would need and what to expect and what not to expect from her.
(THIS DOG IS ONLY AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION WITHIN 90 MILES OF CLOSTER, NJ)

animal.description:
Chanel is a senior girl, born December 6, 2007. 30 lbs. She looks like a schnauzer/dachshund mix. Understands commands in English and Spanish. She would love a quiet, loving home. She is with us after her longtime owner, an elderly woman, no longer could take care of her. She is leash trained, and okay with other dogs... Not cats and doesn't want her face touched. Maybe after she gets really acquainted with you.... She barks to let you know she needs out or if she needs food/water. Does not like to be picked up. Sleeps on doggie bed in our bedroom by the heater.
She has had a recent dental and has her rabies shot and is spayed. See her video on front patio!
In September, Chanel was filmed by HBO for a show to help rescued dogs get adopted!
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *

Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

All he wanted to do was sniff the ground and stare down the empty cat kennels. He didn't want treats. He didn't seek attention from the volunteers. He just wanted to sniff the ground and walk around. Poor guy needs a home to show him what it is like to be a family member.
May update: Poor Kayden is still struggling with his new life. He is better with people, but unsure of other dogs and hides as much as possible. Can you give Kayden the home he seeks? We were able to see a little more of Kaydens personality this weekend. We had him out for a long time on Saturday in hopes to get to know him a little better. Kayden is strong and persistent. He seems indifferent towards his handler and towards other dogs; however, he was not aggressive towards other dogs. We would recommend slow introductions with non-reactive dogs. We would recommend a home without cats for Kayden.

**Please note this animal is not with AAVA - we are networking for rescue/foster/adopter as the liaison for the shelter Visit AAVArescue.com for more information on how to save a shelter animal. Or contact us at: (337)366-0212 voicemail/text . Email: aavarescue@gmail.com

animal.description:
HAPPY girl Demi is so much fun!! As soon as Demi arrived, she showed us her super fun and adventurous side! She is a real active girl who loves to play, play, PLAY! Gentle games of tug, leaping high in the air for her rope toy, climbing up and over logs in the woods and sprint races through the fence with new friends Finney and Poe are all in a days work for Demi! With all of that time running around, she is still ready for more fun time! 

Demi has shown to be super calm in her kennel.. which tells us that she has a nice inside "chill button."

It's very clear to us that Demi has been abused in her previous home situation. We don't have her history.. but sadly she will often cower or flinch if an object or hand is raised. We believe Demi was born an exuberant, zesty, outgoing doggie but situations and unkind humans have taught her otherwise. We always tell her no one will EVER hurt her again and she is safe from here on out!! Sweet Girl <

Upon meeting someone new Demi is sweet and soft, approaches with caution and she appreciates some space to come and go on her own when meeting people for the first time. Demi is super easy to engage and is a big foodie.. treats and play is the way into Demi's darling heart! So learning to trust a new friend doesn't take much time at all! 

Be sure to check out our website for more photos of delightful DEMI! fortheloveofdogsrescue.org

animal.description:
? Adopt Freddy ? 

Freddy boy here is a 1 yr old pitbull mix with (we suspect) pointer. He is neutered, microchipped, HW negative and up to date on vaccinations and preventatives. He was treated for a broken leg when he was at the shelter, it has healed very nicely! 

Anyone familiar with these breeds knows this equates ENERGY. Freddy is the living embodiment of pure caffeine. He’s not one but TWO double shots of espresso. If Chris Traeger from Parks and Rec were a dog, it’s Freddy. He is happy, sweet, hyper, and LOVES to run. He would be the most excellent buddy for anyone who enjoys running marathons for fun, hiking adventures, or anyone who loves being around another extraordinarily positive being from the moment they open their eyes in the morning until they fall asleep again at night. 10/10, he will encourage you to push 10 more miles on your evening jog, you can do it fren! 

In all seriousness, Freddy is a very high energy guy. He is crate trained, and doing well with being housebroken if kept on a schedule. He really needs someone who is willing to complete training classes with him, because as it stands the energy just flows through him like a windy Oklahoma day during tornado season. He needs a similar sized dog with similar energy to be his best friend and playmate. No young children or small dogs/cats, they will not be able to handle his energy.

We plan to send Freddy through obedience training before he is officially adopted. You can apply to meet him now, though! Www.muttmisfits.com/adoption-application

animal.description: If pictures say a thousand words, it's still not enough to describe this adorable mug, Helios. He came to the shelter with a few marks on his record, but since being here, we have fallen in love with him! Understandably, Helios has a few trust issues, and it will take time getting to know him and earn his tail wags and cuddles, but who ever said dating was all fun and games? Helios loves long walks with his person with an occasional stop to graze on blades of grass. He makes sure to live up to his cow-colored coat! Helios is also super-duper dog social and we think he would love to live with a playful doggie friend! Helios was once a sweet-loving family dog but he needs proper intros to new people, and would do best in a low-traffic home. He enjoys a good game of tug-of-war, is well-behaved when left alone in the home, and he is house trained (although like many shelter dogs, he may need a refresher course)! What more is there to ask for in such a cute, little dude? If you think you're ready to commit for the long haul, email the shelter about Helios and his staff advocates can tell you all about him! Click here to view Helios's paperwork.

animal.description:
Sophie is a 4 year old black/tan female Doberman. She is a sweet and sassy, independent girl. Sophie knows what she wants and is willing to allow you to provide it for her. She is always curious with meeting people because she is looking to see if you have anything edible. She will dart off if strangers try to pet her. 
Sophie has cropped ears but very sadly it appears that her ear crop was a "home job". It is incredibly sad to think about what Sophie went through while someone butchered her ears so it’s no surprise that Sophie has extreme trust issues with people. Sophie came to us from a shelter as a stray. She probably escaped from the horrid people who butchered her ears and had used her as a breeder. She had pressure sores that makes you think she was confined a lot. Thankfully Sophie is not there anymore. 
She is with DAR&E in a foster home where her needs and wants are catered to. Sophie is a very smart, independent lady. She is quite the charming Diva :)  Sophie has been with us for about a year. She has grown to trust us somewhat. She still gets nervous if she thinks she is being trapped or thinks you are trying to grab or subdue her. It took months for her to trust me enough to dry her off after being out in the rain. She is afraid of being confined in a crate or small space. 
Sophie has come to enjoy pets and rubs from us but will still dart off sometimes if she feels uncertain. Sophie enjoys car rides but you have to grab her and put her in the car. She is afraid to walk on a leash. Sophie resists anything that is new and out of her routine. This presents certain challenges but day to day she has her routine and is quite happy. Of course in a new home it would take months for her to get to that point again. 
In addition, Sophie has an extreme oral fixation. If she can chew and swallow something, she will eat it. She is extremely curious about everything and immediately seeks to check to see if it is edible. She will eat anything remotely soft and pliable. Furniture, rugs dog beds, non-durable toys, household items, etc. Her food obsession has been helpful in establishing a routine with her. Sophie is house trained as long as you let her out when she indicates she needs to go. If not, she isn't apt to hold it for long. 
Sophie can be quite snarly toward other dogs. I am not sure she would hurt a dog but she puts up a good show. She really doesn't want dogs near her food so she will be best as an only dog.  Sophie needs a very patient caretaker; one that accepts her on her terms and has the ability to keep her safe from her eating obsession. 
 Here are a couple videos of our dear, sweet Sophie: https://youtu.be/-HahED8NEzU  Sophie playing: https://youtu.be/pbFzeSXLLyQ

DAR&E places dogs in MD, DC, VA and parts of WVA only.  
If you are interested in this pet please follow the link below to read about our adoption process and submit an adoption application.  (copy and paste)  
https://www.dobe.net/adoption/adoption-process/

animal.description: Meet Deacon, he is a lab mix with a great personality uh, dog-anality. He is house trained and leash trained. Deacon can be a jumper and loves to run in his yard, so a 6 ft fenced in yard is a must for this boy. If you want to see pure joy, watch him when he is playing with toys. It goes to a whole new level if the toy has a squeaker, those are his absolute favorite. He does not like taking a bath, having someone hold his feet, or getting his nails cut. He's your typical guys guy - not metrosexual at all. Who needs all that floofy stuff anyway? Deacon is going to do best if he is the only animal in the home. He is not a fan of small dogs or kids, he may chase cats, and he may be too high energy for larger dogs. Deacon was bounced around a bit before he went to his foster home, due to that he can be slow to warm up.. But once you are his person - he desires nothing more than to be by your side and have squeaky toys. Did I mention he loves squeaky toys? He would do best with someone that is home a majority of the time. Deacon is still figuring out the world and will need someone who will be patient with him he can't just be thrown into new situations and expect to thrive. A good example, is those spooky moving doors at PetSmart. He doesn't understand them and we'll be honest, they freak him out a little - but he's learning. Deacon weighs approximately 45 lbs and has been neutered. If you think Deacon would make a good addition to your family, fill out an application at lastdaydogs.com 2/2/21 4:21 PM

animal.description:
***All animals listed on our website are in private foster homes. To arrange a meet and greet with a dog, you MUST fill out the adoption application so that it can be sent to the foster parent for review to determine if your home is a match for the dog. If a dog receives multiple applications, we operate on a best-fit basis, not first come first served.***

**Sophia is currently housed at our center after a tree fell through her foster parents home. She is looking for an adoptive home or a foster home.**

Meet Sophie, a sassy older Jack Russell with the most lovely personality. She may be an oldie, but she's definitely a goody. She has a heart of gold with a sweet temperament to go with it. She loves everyone she meets and has a lot of love to give! 

Sophia likes to go for walks and hardly barks. She loves using the doggy door at her foster home and is in and out all day long. Sophia has taken advantage of the front door being open for too long, and has been known to take her own walk upon occasion. Luckily, she is easy to catch, but any potential adopter should be aware of this risk and take precautions to prevent it from happening! Her foster home currently has a sign up warning all visitors that an escape artist lives there, and has had no issues since. 

Sophia would make a good companion for a retired couple, or for someone that has a lot of time to spend with her. She is sensitive to loud noises, and for this reason is looking for a home with no small children. She would need some kind of yard in which to play and would be beyond excited to have a doggy door to use in her forever home! Sophia does have some early signs of hearing and vision loss, but that has not held her back from enjoying and loving life! She is healthy overall, and still has that lovable spunk about her! 

Sophia is currently taking Proin to keep her from leaking urine and gabapentin to help her old lady discomfort related to degenerative disk disease. She will need to remain on these medications for the rest of her life. This sweet old gal can't wait to find a forever home of her own! 

Sophia is spayed, up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, has been dewormed, and is current on her monthly preventatives. Her adoption fee is $300. For additional questions about Sophia, please email the Dog Program Manager at laura@secondchancenc.org. To adopt Sophia, please go to our website and fill out an adoption application! Thanks!
