animal.description:
***All animals listed on our website are in private foster homes. To arrange a meet and greet with a dog, you MUST fill out the adoption application so that it can be sent to the foster parent for review to determine if your home is a match for the dog. If a dog receives multiple applications, we operate on a best-fit basis, not first come first served.***

*****PLEASE READ BEFORE APPLYING***** *Must have a 6ft physically fenced in yard *Must be an only dog *Adoptive family needs to have experience with German Shepherds *Adoptive family must be local to Raleigh and willing to meet several times before adoption Hi there, my name is Ace! Foster mom said she is really looking for a super special home for me. You see, she rescued me from an overfull shelter when I was about to take the walk. The people at the shelter said that I had deteriorated while I was there, going from a very social guy to moody and only liking one of the staff members and growling at everyone else. Foster mom said she would take a chance on me and I am so glad she did! I was very stressed in the shelter, the confinement mixed with all the noise and smells had me overwhelmed and I wasn't sure how to act since I had never left my previous owners home before. It took me a while to warm up to foster mom but now we are best friends! I would follow her anywhere now that she is one of my people!

 My favorite thing to do is try to knock her down while running between her legs (she's not that tall and all 110+lbs of me definitely has the ability to knock her off balance with my shenanigans). After my rescue, it still took me quite a while to figure out that people are not scary and that I could make all kinds of new friends who would love on me just as much as foster mama. Now, as long as I get a chance to say hello on my terms I make new people friends quite nicely. I still probably wont ever be the kind of dog who just runs up to strangers looking for love though but that is just a part of who I am!

 True to my breed, I am super smart! I already know sit and down but I cannot promise I will hold them long because I am just so excitable over love and attention. Foster mom also says I really could use some work on my leash manners. I am very strong (how could I not be for my size??) and still think that I can dictate where we go. I am getting better though and I know with time and training I could be even better. I need to go to a home where I am the only pet. Foster mom does not trust me around kitties as they look like way too much fun to chase. While I love to run the fence-line with other dogs, she says she still cant quite get a read on how I would do actually living with another dog. I get really talkative and bounce around a lot which could just be playfulness but because of my size and strength foster mom thought it best not to push too far. 

I also require a physical fence in my adoptive home. Foster mom says it is best for me so that I can do all of my private business in peace, off-leash and so that walks can be for training and socialization time. As much as I like foster moms young kids, I am not suited for a home with anyone under 16 years old. That super happy exuberance I have around my people would wind up knocking kids over too much and it just is not a good match for me.

 My adoption fee is $300 which includes my neuter, microchip and registration, vaccinations, deworming, and being started on heartworm and flea/tick preventions. Additional questions about me can be emailed to my foster mom at jones@secondchancenc.org If you feel like you could be that super special family that I am looking for, please apply to adopt me at https://www.secondchancenc.org/adopt-a-pet/dog-adoption-application/?src=sidebar""

animal.description:
***All animals listed on our website are in private foster homes. To arrange a meet and greet with a dog, you MUST fill out the adoption application so that it can be sent to the foster parent for review to determine if your home is a match for the dog. If a dog receives multiple applications, we operate on a best-fit basis, not first come first served.***

**Must have a back yard**Must have another dog**Must foster before adopting due to special needs** My name is Clark! My foster mom tells me I am a very handsome boy. I have eyes that will enchant you with just one glance! But it's very important to know that you can't look into my puppy eyes for too long, or it will scare me. I was feral when I was trapped in a rural county, and I am still a special boy in need of a very understanding, patient, and loving home. If you stare at me too long I will bark at you, to let you know that you are making me nervous. That is because I am brand new to living with a family and I do not trust humans. The good news is, I LOVE OTHER DOGS, so I would be a great companion dog for another dog. Dogs who are new to living in family homes require very special owners. My foster mom says that my forever home will have an owner who is patient. She says that means they will have to let me decide things on my own and try not to force me into too many situations too fast. Owning me as a puppy will not be like owning a regular puppy. You won't be able to show me off to all of your family and friends right away and you especially won't be able to cuddle me right away. It can be hard to resist but I will need a confident owner who puts up boundaries around human interaction until it is clear I am comfortable. I have been in foster care for months, and I have made progress, but I am still a long ways away from being a normal house pet. I may NEVER be a normal house pet, but I hope that someone will love me for who I am. My foster mom also says my new owner will be understanding and attentive. They will need to work hard to understand my triggers for fear and find new approaches to situations. For example, since I am going to be scared of you when you take me home, it will be essential for you to already have a room set up for me that is close to the family but not in a high traffic area. You will need to start gradually exposing me to your presence and building trust that when you come into the room, you aren't going to try and catch me. My foster mom thinks my new owner should be someone who has a routine and is consistent. The key to earning my trust will be building my confidence that you are going to feed me and open the door for me to go outside at around the same time everyday. I will come to depend on you for this, and that will help me come out of shell. Consistency will also help me know early on what is expected of me so I can start to grow into a dog who has confidence in himself. Speaking of potty-ing! You will need a yard for me with a fence that has no gaps in it! Right now I am not able to walk on a leash. That will take extensive work from my new owner if I am ever going to be expected to walk on a leash! That means I have to have a yard in order to explore, get exercise, and learn. This is not a forever issue, but it will not be an easy road to get me on the leash. My foster mom also strongly recommends that the home I go to does not have young children. I do seem to trust kids more than adults, but if a child were to push a boundary the last thing foster mom would want is for me to bite a kid out of fear. To be clear, I have never bitten anyone, but it is better to be cautious and upfront from the get go. It is also beneficial that my new home be more laid back, with few visitors. At least until I am in a better spot. I do love other dogs. It could speed up the trust and learning process if my new home has a well trained dog leader in it. I am likely to follow them on the routine and look to them to understand if I can trust you and the situation. The more I watch a human pet, play, and talk to my dog sibling the more I get interested in getting to know that human. The other dog gives me a sense of safety. I know I sound like a lot of work, and in some ways I am. However, if I find my forever home with an owner who works hard to make us teammates it will be a bond unlike any other. I am neutered, up to date on vaccines, microchipped, and current on my monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives. Since I am special needs, my adoption fee is reduced. If you are interested in learning more about me, please email the Dog Program Manager at laura@secondchancenc.org. If you are interested in our foster to adopt option (HIGHLY RECOMMENDED RATHER THAN OUTRIGHT ADOPTION), please fill out an adoption application using this link: https://www.secondchancenc.org/adopt-a-pet/dog-adoption-application/?src=sidebar.

animal.description:
PHOTOS:  Virtually all of our dogs have online PHOTO ALBUMS through SmugMug with LOTS of additional pictures.  Just copy and paste the link below into your browser (or simply type it in) and then search for the dog's "gallery" by name

          http://adoptasleddog.smugmug.com

VIDEOS:  In addition to photo albums, almost every dog has a video which will give you a much better "feel" for his or her personality.  NOTE:  In the new Petfinder format, it has become quite a bit more difficult to find and to play videos.  Please PAGE THROUGH the photos, looking for a photo overlaid in the center with a "play" arrow inside a circle.  This icon is white, so it can be difficult to see. 
 In many (most) cases, the video is the last photo displayed as you page through.  Just click on that photo and it will play.  Please make sure you CHECK ON THE PETFINDER VIDEO ICON, above, to see a video of this wonderful dog!  Our videos will include, at a minimum, whatever info we had on the dog upon (or shortly after) his/her arrival into our program.  There will sometimes be video updates as well.  And in every case, our Adoptions Coordinator can be emailed at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to answer questions and provide the most current information we have on the dog.  

NOTES:  Please see video or contact our Adoptions Coordinator at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM.

ADOPTION DONATION:  $250  Before adoption, all Northern Lights dogs (regardless of whether Petfinder's symbols appear) are spayed or neutered, microchipped, heartworm negative, fully vaccinated and tested/treated for known parasites.
 
WHAT TO DO IF YOU WANT TO ADOPT THIS DOG:  Email us at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to request an application and get started.  WE DO NOT HAVE AN ONLINE APPLICATION - you will have to request one via email.  We will review your application to determine if there is a good fit between you and/or your family and this dog.  We may suggest another dog or dog(s) if we can offer a better fit in terms of lifestyle, experience, other pets, etc.  A vet check, reference checks, and a home visit will be conducted before an adoption can be considered for approval.  
 
NORTHERN LIGHTS DOES NOT HAVE A PHYSICAL SHELTER.  We are a nonprofit rescue organization comprised of individuals who open their private homes to foster dogs in need of a second chance..  When fosters are not available, we often pay to board a dog until space is available.  New fosters and donations to pay for boarding are always desperately needed us.  Email us at KATYLIED2@AOL.COM if you are interested in donating or for information on fostering.
 
FAQ:  For information regarding our organization, as well as adoption policies and practices, please visit our Petfinder Home Page at WWW.NORTHERNLIGHTS.PETFINDER.COM.
 
 
NOTICE:  In the vast majority of cases, the dogs in our program and rescued from shelters, and Northern Lights has no means by which to collect or verify a dog's history.  We work in concert with our veterinarians, and breed and age estimates are based on a combination of professional input and our collective experience.  Our policy with information acquired prior to acceptance and while the dogs are in our care is that of "full disclosure".  It is our goal to ensure the adopter has all available information to ensure the best possible match between the dog and the adopter(s).  If we have identified a behavioral or health condition while the dog is in our care and custody, every effort will be made to correct it prior to adoption, OR the adopter will be made aware of the issue or condition prior to adoption.  Northern Lights' screening process is designed to identify only those adopters who are willing, and have the means, to treat conditions which may occur after adoption, and the adopter will be contractually responsible for doing so. However, Northern Lights' policy is to accept any adopted dog back into the program, at any time, for any reason.

Maddie is a very smiley girl who likes posing for photos!

Maddie has recently been on an outing through our Lucky Break program (where volunteers take dogs on outings to local parks), the volunteers that took her out had this to say:
     Maddie did well on her outing.  After getting some exercise she calmed down and focused on us.  She loved riding in the car and was very affectionate and licked our faces at every opportunity.  She will sit nicely for a treat.  Her leash manners could use some work.  We'll focus on that next weekend.  She saw some small children and wagged her tail and acted interested in meeting them.  She also saw another dog being walked.  She watched the dog but didn't get over excited or growl.  She warmed up to us quickly and although she may seem aloof at first, we think this is just a symptom of shelter anxiety and she is actually quite social. She was a joy to take out. 
She's a little powerhouse high voltage lithium battery that seems to never need recharging. 

Shelter staff think Maddie is about 5 years old.
___________

ORIGINAL POST: Oreo is a 6-7 year old, 70 pound black lab mix that was picked up in south Georgia as a stray. Although a country boy, his manners are fairly refined as he sits quietly in his room in boarding while all the other dogs bark and jump and protest the confinement. He also has good potty manners and there is never a mess to clean up when they come in the morning to let them out. He loves people but doesnt have much use for other dogs and were hoping that someone will be satisfied to just have one sweet Oreo. That being said, he was out with all of the dogs at adoption day and could have cared less because he had a soft lap to sit in. He will go to a foster this week and we will have more information.

animal.description:
DOB: 12/10. WEIGHT: ~50 lbs
Elsie is an older gal who looks to have been bred many times. She has been tested positive for thyroid. She will need medication for the remainder of her life. She is a real love bug and just wants to please. We are on a mission to help this poor girl find the loving, healthy, happy home she deserves. We need to get a picture of her with her big, pink teddy bear. She loves to carry it around with her and it's adorable. It may be the first real thing she's had to call her own! Does fine around young children.
Update March 4, 2014 - This is what her foster mom has to say about her:
Elsie is house trained, will bust out or destroy any kennel you put her in but luckily she is pretty well behaved in the house as long as there are no drawers or cabinet doors she can get into. Also will clear a kitchen counter really quick. Loves to chew up collars and leashes and an occasional coffee table book. She does better if she has plenty of tennis balls to tear up during the day. She is very pushy and bossy with other dogs. If someone is in the spot she wants, she will sit on them till they move. Likes to hide all the toys under the cushion of the couch so she can come back and get them later. She does not start fights, just likes things her way. No cats or small critters of any kind. Gets along with other dogs. It's amazing they tolerate her behavior.' Well, that's pretty clear!***YOU MUST FILL OUT AN APPLICATION BEFORE WE DO ANY MEET AND GREETS. QUESTIONS? CONTACT pcpoundpuppies1@gmail.com
Our adoption fee is $150 which covers a portion of the dog's vetting costs. The adoption process includes the completion of an application followed by an interview.
Click here to submit an adoption application: https://pcpoundpuppies.webs.com/adoption-application
***IMPORTANT: Due to the effects of COVID-19, our Sunday adoption events at Pet Food Center have been canceled until further notice. If there is a dog you are interested in meeting, be sure to contact us and we may be able to set up a meet and greet as soon as possible.***
You can get in touch with us by email at pcpoundpuppies1@gmail.com or by phone at 812-483-4341 for more information.
We respond to inquiries and adoption applications at our earliest opportunity, but please be patient with us as we work full-time jobs and perform this service as volunteers. We do our best to return messages and schedule adoption interviews within a couple of days of receiving your application.
The fastest way to get the ball rolling is to complete an adoption application for the dog that caught your eye. Thank you for considering the adoption of a shelter dog! 2/2/21 6:06 PM

animal.description:
Canine Castaways believes that there is a home for every dog we rescue and we are willing to wait to find it.   However, every now and then certain dogs have ongoing medical expenses that make adoption more difficult.  These dogs have a very special place in our hearts and still deserve a chance at happiness.  We do not want the fear of vet bills to get in their way so we have established our "Forever Foster" program which pays for their ongoing medical care at our primary vet, Animal Ark of Arcadia.  Our "Forever Foster" dogs are looking for their "human heroes" who are not afraid to open their hearts to show them love.

Currently, all of our "forever fosters" are placed with their "forever foster family".   If you would like to learn more about Speedy, Pepi, Rose, Kristoff or Koda please email CanineCastaways@Hotmail.com.

If you would like to make a donation to help with the "Forever Foster" program or a specific "Forever Foster" dog, simply complete the donation form at https://www.caninecastaways.org/forever-foster-program using Paypal or  mail a check to PO Box 3295, Arcadia, FL   34265.   



If you are interested in becoming a "Forever Foster" home, submit the inquiry form at the bottom of the page and we will get back to you.

animal.description: Meet Mr Twinkle AKA Mr. T... a 40lbs Shiba Inu/Korean Jindo/Thai Hound mix currently being fostered in Seattle.  He was found chained 24/7 to a pole at just 2 months of age with no shelter from the sun or rain in a rural area in Phuket Thailand.  Mr T arrived February and is now 1-1/2 years old.  Due to needed knee repairs and covid his adoption has been delayed.  This silly clever little soul will be an amazing dog with the right confident owner.  Mr T is a dominant alpha and needs a very experienced owner.  Mr. T has the typical personality traits of a Shiba Inu/Jindo; fun, quirky, loyal, great on leash and loves walking, hiking, and playing hide and seek which he is not very good at, so you always win.  Once Mr T trusts you he loves his people!  He will talk to you, do zoomies, and walk between your legs to let you know he is there, and his portfolio of other silly antics come to life.  Pillow stealing is on that list.  Mr T is not suitable for apartment living, children or cats.  Mr T does well with other dogs engaging in play dates and at the dog park but not with dogs living in his permanent space.  Mr T can be toy and food agressive as he has had a bit of a chaotic life and needs a steady, calm, confident owner who knows his breed and know when to correct him and handle his alfa quirks.   This little guy loves to play.  He is going through training which will be completed at the end of October.  Mr T has had such a tough life.  If you think you can give Mr T a lifetime loving home please contact us at dogislooking4you@gmail.com..

animal.description: !!! AVAILABLE for Adoption from Foster Care !!! REX A43851763Personality: Here's a medium dog that would love to just cuddle up with you for a movie marathon! Rex loves taking walks around the neighborhood- even five year olds have to keep their body in shape! He's shy at first, but it only takes a tiny bit of effort, a good home, and a few treats, for him to show how loving he can be!Intake Type: StrayWeight: 52 lbsMedical Observations:(2/21) Patient appears healthy, asides from being underweight and having a low grade heart murmur. Heart murmur does not preclude surgery at the shelter, however recommend adoption with medical waiver indicating heart murmur presence. Behavior Observations:(3/6) Volunteer Note -- Leash biting onsite. He doesn't go up the leash but does do that hard tug as he flips his head back and forth. Once we got moving, he dropped the leash and began walking. For the remainder of our walk he would periodically grab the leash and begin to leash bite, before dropping it voluntarily and continuing to walk. He did this several times, the episodes only lasted 10-15 seconds. So he's not a consistent leash biter but when he is doing it, he tugs hard and puts his weight into it. Returning to kennel he became a bit reactive to passing dogs as we walked through the kennels. No issues returning to kennel.(2/28) Short Term foster -- Rex is a very sweet and gentle dog. He was shy at first, but showed improvement each day by coming out of his shell when he was with me.(2/21) Lifesaving -- Slight hesitation but overall easy to loop. Distracted going back in but no real issues. Pulls on leash and would do best harnessed, but manageable if not. Aroused but allows all over handling. Will come to handler for more pets when stopped. Engages in tag/chase games followed by LOTS of zoomies! Will jump on handler gently. No interest in toys at this time. Suggested Running Team. Noble is a good boy. He is shy at first, and needs someone that is patient and has a gentle demeanor. He warms up quickly after meeting you, and fast becomes very, very playful! He love toys of all varieties, but really goes for the squeaky ones and the ropes that he can haul on. He is good with being in his crate for periods of time; he thinks of it as his safe spot and refuge. He is a playful boy whose ears flap in the breeze when he gets very excited. He bounces like a big puppy - which isn't far off. He's a youngin'! He is protective of his food, which is something we are working on with him while he is under our care. His favorite thing in the world is to play tennis ball, endlessly if possible. Noble was taunted and teased mercilessly by children in his past life, so he is not a fan of them now. He travels well in the front seats of cars. He is confident, a clown, and very intelligent.

In true Scarlett O’Hara fashion, she doesn’t share well with the ladies, but she is wonderful with the boys.   So, this lady needs to be the only female in her forever home.  She was rescued from a shelter, facing certain death.  But, now she is thriving and ready to become a part of your family!


You can complete an adoption application on our website at:  
     www.onceuponatailrescue.com
or
     Scroll down on this page & click "More About Us", & then click "Adoption            Application" underneath our bright Pink logo. 

If you want to meet a pup in person, Once Upon a Tail Rescue does adoption events at PetSmart in Covington, LA on most Saturdays with many of our adoptable dogs there. 

Don't forget to complete your application ahead of time, so you don't miss out on the pup you've connected with.  If pre-approved, you have first priority & can usually take home your new best friend the same day!  

*Please note that there is no obligation to adopt by completing an application.*

**All dogs are required to be fully vetted. Shots, rabies, spay/nueter and microchip.  This is all covered in Adoption fee. Some may still need vetting done due to age, size, breed and health. All vetting will be done by rescues vet clinic.

animal.description:
? Adopt Hercules ? 

Hercules is a 5 yr old neutered pittie who is microchipped and up to date on vaccinations and preventatives, heartworm negative. We are looking for a very special adopter for this guy. He was not well cared for in his previous home and when he was surrendered to a local shelter, he quickly ended up on the euthanasia list. His coat looked horrible and he was missing a ton of hair from being severely infested with fleas. As a result of his poor treatment previously, he has some quirks that make it hard to find the right family for him. In addition to the regular obstacles he will have to overcome being A.) a pitbull and B.) dealing with BBD syndrome (big black dog syndrome) he also needs to find a home with no young children and it would be preferred if there are no other dogs. He gets along well with all the other dogs in his foster home but he doesn’t care to be around them. An older calm dog might work okay. He gets anxiety when leaving the house and insists on being able to to see his human at all times. He is sensitive and he’s not a fan of going to the vet. Hercules is a very loyal dog and will attach himself heavily to one or two people. This dog is for the home bodies. The introverts. The Netflix bingers. He wants a best friend to hang out with and to invest all of his love and energy into forever.

We know his perfect family is out there somewhere, and we also know it will be difficult to find them. So please share Hercules post. The more people that see him the greater his chances of finding his new person.

animal.description:
They call me Leon. I'm a good-looking Redbone with big soulful eyes (so I'm told) who's just looking for someone to love me in a long-term relationship. You see, when I love, I love completely but I need some time to get to know you. Can you give me some of your time? I promise to make it worth your while.

I live at EHR's kennel but one day a week my best friend brings me to his house to hang with him and his family. Those are the best days because I get to run & run & just stretch out my long legs. It just feels so good. And I have a canine buddy who runs & plays with me, too, along with a couple of teenaged boys. I mean, those are the happiest hours of my week. And they've helped me learn good house manners so when you find me - and I sure hope you do - you will be impressed by what a good dog I am.

I'm housetrained and I don't jump up on the furniture - I've even completed a dog obedience class. I have lots of energy and I love to play with toys. I'm a good listener and I'm eager to please - all I want to do is make you happy. I've worked hard to become the dog I am today with a lot of help from my friends.

I hope you'll give me the chance to prove that I'm the right dog for you. Go to www.ehrdogs.org and fill out an application to adopt (or to foster if you'd just like to take things slow with me) and be sure to mention my name - LEON! I'll be waiting at the kennel, patiently, hopefully, for you to find me & bring me home.

animal.description:
Hogan is a super sweet boy and a favorite of our staff and volunteers!! He seems to greet his human friends with a smile and they can't help but smile back when they see that happy face. Hogan is a Black Lab mix around 4 years old that weighs about 45 lbs. He was found in an animal shelter in the rural mountains of Georgia, a place where dogs sat in a windowless room all day, every day, with little human interaction or the feel of real grass beneath their paws. A rescue person saw a photo of Hogan, went to meet him there, and decided this boy needed out of there. He was put on a transport bound for 11th Hour Rescue - he was free at last from his sad existence!

Let me tell you a bit about Hogan - this boy's very favorite thing to do is PLAY! Perhaps that's because he came from a place where he sat alone in a run with nothing to do all day. :( But whether it be Fetch or tug of war, Hogan loves his toys! He's also been to Agility Class with a volunteer friend and he did great on the course! He'll even swim when given the chance! Hogan is a smart boy and knows some basic commands like sit, stay, drop and down. He is housebroken, crate trained, and good with most dogs.

Unfortunately, after being adopted for 8 months, Hogan was recently returned to 11th Hour because he became very protective of his home. We feel that Hogan needs a strong owner who has experience with protective/territorial dogs. Although he was very loving with his family (which included a 13 year old), we feel that Hogan would do best in a home with no children because of his protectiveness. Hogan gets along with most dogs and attended doggie daycare in the past.

If you'd like to meet Hogan for yourself, just fill out a dog adoption application at www.ehrdogs.org and be sure to mention his name - Hogan SCAS! This boy would really like to be back in a home of his own again with people who love him.

animal.description:
Our Diamond girl may look like a plain little black dog but she is anything but ordinary! This little munchkin has a 100 watt smile that can light up a room and brighten your day. Despite having lost her home due to serious illness a while back, she is upbeat and entertaining and a joy to be around.

Diamond loves to explore and it's comical to watch her.whether she's surveying the play yards, or investigating a pile of blankets on the floor. She also loves car rides and walks with her best volunteer pals. But right at the top of her list of favorite things, is getting loved on by her people! If you talk to her and pet her, she will look into your eyes and hang onto your every word. She's such a special little girl.

Diamond has waited far too long for a home to replace the one she lost. She has so much love to give and we want someone to love her in return. She's a nice tidy size, around 35 lbs. and she knows some basic commands. She needs to be the only dog in the house, so if you're looking for one special friend, she may be perfect for you!

Please give Diamond her second chance at finding a home and family. You can fill out an adoption or foster application at www.ehrdogs.org and mention her name.DIAMOND BEAUFORT!!

animal.description:
Freddy came from the basement of a vacant house in Paterson and he was scared and unsure of people when he first arrived to 11th Hour, which made it hard for him to trust. He has come a long way though! After Freddy has met you and knows you don't want to hurt him, you've become a friend to him for life. The ONLY time Freddy has ever made a peep is when he lets out some squeals of excitement when he sees his favorite friends coming to his kennel run. Once he's happily with his humans, Freddy is polite and quiet - content to just enjoy good company. Freddy is a simple man, he enjoys milk-bones meant for tiny puppies, rope toys that have squeaky stuffed animals on them, and is happiest when he's able to roll around on a comfy blanket in the backseat of your car. He's the perfect car companion, always up to take a few selfies, stop for a burger, or even just take a long nap while you enjoy a peaceful sunny day. Freddy loves to cuddle, and will take a seat right on your lap! He doesn't quite realize how muscular he is, so he would do best in a home without children both because we don't want him to knock any small humans over and because he would really thrive in a quieter environment. An ideal family for Freddy would let him be an only child, both human and animal wise, and would preferably be an adult couple, or single person looking for a canine companion. He really enjoys long walks in the park, short walks in the yard, or just some lazy couch-potato style bonding - so no matter your lifestyle, Freddy is happy just to spend time with you.

If you are interested in meeting Freddy please fill out the adoption application for Eleventh Hour Rescue.

animal.description:
Atlas Maverick was adopted from us when he was only 2 months old, but was returned after less than a year in the home because they didn't have the time to train or play with him, and the poor pup was spending more and more time crated. Toward the end of his time there, we don't think he was cared for well at all.

Maverick, as his kennel friends call him, was very scared when he found himself back with EHR. Our staff and volunteers have been working with him, but it is not the same as being in a home. He needs slow introductions to people, because he lost his trust in his humans at such a young age. This boy would need a quiet, adult only house where he can learn to relax. He needs someone who will take it slow and build his trust again. He has not had good experiences with cats or small dogs, but having another canine companion who is well balanced and can be a good influence will help give Maverick the confidence he needs. He must be in a home with another dog.

Maverick is house & crate trained, plus he walks well on a leash. With his friends, he is a young boy who loves to play with toys & a game of "Fetch" if you're up for it. He is smart & knows basic commands. He would do best in a home with people who are active & have dog experience.

Can you be the one to give this big guy the place he needs to feel loved and protected? Give him a chance to show you what kind of dog he can be with the right kind of owner! Please fill out an application today at www.ehrdogs.org & be sure to ask for him by name, ATLAS MAVERICK SCAS!

animal.description:
From Shelby's kennel buddy: Shelby was adopted as a puppy and recently returned after 2 years in her home. The owners say they returned her because of her anxiety and because she chews. That being said, Shelby is a sweet girl who is a bit shy at first but loves people. I have seen her come out of her shell a little more and more with new people since being returned.

Shelby is okay on the leash but could use a little work but all in all she's not a big puller at all.
She LOVES to play fetch with her ball and will bring it back to you (we are working on the dropping of the ball). With other dogs I have seen her be a little hit or miss. She's mostly fine when walking by and with her growing confidence she seems to be doing better and better. As with a lot of the dogs, slow intros work best with her, and an overly rambunctious dog will spark her ire. Calm dogs work better at least for now.

Shelby did live with children in her previous home and did well, but calmer, respectful kids would be best since she is nervous.

Shelby deserves a second chance to find someone to love her & help her be the dog we know she can be. If that person might be you, please fill out an application to adopt her or, if adoption isn't possible, to foster her - please mention her name! She is really struggling at the kennel after having been in a home of her own for 2 years.

animal.description:
Max is a big mush of a dog that enjoys the attention of people and smiles from ear to ear when you talk to him. He loves going for a ride in the car and makes the best co-pilot, ever!! Max the Mush has been at the kennel for almost 8 years on and off! It is truly heartbreaking. Max is soo loving and loyal!! He is great in the car, loves walks, his toys, and is food motivated!

Max is approximately 11.5 years old, but he acts much younger. The high stress environment of the kennel is no place for him to live out the rest of his life. He has not had very many opportunities to interact with other dogs so he would do best in a single pet house unless we could find the perfect match of a doggie sibling. Max has met a volunteer's dog and did well with her; even showing signs of wanting to play. However, he has never lived with one, so that might be too stressful of a change for him. He has not reacted well to cats, so we are firm with the no felines rule.

The ideal home for Max would be quiet without many visitors. He would do best with older, respectful kids as he gives big, rough kisses that may startle or knock over a younger child. Max would also need someone who is willing to take it slowly with him and willing to meet him several times before bringing him home. He is such a gem that continuously gets overlooked. He has so much love to give, we promise you will not need anything else if you have Max. He always has the biggest smile on his face, too. Please consider Max!

If you're willing to take a chance on Max, you will be rewarded with a loyal & trusting friend. Please consider giving Max a home to live out his golden years!

Max won the heart of a family and they have very kindly sponsored Max's adoption fee!!!

animal.description:
When Nancy was diagnosed with glaucoma, she required surgery to remove both eyes. :( Considering she has no sight, she does remarkably well in her special foster home, but EHR would love for her to be in an adults-only foster (or forever) home where her condition could be best managed. She can be a little picky about her doggie friends, but is okay with some dogs. EHR's wish is that someone would take Nancy into their home as foster or forever pup & let her live out the rest of her days knowing love and security with people she trusts.

Nancy is a scruffy little girl with great big ears and a thirst for adventure! She is super easy on leash and loves going for walks and exploring the great outdoors. She also loves playing with her toys. Nancy takes treats gently and knows some basic commands. But like many terriers, she has a strong personality and would do best with an experienced owner.

Here's what one of her kennel buddies said about Nancy: She got in and rode extremely well in the car. On the walk itself, she was initially so excited to be out that she pulled in different directions, but because she is so light it was very easy to manage. She settled down quickly, however, and was great on the leash for the rest of the walk. She loves to stop and smell everything like a typical terrier but kept the pace and walked well.

A special girl like Nancy requires a special kind of adopter. If you feel that you could be that special person who could foster or adopt Nancy, please fill out an application at www.ehrdogs.org and be sure to mention her name.NANCY STEELE!!

animal.description:
Bosco dreams of the day he can leave kennel life behind for good. Sure, he's got some great "kennel buddies" who take him for walks or a dip in the lake. And lying on his bed chewing on an antler helps pass the hours in his kennel run. But that's not the same as having a REAL home.

Bosco previously lived in an apartment complex with a couple who adored him. They said he was a quiet, low key guy who just enjoyed being around them. But Bosco didn't do well with other dogs he met in and around the apartment building & he was returned to us. As a result, we think Bosco would do best in a single family, adult-only home (as the only pet) since he does prefer a quiet lifestyle. A fenced-in yard would be ideal so that Bosco could spend time hanging out on his own property with perhaps a deck for just lying in the sun, something he loves to do.

If you take a chance on Bosco & give him your love, he will return that love many times over - he will be your loyal BFF for all his life. This big scruffy pup is very good on leash and makes a great walking partner. He is well mannered and patient, and knows when he needs to wait quietly at your side. He does well in the car, too, though he does have a tendency to try to wiggle his way into the front seat rather than ride in the back. We usually compromise and he stands somewhere in the middle and leans into me which is fine 'cause he loves his people and is so happy when he gets the chance to get away from the kennel for a while. He's even happier if he happens to come across a pond or a lake while he's out because he enjoys a dip in the water any time of year!

Bosco has been back with us for several years now and it's a shame because he is a good boy that really deserves another chance at a home and family. In the meantime, he is loved dearly by his human friends at the kennel. In addition, Bosco takes treats gently, knows some basic commands and loves chewing on elk antlers (check out the video). And he was so well housebroken when he came back to us that he hated to mess his outside run!

Do you have the right situation for this boy & want to make Bosco's dream of freedom and a REAL home come true? If having one special dog in your life is enough for you, please consider Bosco and fill out a dog adoption application at www.ehrdogs.org

If you can't adopt right now but would like to give Bosco a break from kennel life (he's been back with us 4 long years), please consider fostering him.

animal.description:
Hello there, my name is Petey :) Clearly you can see that I am just a handsome boy! I was taken into Eleventh Hour when my recent owners could no longer care for me. Since coming to EHR I have met many wonderful people. My foster who takes me home says I am housebroken, know all my basic commands (and a few bonus extras)

UPDATE FROM CURRENT HOME:

In the time we have had him Petey has improved his understanding of basic commands (sit, stay, down) as well as learned some new ones. We have been working on "Leave it" and "Drop it" and he has been responding well. We also are able to get him to wait for his food until we give the "OK" and are able to stop him eating with "leave it." We have not noticed any type of food aggression with him, he takes treats very nicely and won't take a treat until we say "OK".

Petey is very good in the crate. When we first got him we tried to leave him in the house all day and he had an accident on the carpet EVERY day. We tried baby gates and barriers and he always jumped them. We figured it was a separation anxiety reaction from him. Since we started using the crate he has not had one accident and comes and goes from it on his own when the door is open. It definitely keeps him calm when we are out of the house. We do have him sleep in it at night as well, but he of course would love to just be in bed with us all night if he could. He is such a snuggler, still very affectionate and just wanting to be by us all the time.

We definitely feel like he needs to be an only dog in a family with no children and who wouldn't have him interact with small animals or children. He definitely needs a lot of attention and love. We think he would love to run around and play in a high fenced yard.
He also now responds to the name Dexter.

Whopper is an active boy with a long life ahead of him. He has suffered from seizures in the past but since going on medication, he has been seizure-free.

Whopper would love to find his forever home with an experienced dog handler in an adults-only home. He has lived with dogs in the past. He is eager to please and will learn quickly.

Please consider making Whopper a part of your family. If you can't adopt, please consider fostering Whopper so that he can enjoy the comforts of a home once again. Please fill out an application at www.ehrdogs.org and mention his name, WHOPPER BAILEY!

animal.breeds_label: Australian Cattle Dog / Blue Heeler Mix
animal.description:
Mirage is an energetic little fellow who loves exploring the outdoors, taking walks and even swimming when given the chance. Basically, anything that affords him the chance to be outside works for him! He is a Australian Cattle dog/Blue Heeler mix, and true to his breed, Mirage is a dog that needs to keep busy in order to be at his best. He is sweet and affectionate, but needs a good amount of exercise before settling in to rest. We'd love to see him have a fenced yard so he can get an adequate amount of outdoor time. He loves to play fetch, or run and play with soccer balls that are nearly as big as he is!!

Mirage was picked up as a stray by a rural animal control. He sat in a crate at the facility for weeks before he was rescued and fully vetted for his trip to 11th Hour. Perhaps that's why he's not a fan of confinement and would do best in a home where his people are around most of the time. He's an absolutely gorgeous dog, but would do best with a strong handler who understands the breed.

Mirage is great in the car, decent on leash and knows some basic commands, but hasn't had much one on one training. He can be reactive around dogs so we think he may be best as the only dog in the house. He is a favorite of our staff and volunteers alike, so if you have the time to give, and are in need of an awesome little buddy, please consider Mirage! Please fill out a Dog Adoption Application at www.ehrdogs.org on this great boy today & be sure to ask for him by name - MIRAGE SCAS.

animal.description:
Meet Topaz! This beautiful Carolina Dog mix has the biggest, cutest, pointy ears. She has a great personality and loves everyone. She would love an owner who is very active and will keep her moving. Because she was a stray for so long and did not have consistent training when she was young, Topaz still has some of her puppy tendencies, such as mouthy play and jumping up. However, she is such a smart girl and so eager to please so with some firm training, these behaviors can be quickly corrected with an experienced owner. Because of this, though, we would not suggest her for families with young children.

Topaz is always up for an adventure and LOVES riding in the car, with her head out the window. She also enjoys learning agility training techniques, such as jumps and tunnels. After her exercise, she likes nothing more than to relax on a soft bed and get belly rubs.

Topaz can be dog selective, so she would need the right match for her to live with another dog but we believe it is possible! Topaz requires a 6 ft wood or vinyl fenced in yard (she can climb chain link) - this is due to her high energy level but more importantly because even after a long walk, she prefers to due her business privately, off leash and away from her people. A generous donor has covered part of her adoption fee! Topaz is spayed, up to date on vaccines and microchipped.

To meet Topaz, please fill out an application at www.ehrdogs.org.

I have spent half my life in the kennel, therefore I need someone who will be patient with me and give me time to earn their trust. I would be happiest in a home with no other pets or young children. I am a typical Akita, which means I am highly energetic and need to be kept busy. I need an owner with large dog experience and someone who understands my breed. I will make a very loyal companion for the right person...I know you are out there!!

If you'd like to meet me, please fill out an adoption application & be sure to mention my name!

animal.description:
Meet Lucky!!! He might not have been so lucky in the past, but we hope he will be lucky in the future. Lucky is a 4 year old Labrador Retriever/Cattle dog mix who was surrendered to a kill shelter because the kids were no longer interested in him and the mother didn't want to pay for someone to watch the dog when they went on vacation!!!

Lucky is amazingly affectionate, eager to please and housebroken. He bonds quickly with his owner and is protective of his both his home and owner, he would make a great watchdog in a quiet household. Should go to home with an experienced, adult dog owner and he must be the only dog in the house. Lucky is very energetic and playful, he should get daily exercise, a fenced in yard would be ideal.

11th Hour Rescue now wants to give this sweet, loving boy the chance to find a family who will love him, appreciate him, and treat him like one of the family. Lucky has undergone training for leash manners and basic obedience.

Lucky is up to date on vaccinations, neutered, and microchipped.

Don't you want to be the one that shows Lucky that he can be part of a loving family? If you're interested in Lucky go to EHRDOGS.ORG and submit an application. Don't forget to ask for LUCKY HAVARD!!!!

Biscuit is extremely smart and bonds quickly with his trusted handler. Once he bonds, he will NEVER take his eyes off of you. He loves car rides and long walks or jogs in the park. Biscuit would do best in a home without a lot of distractions and with someone who will be dedicated to him and keep him on a consistent schedule. If you are interested, please visit www.ehrdogs.org and fill out an application and ask for Biscuit.
